<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Measure of Trade Jumps  </HEADLINE>
By MARI YAMAGUCHI, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- A surge in exports to Asia pushed Japan's broadest
measure of trade 33.3 percent higher in February, the government
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The surplus, measured before adjustment for seasonal factors,
increased to $13.9 billion (1.474 trillion yen) from the same month
last year, the Finance Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
   The larger-than-expected rise followed 12 straight months of
year-on-year declines. A survey of economists by Dow Jones
Newswires had predicted a surplus of $12.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The current account measures trade in merchandise, services,
tourism and investment. It is calculated by determining the
difference between Japan's income from foreign sources against
payments on foreign obligations. It excludes net capital
investment.
</P>
<P>
   Finance Ministry officials attributed February's jump to an
increase in exports, particularly to Asian countries where strong
demand has kept shipments from Japan on the rise since June.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's exports to Asia rose 32.1 percent in February, compared
to a 18 percent decline a year earlier, when the region had not
completely overcome its currency crisis, said Kenichi Habu, a
ministry official. Asia accounts for nearly 40 percent of Japan's
overall exports, he said.
</P>
<P>
   February exports to the United States rose 10.8 percent, while
those to Europe increased 3.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said that more increases in the current account surplus
may be in store. ''Given the strength of exports and stabilization
of oil prices, we may be seeing signs of a bottoming-out process,''
said Peter Morgan, chief economist at HSBC Securities (Japan).
</P>
<P>
   In January, the surplus fell to its lowest level in two years on
a rise in oil prices and the yen's strengthening against the
dollar.
</P>
<P>
   A huge surplus has been a constant source of friction with the
United States and other trading partners. They have been urging
Japan to boost its economy to stimulate imports. Japan is
struggling to emerge from its worst economic downturn in 50 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
