<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Official: PetroChina Plans Layoffs  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING (AP) -- PetroChina Co. reportedly will cut 7,000 jobs
this year to satisfy investors in its new multibillion-dollar
foreign stock issue.
</P>
<P>
   The state-controlled oil company had cut 1 million jobs in
preparation for the public offering that raised almost $3 billion
last week in Hong Kong and New York.
</P>
<P>
   But investors complained the remaining 480,000-member work force
was still too big, a company official, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, told Dow Jones Newswires.
</P>
<P>
   The company agreed to cut jobs gradually, beginning by
eliminating between 5,000 and 7,000 positions this year, the
official said. The person did not say how the jobs would be
eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   Previous cuts involved moving workers to other parts of
PetroChina's parent, state-owned China National Petroleum Co.
</P>
<P>
   Investor concern about the health of PetroChina's operations
forced the company to cut the price of its public offering by
nearly half. The shares, which began trading on the New York Stock
Exchange on Thursday, have since fallen below their offer price of
$16.44, closing Monday at $15.18}, unchanged from Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
