<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Legislative committee votes $550,000 for Attica survivors  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- The widows or other surviving relatives of
the 11 state prison employees killed in the 1971 Attica state
prison riot may be in line for one-time benefits of $50,000 each.
</P>
<P>
   A legislative conference committee Monday voted unanimously that
$550,000 be included in the 2000-01 state budget for the families
of prison employees who died during the September 1971 Attica riot.
</P>
<P>
   Legislators said they are trying to redress an injustice created
following the riot when survivors of dead guards were assured by
state officials that they would be provided for. Those families
said they were not told that by signing death benefit checks, they
were forfeiting their right to sue state officials.
</P>
<P>
   The urgency to help the guards' families was heightened in
February when a federal judge approved a $12 million settlement
with inmates who claimed they were brutalized by guards during the
retaking of Attica after the four-day riot. Of that, $4 million
will go to pay legal fees.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Dale Volker, R-Erie and chairman of the Senate's codes
committee, said the settlement with inmates simplified the question
of whether guards' families should get the special payments.
</P>
<P>
   ''Until the inmate situation was straightened out, there were
many people who felt that we, in effect, shouldn't do this,''
Volker said. ''I didn't agree with that. We could have done this
some years ago, all we had to do was to agree to give to the
inmates also.''
</P>
<P>
   Volker said he and others objected to paying awards to inmates
because, ''We shouldn't, in my opinion, give money to the people
who started a riot.''
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-two inmates and 11 prison employees were killed at
Attica, most died during the shooting by state police officers
during the retaking of the prison ordered by ex-Gov. Nelson
Rockefeller.
</P>
<P>
   The $50,000 would amount to a typical death benefit in 1971,
Volker said. State prison guards then made an average of about
$9,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Volker said legislators are also trying to devise a way to make
the payments exempt from state taxes.
</P>
<P>
   G.B. Smith, a guard who survived being an Attica hostage, said
he does not believe the $50,000 is ''enough compensation'' for the
widows of those guards killed at Attica. In fact, he said he also
did not think $90,000, as Republican state Assemblyman Daniel
Burling of Wyoming County has proposed paying families, is
adequate.
</P>
<P>
   ''Some of the widows, they have been living paycheck to
paycheck,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said the Attica widows and survivors plan to meet this
weekend to discuss death benefits. The group is also seeking an
official apology from the state and for the official files about
the Attica riot to be unsealed.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George Pataki's aides monitored the work of the budget
committee which approved the special Attica payment Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ''The governor supports full and fair compensation for the
families of the guards killed at Attica,'' spokesman Charles
Deister said.
</P>
<P>
   Volker and the co-chairman of the budget committee, Assemblyman
Joseph Lentol, D-Brooklyn, did not disagree that $50,000 -- or even
$90,000 -- is not enough to compensate the families of those killed
at Attica.
</P>
<P>
   ''Of course they're right ... What is enough?'' Volker said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
