<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Leaders say budget process is on track  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Some of the legislative conference
committees may need more time to finish trying to resolve
outstanding issues about the 2000-01 state budget.
</P>
<P>
   The chief committee -- comprised of the top legislative leaders --
is set to expire today, but it can be extended to allow more time
for the resolution of spending questions in the $78 billion budget.
</P>
<P>
   That more time would be needed was suggested by activities
Monday, when the general conference committee did not even meet
because eight of the nine subcommittees had failed to conclude
their portions of negotiations over the new state spending plan.
</P>
<P>
   The current state fiscal year began April 1, and this is the
16th straight year New York's budget will be adopted late.
</P>
<P>
   While the most important discussions about the budget were
continuing to be conducted in private, legislative leaders insisted
Monday their ''public'' conference committees were working.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations over the weekend involving legislative staffers
and, on occasion, Gov. George Pataki's aides, produced agreements
on some of the outstanding issues in the 2000-01 budget.
</P>
<P>
   There were no deals, however, on such major portions of the
spending plan as education, transportation and tax cuts, Senate
Majority Leader Joseph Bruno said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's going really well,'' Bruno said, though he cautioned that
there was always a risk of a ''serious glitch'' developing.
</P>
<P>
   Typical was the report of the chairmen of the health conference
committee, who said staffers had been talking since last Thursday
about how to enhance the state's EPIC prescription drug program for
the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   ''The reason we don't have much to announce -- that's an
exaggeration, the reason we don't have anything to announce -- is
the EPIC program is still under discussion,'' said Assemblyman
Richard Gottfried, a Manhattan Democrat who chairs the Assembly's
Health Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Without negotiators deciding how much more that program will
cost, Gottfried said it did not make sense for the subcommittee to
discuss in earnest spending on other health-related programs.
</P>
<P>
   Asked afterward if such discussions about the prescription drug
program should be in public among members of the subcommittee,
state Sen. Kemp Hannon said it would not be practical.
</P>
<P>
   ''You say, 'Why can't you do it in public?''' said Hannon, a
Long Island Republican who chairs the Senate Health Committee.
''You can say, 'This is what I'd like, that is what I'd like.' But
then what you have to do is you have to go back to the computers
and run it through a spreadsheet which says, 'Presuming 10 percent
participation in Year One up to 30 percent participation in Year
Two.'''
</P>
<P>
   It is not realistic to hold such technical discussions in the
conference committee setting, Hannon said.
</P>
<P>
   A co-chairman of the higher education subcommittee, Democratic
Assemblyman Edward Sullivan of Manhattan, said legislators on the
committee were waiting for staffers to conclude their talks, but
that agreements were close on outstanding issues. They include an
increase to the state's Tuition Assistance Program.
</P>
<P>
   The subcommittee on public protection issues, meantime, finished
its work and voted to send the main conference committees its
recommendations. They included a $550,000 payment for a special
one-time benefit payment to the widows of the 11 prison staffers
killed during the 1971 Attica prison riot and no recommendation for
the new maximum-security state prison Gov. George Pataki wanted to
build.
</P>
<P>
   ''We worked diligently and tirelessly in an effort to come to an
agreement,'' Assemblyman Joseph Lentol, a Brooklyn Democrat, said.
''It was not in an effort to be contentious and to disagree.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
