<HEADLINE> Liberal Party boss says Giuliani to seek Liberal line  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT, AP Political Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- The head of the state's Liberal Party says
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani has told him he will seek the third party's
ballot line to go with the Republican nomination for the Senate
race against Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Liberal Party boss Raymond Harding said Monday that Giuliani
told him that more than three months ago.
</P>
<P>
   The information prompted the chairman of the state Conservative
Party, Michael Long, to say that ''clearly the mayor would be
shutting the door'' to possible Conservative Party backing ''if he
goes to seek the Liberal Party endorsement.''
</P>
<P>
   Long also warned that Liberal Party backing for Giuliani could
wind up hurting Texas Gov. George W. Bush's Republican presidential
candidacy in New York. The Conservative Party is expected to back
Bush's candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   No Republican has won statewide office in New York without
Conservative Party support since 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, no Democrat has won statewide office without Liberal
Party support since the party's founding more than 50 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the Conservative Party has been considered more
critical in statewide elections. It provided the margin of victory
to Republican George Pataki in the 1994 governor's race against
incumbent Democrat Mario Cuomo, who also ran with Liberal Party
backing.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other states, New York allows major party candidates to
also run on minor party lines and the votes are added together to
determine winners. That makes the third party support particularly
important in close elections. Polls have shown the Giuliani-Clinton
contest to be close.
</P>
<P>
   ''This isn't news,'' Giuliani maintained Monday when asked about
Harding's comments. The mayor added: ''I've said this a number of
times -- I want everybody's line.'' Giuliani said that included the
Liberal as well as the Conservative and Independence parties'
lines. The Independence Party is the New York arm of the national
Reform Party.
</P>
<P>
   While the mayor has expressed a desire in the past to have all
the ballot lines he could get, he has repeatedly refused to be
pinned down when asked about which specific ones he would seek.
Long has consistently said that should Giuliani run with Liberal
Party backing, he could forget about the Conservative Party line.
</P>
<P>
   Harding said Monday that the Liberal Party's policy committee
would meet May 6 to interview prospective Senate candidates. He
said Giuliani and Green Party candidate Mark Dunau have already
asked for interviews.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton adviser Harold Ickes said Monday he had just received
the Liberal Party's letter about the interviews. ''It's fair to say
we're going to consider it,'' Ickes said.
</P>
<P>
   Harding, one of Giuliani's main political advisers, said he and
the New York City mayor got together in December and it was at that
time that Giuliani ''said he was requesting me to advise the policy
committee that he would be seeking the Liberal nomination.''
</P>
<P>
   The Liberal Party has backed Giuliani in his mayoral
candidacies.
</P>
<P>
   Long said that because Harding and Giuliani ''are attached at
the hip,'' the mayor ''will get the Liberal Party endorsement'' for
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Long has maintained for months that unless the mayor rejected
Liberal Party support and came out against what critics call
''partial-birth abortion,'' there was no chance of him winning
Conservative Party backing. An abortion rights supporter, the mayor
has refused to support a ban on the abortion procedure.
</P>
<P>
   While some Republican leaders have been working to bring the
Conservative Party and Giuliani together, Long said Monday that the
mayor has been engaging in what ''was clearly a political charade
to keep everyone off guard.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I've been saying all along that this was nothing but a game,''
Long said.
</P>
<P>
   Long said he is going ahead with plans to field a Conservative
Party candidate other than Giuliani, a move that many Democrats and
Republicans believe could hurt the mayor's chances. Long has
refused to identify the possible contenders for the Conservative
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Long said that with the Liberal Party expected to back Democrat
Al Gore's presidential bid, the combination of Gore and Giuliani on
the Liberal line ''is not going to help George W. Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   ''That's what happens when you give an endorsement to a person
who's really not a bona fide Republican,'' Long said, an obvious
rebuke to the state's GOP leadership that is backing Giuliani.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
