<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Opening statements in trial of former Wall Street exec linked toporn star  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY NEUMEISTER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Prosecutors say it was more than just pillow
talk between a married Wall Street executive and an X-rated movie
star three years ago that led to insider trading charges against
both of them.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Alex Young K. Oh told jurors during
opening statements Monday that she will show them thousands of
pages of documents as well as bank, broker and telephone statements
to prove that James McDermott Jr. violated the law repeatedly with
sex-peddling actress Kathryn Gannon.
</P>
<P>
   Gannon is the star of ''Shades of Blonde,'' ''Sins of the
Flesh,'' ''The Passion Potion'' and ''The Violation of Marylin
Star,'' among other movies.
</P>
<P>
   Oh described Gannon only as a ''28-year-old blonde, an
attractive woman who was also a dancer and model'' and sometimes
performed under the stage name Marylin Star.
</P>
<P>
   The sanitized court version of Gannon's career was ordered by
U.S. District Judge Kimba Wood, who rejected government arguments
that her porn job explained why McDermott wanted to impress her
with his stock-knowledge prowess.
</P>
<P>
   The wife of McDermott, the former chief executive officer at
Keefe, Bruyette &AMP; Woods, sat behind him in court as Oh accused the
$4 million-a-year executive of living a dual life between 1997 and
1999 by engaging in the affair while seeming ''to be the master of
his universe.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh said McDermott supplemented Gannon's annual income of between
$50,000 and $100,000 with $80,000 in checks along with secret
information about six companies that allowed her to make large
profits.
</P>
<P>
   Gannon then allegedly gave inside information to another man
with whom she was having an affair, Anthony Pomponio, who made
trades as well. Gannon and Pomponio made $170,000 on the illegal
stock trades over eight months, Oh said.
</P>
<P>
   Pomponio is on trial with McDermott. The United States is
seeking the extradition of Gannon from her Canadian home.
</P>
<P>
   After several references to the affairs the men had with Gannon,
Oh told the jury she was ''not bringing up the extramarital affairs
to humiliate them.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Muller, a lawyer for McDermott, told the jury in his
opening statement that the charges against his client are false
while acknowledging the affair, which he said began in 1996 and has
''humiliated him over time.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It is that relationship that has brought him to this courtroom
today,'' Muller said.
</P>
<P>
   He said his client's innocence would be clear if the jury
scrutinized what McDermott said to Gannon and when he said it.
</P>
<P>
   He predicted the jurors would conclude McDermott recommended to
Gannon companies that were well-known merger candidates because
1997 and 1998 were years when bank stocks were undergoing merger
mania after deregulation by Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Muller said McDermott made the recommendations to Gannon during
''thousands of opportunities, face to face or on the phone,''
before the stocks joined a list at McDermott's company that must be
kept secret.
</P>
<P>
   The defense lawyer revealed how close McDermott had become to
Gannon when he said there were more than 500 telephone calls
between them and more than 300 beeper pages in a single year.
</P>
<P>
   It would be absurd to think McDermott would risk his $4
million-a-year job, his 26-year marriage and his relationship with
his two teen-age daughters to feed Gannon's inside stock tips, on
which she made only $15,000, Muller said.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer noted that McDermott had enough extra cash that he
wrote her checks totaling nearly $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Dunn, a lawyer for Pomponio, said his client did not
belong in court on criminal charges, especially after he revealed
everything he knew to the Securities and Exchange Commission and
volunteered to help the agency.
</P>
<P>
   McDermott, 48, of Briarcliff Manor, Pomponio, 45, of North
Caldwell, N.J., and Gannon, 30, who has a home in Miami, Fla., are
all charged with conspiracy and securities fraud.
</P>
<P>
   McDermott and Pomponio remain free on bail.
</P>
</TEXT>
