<P>
 Tuesday, April 11, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Marines Remains Recovered From Wreckage
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MARANA, Ariz. (AP) -- Military investigators prepared to begin removing the
remains of 19 Marines Tuesday from the charred wreckage of an MV-22 Osprey
aircraft that crashed and burst into flames during a training exercise. Removing
the bodies is expected to take several days, and DNA testing may be necessary to
identify the victims, said Marine Lt. Mark Carter, a spokesman for the Marine
Corps Air Station in Yuma, where the flight originated. Military investigators
spent Monday taking measurements and reviewing pieces of the Osprey, which takes
off and lands like a helicopter but flies like a plane.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
More Vitamins Should Come From Food
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- While Americans should have more vitamins C and E in their
diets than currently recommended, huge doses of these vitamins and other
antioxidants have no proven benefit and may even be harmful, government
researchers said Monday. Antioxidants scavenge the body for roaming oxygen
molecules known as ''free radicals'' suspected of triggering cancer and other
disease. Many people routinely take high doses of vitamin C and other
antioxidants in the belief that they will prevent or cure illnesses. But not
enough evidence exists to support claims that massive doses of antioxidants can
improve health, said researchers from the Institute of Medicine.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Chinese To Lend National Zoo Two New Pandas
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The National Zoo's empty Panda House may once again be
occupied by a pair of the rare animals following an agreement between the
Chinese government and zoo officials. Two top zoo officials returned from China
on Sunday after both sides signed a letter of intent on the arrangements, which
would lend the pandas to the zoo for 10 years, The Washington Post said Tuesday.
Smithsonian Secretary Lawrence M. Small is scheduled to announce the agreement
at a news conference Tuesday morning, the Post said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Thousands Gather for Cuban Boy in Miami
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- Thousands of people gathered Monday night near the home of
Elian Gonzalez's great-uncle, praying for Elian and criticizing federal
officials for their handling of the case. Police closed about 30 city blocks to
traffic. After refusing for months to return Elian to his father, the boy's
great-uncle met with government-appointed psychiatrists Monday to arrange a
transfer that won't traumatize the child. The meeting lasted an hour. Attorney
General Janet Reno had described Monday's meeting as an important step toward
reuniting the 6-year-old boy with his father this week.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Parents Talk Drugs More With Kids
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- A study by the Partnership for a Drug-Free America found
more parents are speaking frankly with their children about drugs, but many of
them fear -- incorrectly -- that the message is not getting through. The survey,
released Monday, found that 57 percent of parents said they have spoken with
their children at least four times in the past year about drug use. Sixty-four
percent said they have ''thoroughly'' covered the topic. A study last year by
the partnership indicated that teen-age approval of marijuana and other drugs
was declining.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Peru's Fujimori Nears Majority
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru (AP) -- Peru's iron-fisted president, Alberto Fujimori, was close
Monday to a majority of votes needed to win a third term without a runoff. But
his main opponent, Alejandro Toledo, rejected the early results, complaining of
election fraud. Toledo, a U.S.-trained economist who had appeared to be headed
toward a second-round showdown with Fujimori, warned he would lead street
protests if he lost. With 55.9 percent of the ballots counted, indicated
Fujimori 49.6 percent to Toledo's 40.6 percent.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
New Mars Images Show Landscape
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. (AP) -- New images from NASA's Mars Global Surveyor show
intricate, frosting-like layers near the south pole that could help scientists
unlock the secrets of the Red Planet's climate history. The layers of dry ice,
water ice and dust most likely formed as Mars' climate changed. Scientists hope
to better understand the forces that shaped the layers by closely studying the
images and comparing them to others taken in the future.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Down in Early Trading
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks slipped at the end of the morning session
following an overnight decline in technology issues on Wall Street. The Nikkei
shed 19.45 points to 20,599.61.
</P>
