<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 01:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CENSUS OFFICIALS: Virginia gets to count Connecticut prisoners  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) -- When it comes to the 2000 census,
Connecticut's loss is Virginia's gain.
</P>
<P>
   That's because the 477 Connecticut prisoners transported in
October and November to Wallens Ridge State Prison in Big Stone
Gap, Va, to ease overcrowding are now officially residents of
Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Connecticut is paying Virginia as much as $11
million per year to house the prisoners, the inmates cannot be
included in Connecticut's census tally.
</P>
<P>
   According to U.S. Census officials, a person is a resident of
the place in which he spends six months or more per year.
</P>
<P>
   When Connecticut's prison count was done last week, the absent
inmates were not added to the rolls. That could cost the state
about $2.8 million a year for the next 10 years, based on per
capita federal payment statistics, The Advocate of Stamford
reported. The federal money goes to schools, road improvements and
social services for disabled, low-income or unemployed people.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut Secretary of the State Susan Bysiewicz said she's
upset that the state will not be able to count the transferred
inmates.
</P>
<P>
   ''To me, it's very frustrating if our state is paying thousands
of dollars to house to house prisoners out of state and we cannot
count them in our own state. ... Federal funds are critical to
Connecticut,'' Bysiewicz told The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   ''When these prisoners finish paying their debt to society, most
likely they will be back in our state and they will be consumers of
all of the services those federal funds will be used for,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Current preliminary projections show that Connecticut is likely
to lose a Congressional seat, census officials have said.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Rocks, head of the Census Bureau's Hartford regional
office, said the reason is not that Connecticut's population is
shrinking -- Connecticut's population has been growing since 1997 --
but that other states have grown faster over a longer period.
</P>
<P>
   Bysiewicz noted that the state also appeared in danger of losing
a seat in 1990, but kept it by a slim margin.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am urging people to fill out their census forms and get them
back ... I don't want people in Connecticut to be discouraged by
the fact that we might lose a seat and then not bother to fill them
out. It's very important that we get the most complete and accurate
count possible.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-11-00 0108 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000411.0015 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 01:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report shows improvements at Long Lane  </HEADLINE>
By ADAM GORLICK, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- A report on the performance of the
state's juvenile detention center finds improvements in the
treatment and behavior of inmates, but problems with security.
</P>
<P>
   The report, paid for by the U.S. Department of Justice, compares
the Long Lane School in Middletown to 31 other juvenile detention
centers across the country. The facilities volunteered for the
study and were graded on 96 points such as safety, security and
programs for residents. The report compares performances in June
1998 and August 1999.
</P>
<P>
   In many areas, including the amount of mental health treatment
residents receive, Long Lane performed better than the average of
the other facilities. It fared worse than the average in areas such
as resident misconduct, attacks on staff, and escapes, although the
school's own numbers in that area improved between reporting
periods.
</P>
<P>
   ''(The report) shows some progress at Long Lane,'' Rep. Robert
Farr, R-West Hartford, said Monday. ''But I think there are still
going to be problems until they move into the new facility.
Hopefully the assaults on staff members will be reduced and the
kids and staff will feel more secure.''
</P>
<P>
   In the summer of 2001, Long Lane will be replaced by a new
state-of-the-art complex, also in Middletown.
</P>
<P>
   The report comes after the Legislature's Program Review and
Investigations Committee has recommended stripping DCF of juvenile
justice responsibilities. Long Lane has been under political and
public scrutiny since a 15-year-old committed suicide in 1998. The
facility, which currently houses about 200 juveniles, also has been
troubled by recidivism and runaways.
</P>
<P>
   While the report shows major misconduct by juveniles was cut
nearly in half, it does not offer specific numbers. There were more
incidents of misconduct at Long Lane than other facilities,
according to the report.
</P>
<P>
   Doug McAvay, Long Lane's assistant superintendent, estimated
there were 438 incidents of misconduct in June 1998. That number
fell to about 234 in August 1999, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've improved significantly,'' said Kristine Ragaglia,
commissioner of the Department of Children and Families which
oversees Long Lane and the state's juvenile justice system. ''It
looks like we've turned a major corner in terms of programming and
mental health services.''
</P>
<P>
   There were about 20 staff injuries resulting from conflicts with
juveniles during August 1999, compared to one a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The number of escapes from Long Lane was down in 1999, but still
above the national average. Ragaglia blames that number on the lack
of solid security systems at the 129-year-old Long Lane School.
</P>
<P>
   ''The new facility will make a big difference for safety and
security,'' Ragaglia said ''We've had more walkaways, but we're one
of few programs that doesn't have multiple locking systems.''
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-seven percent of the 30 Long Lane staff members surveyed
said last August that they fear for their safety. Only 20 percent
said they were afraid in June 1998. An average of 20 percent of
staff members at the other juvenile detention facilities said they
fear for their safety.
</P>
<P>
   David Crowley, a consultant who worked on the report, said the
fear factor has increased because staff members are more engaged
with the residents. New programs require the staff to interact more
with the juveniles, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''As that continues, and they get more education and training,
they'll feel more comfortable and less afraid,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-11-00 0108 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000411.0016 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 01:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Revenue Services trying to track down 12,000 recipients  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- The state is trying to find some 12,000
people who were sent $50 sales tax rebate checks that were returned
by the post office as undeliverable.
</P>
<P>
   The undelivered check total is nearly three times the amount
from the state's first rebate program two years ago, and it
primarily involves Social Security recipients, Department of
Revenue Services spokeswoman Ellen Schneider said.
</P>
<P>
   Some outdated addresses are expected in any program of this
size, Schneider said, noting that about 4,000 of the 1.5 million
income tax rebate checks were returned in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 10,000 of the undelivered checks from last year's program
this time involve Social Security recipients. The names and
addresses of those recipients were given to the state by the
federal government.
</P>
<P>
   The undelivered checks are one of a number of problems in the
1999 rebate program, which also has struggled with faulty
projections of eligible recipients, a funding shortfall, and delays
in receiving address information from federal officials.
</P>
<P>
   The 1999 rebate originally was budgeted to return $108 million
in state surplus funds to 2.16 million taxpayers: 1.86 million
people who filed state income tax returns, 200,000 Connecticut
residents who filed only federal returns, and 100,000 Social
Security recipients.
</P>
<P>
   Checks to most state return filers went out in September, with
the rest due out in late December after address lists were obtained
from the U.S. Social Security Administration.
</P>
<P>
   State tax officials announced the first delay in December,
blaming faulty electronic tape from the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   In early January, before taking administrative leave, tax
Commissioner Eugene Gavin said rebate recipient projections were
way off, and another 220,000 federal filers and Social Security
recipients needed checks, meaning the program required an infusion
of another $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, new federal mailing data was obtained and all of the
remaining checks have been sent out, Schneider said. But many have
come back.
</P>
<P>
   Staffers are researching the returned checks, comparing them
with departmental records to see if errors can be cleared up.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Revenue Services is asking anyone who believes
they should have received a rebate check to call the agency. In the
Hartford area, residents can call (860) 297-5962. Elsewhere in the
state, the call is toll free at (800) 382-9463.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
