<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 01:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Wins Pulitzer For No Gun Ri  </HEADLINE>
By BETH GARDINER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- For nearly 50 years, the story of No Gun Ri went
unreported.
</P>
<P>
   Koreans who said American soldiers had killed hundreds of
civilians in the tiny hamlet in the early days of the Korean War
were rebuffed in Washington and Seoul, their story ignored.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in 1998, newsman Sang-hun Choe of The Associated Press
reported the survivors' allegations and the U.S. military's denial
that the Army unit they blamed was anywhere near No Gun Ri.
Investigative researcher Randy Herschaft quickly found records
discrediting the denial, and AP launched a broader investigation.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the project won the Pulitzer Prize, the news
cooperative's first in the investigative reporting category. Choe,
reporter Martha Mendoza, AP Special Correspondent Charles J. Hanley
and Herschaft spent months digging in U.S. military archives and
interviewing veterans and survivors.
</P>
<P>
   They produced a mountain of evidence to support the Koreans'
charges -- that U.S. soldiers machine-gunned hundreds of civilian
refugees at No Gun Ri in July 1950, including many cowering under a
railroad bridge.
</P>
<P>
   Champagne corks popped and cheers rang out at AP headquarters as
reporters, editors and executives celebrated the prize.
</P>
<P>
   The winners were thrilled, but said their excitement was
tempered by sorrow over the tragedy they discovered.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is great news,'' said Mendoza, 33, speaking by telephone
from Phoenix. But, she added, ''This was a story about people dying
and people's lives being ruined, so that's on my mind at the same
time.''
</P>
<P>
   The Korean villagers said about 400 people were killed at No Gun
Ri, including 100 machine-gunned by U.S. warplanes. The AP cited a
dozen American veterans who confirmed the Koreans' charges,
although their recollections of the number killed varied.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're very proud of the story and of the people whose talent
made it possible,'' said Louis D. Boccardi, AP's president and CEO.
''It was powerful and fair.''
</P>
<P>
   The allegations, which led to stories uncovering other fatal
attacks, would make the Korean killings only the second known case
of large-scale slayings of noncombatants by U.S. ground troops in
the 20th century's major wars. The other was Vietnam's My Lai
massacre, in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   Hanley, 52, who has reported for the AP from more than 70
countries, is on leave writing a book about No Gun Ri. He said he
and his collaborators were grateful their story was recognized.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're very proud,'' he said. ''But our celebration has to be
tempered by the nature of what we confirmed. The greater tributes
today really belong to the U.S. veterans who helped us ... and most
of all to the Korean survivors.''
</P>
<P>
   Mendoza was a national writer with the AP Special Assignment
Team in 1997 and '98 and is now correspondent in San Jose, Calif.
She was recently named a national investigative reporter.
</P>
<P>
   William E. Ahearn, AP vice president and executive editor, said
the prize was a tribute to the reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ''And, since it's the first Pulitzer for investigative reporting
won by AP, it's a tribute to the efforts of so many in the last
decade in particular to instill hard-edged journalism throughout
the ranks,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Herschaft, 39, who joined AP in 1985, said seeing the story win
was ''an exhilarating feeling.'' Choe, 36, speaking by phone from
Korea, said it was great news for the survivors.
</P>
<P>
   ''I thank them for telling their stories to me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks after the first AP story, a follow-up piece reported
that hundreds of other refugees were killed by U.S. forces in other
incidents in the war's first weeks, many when two bridges were
blown up as civilians streamed across.
</P>
<P>
   A later report said American jets repeatedly attacked groups of
Koreans in civilian clothes in 1950 and '51, in some cases killing
hundreds of refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Korean survivors had been telling their story for years, but
their accounts were dismissed by officials in Washington and Seoul.
After the AP report was published and broadcast -- on the news
cooperative's print, television, radio and Internet services -- both
the Pentagon and South Korea opened investigations.
</P>
<P>
   Some survivors are seeking payment and an apology from the U.S.
government.
</P>
<P>
   Managing Editor Jonathan Wolman said the award highlighted AP's
investigative reporting and its ability to disseminate stories in
many media. The award was the 46th Pulitzer Prize the AP has won.
</P>
<P>
   ''The work came from across 10,000 miles, and it's a proud day
for all of us,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The No Gun Ri story has won a number of other prizes: The George
Polk Award for international reporting, the SAIS-Novartis
International Journalism award, a first place National Headliner
Award for coverage of a major news event, a special award for
excellence from the Samsung Press Foundation and a journalist's
award from the Korea Journalists Association.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   http://wire.ap.org/APpackages/nogunri/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-11-00 0125 </TRAILER>
