<HEADLINE> Pulitzer Jury Recommendations  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Finalists for the 2000 Pulitzer Prizes. Pulitzer
juries make up
to three recommendations in each category without listing them in
order of preference. The Pulitzer Board, which awards the prizes,
is not limited to those recommendations in choosing a winner.
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOURNALISM
</P>
<P>
   Public service -- The Washington Post, notably for the work of
Katherine Boo, disclosing neglect and abuse in the city's group
homes for the mentally retarded (winner); the staff of the Chicago
Tribune, for its investigation documenting misconduct among
prosecutors and inequities in death penalty cases; Mark Fazlollah,
Craig R. McCoy, Michael Matza and Clea Benson of The Philadelphia
Inquirer, for investigative series, including an innovative
presentation on the newspaper's Web site, revealing how
Philadelphia police routinely minimized and did not investigate
many sexual assault claims.
</P>
<P>
   Breaking news reporting -- Staff of The Denver Post, for its
coverage of the student massacre at Columbine High School (winner);
staff of The Oregonian, Portland, for coverage of a cargo ship that
ran aground and broke apart and the failed efforts of officials to
contain the damage; staff of The Raleigh (N.C.) News &AMP; Observer for
its coverage of destruction caused by Hurricane Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   Investigative reporting -- Sang-hun Choe, Charles J. Hanley and
Martha Mendoza of The Associated Press, for detailing with
extensive documentation the decades-old secret of how American
soldiers killed hundreds of Korean civilians at No Gun Ri Bridge
early in the Korean War (winner); Kurt Eichenwald and Gina Kolata
of The New York Times, for reporting how pharmaceutical companies
secretly paid doctors to test drugs on patients; Sam Roe, of The
Blade, Toledo, Ohio, for articles citing a 50-year pattern of
misconduct by the American government and the beryllium industry in
the production of metal used in nuclear bombs, which resulted in
death and injury to dozens of workers.
</P>
<P>
   Explanatory reporting -- Eric Newhouse of the Great Falls (Mont.)
Tribune, for his look at alcohol abuse and problems it causes in
the community (winner); Brent Walth and Alex Pulaski, of The
Oregonian, Portland, for series on how politics influences
pesticide regulation; Michael Winerip of The New York Times, for
his profile of a mentally ill man who pushed a woman to her death
before a subway and an overview of deficiencies in the mental
health system.
</P>
<P>
   Beat reporting -- George Dohrmann of the St. Paul (Minn.) Pioneer
Press, for his stories revealing academic fraud in the men's
basketball program at the University of Minnesota (winner); David
Cay Johnston of The New York Times, for his coverage of problems
stemming from the reorganization of the Internal Revenue Service;
and Robert O'Harrow Jr. of The Washington Post, for stories on
threats to personal privacy in an increasingly digital age.
</P>
<P>
   National reporting -- Staff of The Wall Street Journal, for
stories questioning U.S. defense spending and military deployment
in the post-Cold War era (winner); Anne Hull of the St. Petersburg
(Fla.) Times, for her stories on Mexican women who work in North
Carolina crab shacks in pursuit of a better life; David Jackson and
Cornelia Grumman of the Chicago Tribune, for series on the
lucrative side of privatizing jails and foster programs for
troubled youths.
</P>
<P>
   International reporting -- Mark Schoofs of The Village Voice, for
series on the AIDS crisis in Africa (winner); staff of The
Associated Press, for coverage of the Russian attack on Chechnya;
staff of The Washington Post, for coverage of the war in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Feature writing -- J.R. Moehringer of the Los Angeles Times, for
portrait of an isolated river community in Alabama where many
descendants of slaves live and how a proposed ferry could change
their lives (winner); David Finkel of The Washington Post, for his
account of a woman forced to choose between staying with her family
in a Macedonian refugee camp or leaving to marry a man in France;
Hull of the St. Petersburg Times, also a finalist in national
reporting category.
</P>
<P>
   Commentary -- Paul A. Gigot of The Wall Street Journal, for
columns on politics and government (winner); Michael Kelly of The
Washington Post Writers Group, for observations of cultural and
political issues; Colbert I. King of The Washington Post, for
columns on social and urban problems.
</P>
<P>
   Criticism -- Henry Allen of The Washington Post, for writing on
photography (winner); Michael Kimmelman of The New York Times, for
observations on art and artists; Andrew Sarris of The New York
Observer, for film criticism.
</P>
<P>
   Editorial writing -- John C. Bersia of The Orlando (Fla.)
Sentinel for editorials attacking predatory lending practices in
the state (winner); Fred Hiatt of The Washington Post for
editorials on the Kosovo crisis; Philip Kennicott of the St. Louis
Post-Dispatch for a campaign against a proposition that would allow
Missouri residents to carry concealed weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Editorial cartooning -- Joel Pett of the Lexington (Ky.)
Herald-Leader for a portfolio of cartoons (winner); Robert Ariail
of The State, Columbia, S.C.; and Clay Bennett of The Christian
Science Monitor.
</P>
<P>
   Spot news photography -- Staff of the Denver Rocky Mountain News
for photographs taken after the Columbine High School massacre
(winner); Lacy Atkins of the San Francisco Examiner, for photo of
Brandi Chastain after she scored the winning goal in the Women's
World Cup Soccer final; the photo staff of The Seattle Times, for
pictures of rioting that disrupted the World Trade Organization
conference.
</P>
<P>
   Feature photography -- Carol Guzy, Michael Williamson and Lucian
Perkins of The Washington Post, for images depicting the plight of
the Kosovo refugees (winner); Nuri Vallbona and Candace Barbot of
The Miami Herald, for photographs of a neighborhood crippled by
drugs and violence; photo staff of the Worcester (Mass.) Telegram &AMP;
Gazette, for photos of the grief that followed the death of six
firefighters.
</P>
<P>
   ARTS
</P>
<P>
   Fiction -- Jhumpa Lahiri for ''Interpreter of Maladies''
(winner); Ha Jin for ''Waiting''; and Annie Proulx for ''Close
Range: Wyoming Stories.''
</P>
<P>
   Drama -- Donald Margulies for ''Dinner With Friends'' (winner);
Suzan-Lori Parks, ''In The Blood''; August Wilson, ''King Hedley
II.''
</P>
<P>
   History -- David M. Kennedy, ''Freedom From Fear: The American
People in Depression and War, 1929-1945'' (winner); James H.
Merrell, ''Into the American Woods: Negotiators on the Pennsylvania
Frontier''; Kevin Phillips, ''The Cousins' Wars: Religion, Politics
&AMP; the Triumph of Anglo-America.''
</P>
<P>
   Biography -- Stacy Schiff for ''Vera (Mrs. Vladmir Nabokov)''
(winner); Bobbie Ann Mason, ''Clear Springs: A Memoir''; Dava
Sobel, ''Galileo's Daughter: A Historical Memoir of Science, Faith
and Love.''
</P>
<P>
   Poetry -- C.K. Williams, for ''Repair,'' (winner); Rodney Jones,
''Elegy for the Southern Drawl''; Adrienne Rich, ''Midnight
Salvage, Poems 1995-1998.''
</P>
<P>
   General nonfiction -- John W. Dower, ''Embracing Defeat: Japan in
the Wake of World War II'' (winner); Brian Greene, ''The Elegant
Universe: Superstrings, Hidden Dimensions, and the Quest for the
Ultimate Theory''; Scott Weidensaul, ''Living on the Wind: Across
the Hemisphere with Migratory Birds.''
</P>
<P>
   Music -- Lewis Spratlan (libretto by James Maraniss), ''Life Is a
Dream, Opera in Three Acts: Act II, Concert Version,'' (winner);
Donald Martino, ''Serenata Concertante''; and John Zorn, for
''contes de fees.''
</P>
</TEXT>
