<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 02:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judge rules city, Del-Debbio must have trial on how much they payRobinson  </HEADLINE>
By SAMUEL MAULL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Almost six years ago, undercover transit Officer
Desmond Robinson was shot in the back by a police officer.
</P>
<P>
   Now a judge has ruled that the police officer, along with the
city, must go to trial to determine how much they will pay
Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   Both officers have since left their enforcement jobs.
</P>
<P>
   State Supreme Court Justice Kibbie Payne denied a motion by
former police Officer Peter Del-Debbio to reargue whether he is
liable for shooting Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   Del-Debbio, now 40, shot Robinson four times in the back on Aug.
22, 1994, on the E and F subway platform at 53rd Street and
Lexington Avenue. At the time, Robinson had his gun drawn because
he was searching for a gunman in the Manhattan station.
</P>
<P>
   Del-Debbio was convicted in 1996 of second-degree assault and
was sentenced to time served plus five years' probation and 200
hours of community service. He was dismissed from the police
department.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, now 37, is retired on disability. He sued the city and
Del-Debbio for $50 million and asked the court to declare the city
and the former police officer liable for his injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Del-Debbio asked the court to let him relitigate his defense
that Robinson's own conduct caused his injuries. Del-Debbio said
Robinson did not show a police badge or the undercover officers'
color of the day to identify himself nor did he wear a bulletproof
vest.
</P>
<P>
   The city argued that it should not be held automatically liable
because a question exists about whether Del-Debbio was acting
within the scope of his employment and doing his duty as a police
officer when he fired at Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   In his five-page decision released Monday, the judge wrote that
the question of whether Del-Debbio properly used his gun was
decided by the jury that convicted him. The jurors were told to
consider whether Del-Debbio had been justified in firing.
</P>
<P>
   The judge also ruled that the city is responsible for the
consequences of Del-Debbio's acts because he, though off duty, was
''engaged in the execution of a function specifically prescribed by
his employer, defendant city, when he shot Robinson.''
</P>
<P>
   Lorna Goodman, a lawyer for the city, said city officials were
studying the judge's decision and had not decided whether to
appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Del-Debbio's lawyer, Stephen Worth, said he had not seen the
judge's decision and could not comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
