<HEADLINE> Paper: Keyshawn May Talk to Bucs  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- The New York Jets have given wide receiver
Keyshawn Johnson's agent permission to talk with the Tampa Bay
Buccaneers regarding a new contract, The Star-Ledger of Newark
reported Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   If Jerome Stanley and the Bucs can reach an agreement, it is
believed a trade can be worked out by this weekend's NFL draft.
</P>
<P>
   A person familiar with the situation told the newspaper this is
the first time the Jets have given Stanley permission to try to
work out a deal with another team.
</P>
<P>
   No team would trade for Johnson unless first reaching a deal
with him on a contract extension. Johnson, who has two years left
on his original contract, is paid far less than the top receivers
in football. Johnson has asked the Jets to renegotiate, but thus
far, they have refused.
</P>
<P>
   If the Bucs can reach an agreement with Johnson, it is believed
they would send the 13th and 27th picks in Saturday's draft and
either wideout Bert Emanuel or Reidel Anthony to the Jets for the
Pro Bowl wide receiver.
</P>
<P>
   Such a deal would give the Jets four first-round selections as
they currently own the 16th and 18th picks. The Jets could then
decide to keep all four or try to trade some in an attempt to move
up in the draft.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets could not be reached for comment Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson has two years remaining on a contract that will pay him
$2.2 million this season counting incentives. He isn't
participating in the team's offseason conditioning program and is
threatening to be a training camp holdout.
</P>
</TEXT>
