<HEADLINE> Yarnall Pitches Six Strong Innings  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) -- Ed Yarnall pitched six strong innings for
the Columbus Clippers on Monday but got a no-decision at the start
of his bid to return to the New York Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Yarnall, 1-0 with a 3.71 ERA in 17 innings with the Yankees last
season, allowed two runs on three hits in the Clippers' 3-2 victory
over the Charlotte Knights.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think I threw more balls than strikes which is never good
for any pitcher,'' Yarnall said. ''Luckily, they didn't get the big
hit, the big inning. I was able to work my way out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Yarnall was sent to Columbus, the Yankees' Triple-A affiliate,
after allowing 25 runs and 28 hits in 9 1-3 innings during four
spring training appearances.
</P>
<P>
   The 24-year-old left-hander thought he lost a little command on
his pitches Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mechanically I'm not very sound right now. I'm a little
erratic,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Yarnall was acquired from Florida after the Marlins got him from
the New York Mets in the Mike Piazza trade.
</P>
<P>
   ''The big thing for me is to not let guys get on base,'' Yarnall
said. ''I'm not a guy who's going to punch out a lot of guys. I
have to work my breaking ball and spot my fastball.''
</P>
<P>
   Yarnall was 13-4 with a 3.47 ERA with Columbus last season and
was named International League pitcher of the year.
</P>
</TEXT>
