<HEADLINE> Report Says USDA Inspection Lax  </HEADLINE>
By PHILIP BRASHER, AP Farm Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Airline passengers caught sneaking fruit or
other prohibited food into the United States have little to fear
from federal authorities. Fewer than one in every 100 passengers
caught with contraband at Miami's busy airport is fined,
investigators say.
</P>
<P>
   Farmers, scientists and government officials are becoming
increasingly alarmed about insects, bacteria and other agricultural
pests that are getting into the country as a result of booming
international trade and travel.
</P>
<P>
   But a report by the Agriculture Department's inspector general
is critical USDA inspectors' efforts to curb the problem in
Florida, which handles 70 percent of all perishable commodities,
fresh-cut flowers and plants that enter the country by air.
</P>
<P>
   Because violators are fined infrequently, ''there is little
deterrent to prevent individuals arriving at Florida ports from
bringing prohibited agricultural items into the country,'' the
report said.
</P>
<P>
   The investigators also said that cargo ships often were not
inspected for a full day after their arrival at Florida ports,
giving time for flies and other hitchhiking insects to leave the
vessels.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with USDA's Animal and Plant Health Inspection Service
declined comment Monday. The agency is still preparing a formal
response to the inspector general's report, which was completed
last month, a spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   In comments that accompanied the inspector general's report,
USDA officials said they were considering a number of ways to
improve the program's effectiveness.
</P>
<P>
   USDA tried, but then dropped, a pilot program in Miami in which
all airline passengers caught with contraband were given a choice
of paying a fine or watching a video about the potential harm of
imported pests. The inspection service found that it took too much
staff time, said Sue McAuley, a spokeswoman for the agency.
</P>
<P>
   Airline arrivals represent the highest risk for pests getting
into the country, yet more than 80 percent of the passengers
estimated to be carrying prohibited food items are never caught,
according to the inspector general's report.
</P>
<P>
   USDA officials say the fines are too low to be much of a
deterrent -- $50 for failing to declare an item and $100 for
subsequent offenses. Even so, inspectors are reluctant to impose
them even for passengers who won't confess to carrying contraband,
the investigators said.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1998 budget year, an estimated 84,910 passengers
arriving in Miami were caught with prohibited food items that they
had not declared, and 672 were assessed fines, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Some 7.2 million airline passengers and 1.7 million tons of
cargo arrived in Miami from overseas during that period.
</P>
<P>
   The report also criticized the department from failing to assess
fines on cruise-ship passengers. The department said it didn't have
the authority to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: USDA's Inspector General: http://www.usda.gov/oig
</P>
<P>
   Animal and Plant Health Inspection Service:
http://www.aphis.usda.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
