<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Michael Ross says he accepts death sentence  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW LONDON, Conn. (AP) -- In an interview with The Day of New
London, serial killer Michael Ross says he accepts his latest death
sentence and will work to speed up the appeals process.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's been 16 years,'' Ross told The Day in a telephone
interview from death row. ''You know, it's got to end. I can't let
this go another 10 years.''
</P>
<P>
   A Superior Court jury last week recommended six death sentences
for Ross, 40, in the killing of four teen-age girls in rural
eastern Connecticut during the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Ross was originally convicted and sentenced to death in 1987.
But in 1994, the state Supreme Court ordered a new penalty hearing,
ruling the prosecution had withheld some psychiatric evidence from
the defense.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview conducted for The Day by Martha Elliott, a
freelance writer who is working on a book about the case, Ross said
he will not allow his lawyers to file any non-mandatory appeals.
</P>
<P>
   ''I will do everything in my power to accept this verdict of the
jury and to see that there is not a Ross Three,'' he said. ''Of
course, no one will believe that. They'll say its just manipulation
again.''
</P>
<P>
   After Ross is sentenced, there will be an automatic appeal to
the state Supreme Court. The appeal can be limited to sentence
review or can be broader and include allegations of error and
mistakes made during the death-penalty hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Ross said he is looking for a new attorney because he does not
trust the state's public defenders to represent him at that
hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ''They'll file an appeal of error over my objections,'' he said.
''I can't do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Ross said he was disappointed in the jury's verdict, especially
after their deliberations took nine days.
</P>
<P>
   ''I thought they were concerned with the issues of mitigation,
but -- so I was a little surprised,'' he said. ''But when I sat down
and reflected it was like, you know, hey, I sort of respected it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ross also praised his lawyers, Public Defenders Karen Goodrow
and Barry Butler, for their efforts, and thanked the prosecutor,
New London State's Attorney Kevin T. Kane.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think he did a very good and gentlemanly job,'' Ross said.
''I appreciate the sensitivity he showed to the families by not
sensationalizing the aggravation, and I think he should be
commended for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Ross also told The Day that it was difficult each day of the
hearing to face the mother of one of his victims.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was hard, and in fact at some points during the trial I was
unable to look at her,'' he said. ''I am very ashamed of my actions
and what I did to her daughter. I just wish there was something I
could do.''
</P>
<P>
   Ross is due back in court Thursday, when the judge will review
several post-verdict motions and set a sentencing date.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
