<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Critics Launch Boycott  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY MARGASAK, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Advocates of human rights in Myanmar, peace in
Colombia and economic justice here in the nation's capital are
pressing their concerns, taking advantage of daily protests against
the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Washington is awash in demonstrations, teach-ins, concerts and
news conferences, including a planned religious procession today
that was to end at World Bank headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   The economic ''Stations of the Cross'' protest is sponsored by
The Religious Working Group on the World Bank and the International
Monetary Fund. The coalition of about 40 church-affiliated groups
normally conducts its procession on Good Friday.
</P>
<P>
   This year, ''we're taking advantage'' of the weeklong protests
against the two institutions that lend money to poor nations, said
the coalition's Judy Coode. But with an office in Washington and a
regular dialogue with economic policy-makers, ''we're always
here,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Protesters believe that the bank and IMF, which lend money to
poor countries, impose crushing austerity and debt repayment
conditions that make it impossible for those nations to spend money
on social programs.
</P>
<P>
   The religious protesters are not alone in taking advantage of a
week when demonstrators are pouring into Washington.
</P>
<P>
   There's a dinner to promote democracy in Myanmar, also known as
Burma. A rally will oppose military aid to help Colombia fight drug
lords, a protest coinciding with the U.S. visit of Colombian
President Andres Pastrana. And a forum in a poor section of
Washington will explore poverty, health care, racism and employment
in the capital.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, World Bank critics launched a global campaign to boycott
the institution's bonds. Boycott organizers announced their plans
just as environmental demonstrators blocked a street and triggered
a confrontation with police. Seven were arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Demonstrators against policies of the bank and the IMF are
building toward a large rally Sunday, when world finance ministers
are scheduled to meet in downtown Washington. Protesters said they
would try to stop the ministers from entering the bank's
headquarters only a few blocks from the White House.
</P>
<P>
   The anti-bank groups want to persuade labor unions, churches,
brokerage houses, commercial banks, universities, municipalities
and average investors not to buy the bank's bonds, which now enjoy
the highest rating.
</P>
<P>
   ''We want to chip away at their AAA rating,'' said Dr. Kevin
Danaher, director of public education for Global Exchange, a San
Francisco human rights group. He said that while some boycott
organizers want to reform the bank, others want it abolished.
</P>
<P>
   Added Pratap Chatterjee, an environmental commissioner of
Berkeley, Calif: ''We want to break the bank.''
</P>
<P>
   World Bank President James Wolfensohn called the bond boycott
''a misguided effort aimed at the wrong target.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Investors ... are unlikely to be swayed by this campaign,''
Wolfensohn said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In a message to the World Bank staff, he said they should be
proud of the work they do. ''We are leading in many of the areas
people are complaining about, such as the fight against poverty,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, hoping to counter criticism of its operations, the
International Monetary Fund decided Monday to establish an
independent watchdog group.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers welcomed the IMF's action,
saying it ''demonstrates important progress in making the IMF a
more accountable and transparent institution...''
</P>
<P>
   In the past the IMF has relied on self evaluation by its own
departments supplemented by reports commissioned from outside
consultants.
</P>
<P>
   The World Bank supplies loans to fund development projects in
poor countries, and the IMF, its sister institution, responds to
financial crisis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-11-00 0313 </TRAILER>
