<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 03:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Margulies Wins Drama Pulitzer  </HEADLINE>
By HILLEL ITALIE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Academy Award winners know weeks ahead of time
that they might get the big prize. When this year's Pulitzer Prizes
were announced, some winners didn't even realize they were in
serious contention for an award.
</P>
<P>
   ''I had no idea,'' said author Jhumpa Lahiri, who received the
fiction prize Monday for her story collection ''Interpreter of
Maladies.''
</P>
<P>
   There were a few unexpecting -- and unexpected -- winners this
year as voters went mostly for lesser-known artists, including
playwright Donald Margulies. He received the drama prize for his
off-Broadway play ''Dinner With Friends,'' the story of two married
couples and what happens when one decides to divorce.
</P>
<P>
   The 47-year-old Margulies, in Seattle for rehearsals of a new
play, called the drama prize ''a pleasant surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The play emerged out of a particular time in my life, a
mid-life reflection on the pains of fidelity, friendship and sexual
passion,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His competition included past Pulitzer winner August Wilson's
''King Hedley II'' and Suzan-Lori Parks' ''In the Blood.''
</P>
<P>
   With the fiction Pulitzers usually given to veteran novelists,
Lahiri had three good reasons not to expect the prize: She's young
(age 32), a short story writer and ''Interpreter of Maladies'' is
her first book.
</P>
<P>
   A New York resident, Lahiri had spent the weekend in Boston,
where she received the PEN/Hemingway prize for best first fiction.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were actually joking about the Pulitzer Prize yesterday,''
she said, referring to the awards dinner for the PEN/Hemingway. ''A
friend of the family said, 'The Nobel is next.' Ha, ha. And
somebody else said, 'No, no, the Pulitzers come before that.' We
were just laughing about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The favorite for fiction was Ha Jin, who had already gotten the
National Book Award and the PEN/Faulkner prize for his novel
''Waiting.'' Jin and Annie Proulx, winner of the fiction Pulitzer
in 1994, were finalists.
</P>
<P>
   The biography winner, Stacy Schiff, had been thinking more about
the Oscars lately than the Pulitzers. Schiff, cited for ''Vera
(Mrs. Vladimir Nabokov),'' is nine months pregnant and had rooted
for the equally expectant Annette Bening to win for best actress.
</P>
<P>
   ''I wanted to see what her dress looked like, if it looked any
better than what I've been wearing lately,'' said Schiff, whose
book depicts the rare happy literary marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Historian David M. Kennedy and poet C.K. Williams were among the
other winners in arts categories. The Pulitzer for general
nonfiction was awarded to John W. Dower for ''Embracing Defeat:
Japan in the Wake of World War II.'' He earlier won the National
Book Award for the same work and also won the Bancroft prize, an
award for historians.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is astonishing,'' said Dower, 65, a professor of history
at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology. ''I'm going to dance
around with my wife for a few moments.''
</P>
<P>
   The music award went to Lewis Spratlan for his composition,
''Life Is a Dream, Opera in Three Acts: Act II, Concert Version.''
Spratlan composed the opera on a commission from the New Haven
Opera Theater in the 1970s, but the company went out of business
and the opera has never been performed.
</P>
<P>
   He received a commission for a chamber piece for a music group
in Boston, Dinosaur Annex Music Ensemble, and wrote ''Life Is a
Dream'' for a concert version.
</P>
<P>
   ''If, on the strength of the Pulitzer, I'm able to have a
successful production of 'Life Is a Dream,' I would love to write
another opera,'' he said. ''I wouldn't do it on speculation. That's
too much of a heartbreak.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy won the history award for ''Freedom From Fear: The
American People in Depression and War, 1929-45.'' The history
teacher also has written books on the life of Planned Parenthood
founder Margaret Sanger and World War I.
</P>
<P>
   ''I gave up wine for Lent, but I think I'm going to give myself
a dispensation,'' said the 58-year-old Kennedy after receiving word
of his win.
</P>
<P>
   Poetry winner Williams, 63, was teaching a class at Princeton
when he received word of his Pulitzer. The students applauded.
</P>
<P>
   ''They were very happy,'' Williams said. ''I'm a little
speechless. It feels nice.''
</P>
<P>
   The awards will be presented May 22.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On The Net: http://www.pulitzer.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
