<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stock Prices Close Lower  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks closed moderately lower Tuesday, with
high-technology issues pulling down the market. The U.S. dollar was
higher against the yen.
</P>
<P>
   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average fell 96.54 points,
or 0.47 percent, to close at 20,522.52 points on the Tokyo Stock
Exchange. On Monday, the average closed up 366.25 points, or 1.81
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar was trading at 106.70 yen on the Tokyo foreign
exchange market at 3 p.m. (0600 GMT) Tuesday, up 0.64 yen from late
Monday in Tokyo and above its late New York level of 106.47 yen
overnight.
</P>
<P>
   On the stock market, technology stocks pulled the market down
after sharp losses on the U.S. Nasdaq market Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, the Nasdaq composite index fell 258.25 to 4,188.20,
its second largest point drop. The Dow Jones industrial average
rose 75.08 to 11,186.56 at Monday's close.
</P>
<P>
   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the
first section fell 15.65 points, or 0.92 percent, to close at
1,701.09. The TOPIX closed up 39.12 points, or 2.33 percent, on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In currency dealings, the dollar moved slightly higher in light
trading as investors grew cautious ahead of a weekend meeting of
Group of Seven finance officials.
</P>
<P>
   Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa said Tuesday he will tell G-7
counterparts that Japan's stance on foreign exchange is unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   ''You have seen for yourselves what we do when we feel that a
rapid strengthening of the yen is problematic,'' Miyazawa said at a
regular news conference, referring to dollar-buying intervention in
currency markets by the Bank of Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials have said the yen's rapid rise against the
greenback could hurt Japan's unstable economic recovery by making
exports more expensive abroad, and cutting into the earnings of
export-led companies.
</P>
<P>
   Finance ministers and central bankers from the G-7 -- the United
States, Japan, Britain, France, Italy, Canada and Germany -- will
gather in Washington this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   In other currencies, the euro was traded at 102.76 yen, up from
101.50 yen late Monday in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond rose
to 1.7400 percent from Monday's finish of 1.7350 percent. Its price
fell 0.04 point to 101.38.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-11-00 0332 </TRAILER>
