<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 03:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Republicans To Honor House Chaplain  </HEADLINE>
By JENNIFER LOVEN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The national Republican Party's events today
honoring the House's first Catholic chaplain are raising some
eyebrows on Capitol Hill, particularly among Democrats who say the
party appears to be seeking to score points with an influential,
but bruised block of voters.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Daniel P. Coughlin's appointment as chaplain last month
came after a protracted battle during which some Democrats accused
GOP leaders of being anti-Catholic because they first chose a
Presbyterian minister for the post.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're glad that Republican leaders finally welcomed a Catholic
chaplain into the United States Congress,'' Jenny Backus,
spokeswoman for the Democratic National Committee, said Monday.
''However, the best way for Republicans to try and woo the Catholic
vote is to abandon what appears to be a patently obvious political
ploy and start passing programs.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republican National Committee invited members of Congress
and the media to a late afternoon Mass at a church near the Capitol
at which the Chicago priest will be one of the celebrants and will
deliver the homily. The RNC also is hosting a reception afterward,
and is billing the appearances as Coughlin's first since taking the
job.
</P>
<P>
   RNC spokesman Chris Paulitz insisted the event was only intended
to introduce Coughlin to those he will be counseling, with all
House members -- both Democratic and Republican -- invited.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a completely apolitical event. ... There is not going
to be any effort to score political points with anyone,'' Paulitz
said. ''If some people want to play games with this, I'm sorry.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for House Speaker Dennis Hastert said the Illinois
Republican is planning his own reception for Coughlin to meet
lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   ''Father Coughlin is someone who is going to serve the House in
a non-partisan way,'' John Feehery said. ''Partisan politics should
be taken out of this job.''
</P>
<P>
   Hastert and other Republican leaders came under fire late last
year when they announced the selection of the Rev. Charles Wright
for the chaplain job. Democrats insisted that a Catholic priest,
the Rev. Timothy O'Brien, was the top choice of a bipartisan
selection committee and accused the GOP leadership of anti-Catholic
bias.
</P>
<P>
   The speaker vehemently denied the characterization.
</P>
<P>
   But as the controversy lingered through the winter, Republicans
worried they were losing ground with Catholic voters, who account
for 25 percent or more of the turnout in national elections and a
higher percentage in some key states.
</P>
<P>
   Wright eventually withdrew and Hastert unexpectedly appointed
Coughlin.
</P>
<P>
   In an unusually pointed speech at the time, Hastert blamed
Democrats for ''maliciously seeking political advantage by making
these accusations.''
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, the RNC has issued a steady stream of statements
suggesting Democrats favor revoking the Vatican's permanent
observer status at the United Nations. RNC Chairman Jim Nicholson
and former Vatican Ambassador Thomas P. Melady, both Catholic
Republicans involved in that effort, are listed as hosts for the
Coughlin event.
</P>
<P>
   Coughlin, a 40-year veteran of the Chicago Archdiocese, was most
recently a vicar to its parish priests. His duties in the
$138,000-a-year chaplain job include opening each day's House
session with prayer and ministering to House members and their
families.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-11-00 0341 </TRAILER>
