<DOCNO> APW20000411.0074 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 04:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Group Seeks Inquiry of First Lady  </HEADLINE>
By PEGGY HARRIS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- First lady Hillary Rodham Clinton's
actions in the Whitewater venture have now come under scrutiny of
the Arkansas Supreme Court's disciplinary arm, which is already
considering a complaint seeking to disbar President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to a conservative group last week, the executive
director of the court's committee on professional conduct said the
panel is reviewing the group's allegation that Mrs. Clinton may
have violated the Arkansas code of conduct requiring lawyers to act
with honesty and integrity.
</P>
<P>
   Executive director James Neal said he would evaluate information
from federal regulators that Mrs. Clinton, as a lawyer in Little
Rock, created a real estate document later used by her Whitewater
partners' savings and loan to deceive federal regulators.
</P>
<P>
   The document helped enable the payment of $300,000 in real
estate commissions to the father-in-law of Mrs. Clinton's former
law partner, Webster Hubbell.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton says she recalls nothing about the matter.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, her lawyer, David Kendall, called the Landmark Legal
Foundation's complaint ridiculous and ''partisan nonsense.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Anyone with a 33-cent stamp can file a complaint,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The group filed the complaint against Mrs. Clinton in 1996, but
said it never got a response.
</P>
<P>
   In his letter, Neal said he thought he had reviewed the matter
earlier but he was unable to find a copy of his response.
</P>
<P>
   ''Therefore, this office will again review and evaluate the
information provided in your earlier correspondence,'' Neal wrote.
</P>
<P>
   All complaints to Neal's office are handled with an initial
review by the executive director, who has the authority to reject
them.
</P>
<P>
   The Landmark Legal Foundation's complaint was based on a report
by the inspector general of the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp.
focusing on the actions of Mrs. Clinton for the S&AMP;L owned by her
Whitewater partners, Jim and Susan McDougal.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, the committee is giving the president until April 21
to respond to a request that he be disbarred for allegedly lying in
the Monica Lewinsky scandal.
</P>
<P>
   The Arkansas Supreme Court in January ordered the committee to
take up long-standing complaints against the president, including
one arising from a federal judge holding Clinton in civil contempt
of court for giving misleading testimony regarding Lewinsky in the
Paula Jones sexual harassment lawsuit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-11-00 0418 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000411.0075 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 04:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Remains of Marines To Be Removed  </HEADLINE>
By MICHELLE RUSHLO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARANA, Ariz. (AP) -- Military investigators prepared for the
painstaking process of removing the remains of 19 Marines who died
in a fiery crash of an MV-22 Osprey aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   Officials spent Monday taking measurements, examining pieces of
the charred wreck and trying to ensure that investigators could
remove the remains safely, said Lt. Mark Carter, a spokesman for
the Marine Corps Air Station in Yuma, where the flight originated.
</P>
<P>
   Recovery of the remains was expected to begin today.
Investigators said identification will likely take several days and
involve DNA, fingerprints and other records.
</P>
<P>
   ''The process is a slow process because it's a detailed
operation,'' Carter said.
</P>
<P>
   The Osprey crashed Saturday during an evacuation training
exercise at Marana Northwest Regional Airport, about 30 miles
northwest of Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   The victims included four crew members from Quantico, Va., 14
Marines from Camp Pendleton, Calif., and one from Marine Corps Air
Station-Miramar in San Diego County.
</P>
<P>
   Capt. Aisha Bakkar-Poe, a spokeswoman at the Pentagon Marine
Corps headquarters, said Monday a preliminary cause for the crash
could be released in the next week or two.
</P>
<P>
   She said the corps remains confident the innovative Osprey,
which Marines are evaluating under war-type conditions, is safe. It
is expected to replace an aging fleet of CH-46 Sea Knight
helicopters.
</P>
<P>
   Ospreys, designed for cargo and personnel transport, take off
and land like helicopters and fly like planes.
</P>
<P>
   The Marines are not flying their other four MV-22 Ospreys, but
Bakkar-Poe said that mostly was out of respect for the victims'
families and the other Osprey crews.
</P>
<P>
   ''We really don't feel there's a design flaw,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She said the Osprey that crashed had flown more than 135 hours
since it was delivered to the corps on Jan. 17. The aircraft had
been averaging 40 hours a month in the air -- about twice as much as
most Marine aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   The extra flight time should not have been a factor in the
crash, however, Bakkar-Poe said.
</P>
<P>
   The Osprey was introduced in September. The Marines have ordered
360 of them to be delivered by 2014 at a cost of $44 million each,
said Pentagon spokesman Capt. Rob Winchester.
</P>
<P>
   The mother of one of the victims, Keoki Santos, 24, of Grand
Ronde, Ore., said her son had concerns about riding in the Osprey.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was really, really nervous about the whole thing,''
Christina Mercier said. ''He was a beautiful, high-spirited, true
Marine. He didn't want to just go into the service for four years.
He enlisted to be a career man. And they killed him. They wanted
him to be a guinea pig for these new airplanes.''
</P>
<P>
   The Marine Corps lists two other crashes during the Osprey's
development: A 1991 Delaware accident blamed on gyro wiring
problems, and a 1992 Virginia crash that killed all seven people on
board after an engine caught fire.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Camp Pendleton:
http://www.cpp.usmc.mil/jpao/home.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
