<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 04:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Women's Soccer League Launched  </HEADLINE>
By BARRY WILNER, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The Women's World Cup champions are in total
support of the Women's United Soccer Association.
</P>
<P>
   All 20 members of the U.S. national team that captivated the
country in winning the world title last year have signed letters of
intent to play in the WUSA.
</P>
<P>
   The league plans to begin next April with eight teams and a
total of 80 games.
</P>
<P>
   ''We know they are committed to women in the WUSA,'' team
co-captain Carla Overbeck said Monday. ''If we are with another
league, which we are hoping will not happen, that would not be the
focus. This group of investors was excited about the World Cup and
the success we had, and jumped in very quickly when approached
about starting a women's professional league. We are looking
forward, and we're excited about their excitement for us.''
</P>
<P>
   The WUSA approved eight cities: Atlanta, Boston, New York,
Philadelphia, Orlando-Tampa, San Diego, San Francisco and
Washington. Listed as alternates were Chicago, Columbus, Detroit,
Los Angeles, Miami, Portland, Raleigh-Durham and St. Louis. Any of
those cities might be selected if one of the original eight drops
out. Also under consideration are Milwaukee, Denver and Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The keys to success are signing the best players and hooking up
with television.
</P>
<P>
   The WUSA has letters of intent from the top Americans, plus such
international stars as Sissi of Brazil, Charmaine Hooper of Canada,
Julie Murray of Australia and Patience Avre of Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
   Star players would be spread among the eight teams, meaning at
least a half-dozen would be on the field for each game.
</P>
<P>
   Turner Broadcasting reached a four-year agreement with the WUSA
to televise games on TNT and CNN/SI, mostly on weekend afternoons.
</P>
<P>
   With such major communications outfits as Time-Warner, Comcast
and Cox owning teams, the WUSA has deep pockets, too.
</P>
<P>
   ''The key is this group is passionate about soccer and they will
benefit soccer,'' said Tony DiCicco, who coached the U.S. World Cup
squad and is now a consultant to the new league. ''We are going to
enhance soccer. The truth is, the resources of this investor group
are something I have been waiting for my entire life and it only
makes sense for the growth of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Soccer Federation set a May 1 deadline to submit
business plans. The WUSA already has done so, and Major League
Soccer also will submit a plan.
</P>
<P>
   ''The official U.S. Soccer standards require each team with a
minimum salary level of $400,000,'' said John Hendricks, chairman
of the board for the WUSA and chairman and CEO of Discovery
Communications. ''From the investor side, to get the absolute top
players involved, we needed to double that budget.
</P>
<P>
   ''The soccer federation has a standard for guaranteed funding
for a minimum of three years. We wanted to go longer and we have
lined up funding for a full six years: a development year as well
as five years of league play.''
</P>
<P>
   Each of the initial eight markets required a $5 million
investment.
</P>
<P>
   MLS contacted last December about combining efforts. In turn,
WUSA has given a cooperation proposal to the men's league, now in
its fifth year.
</P>
<P>
   ''We believe we can achieve far more working together than
alone,'' MLS commissioner Don Garber said. ''A combined effort
would help us position ourselves vs. the other sports as opposed to
cannibalizing on the support of either leagues. Collectively, we
would ensure the women's viability, which is important to us.''
</P>
<P>
   But neither side envisions the other as the controlling entity
in such an arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   ''You need an investment group solely behind the women's game as
its main priority,'' Hendricks said. ''The MLS focus is on the men,
the WUSA on the women and it provides a chance to build the sport
of soccer throughout the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   WUSA envisions stadiums with capacities of 6,500 to 10,000, far
smaller than MLS sites. It might not find those venues immediately,
and could temporarily emulate the MLS, which has many teams playing
in NFL stadiums.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of where they play, the U.S. women believe the
phenomenon that was the 1999 World Cup has a carryover effect. That
carryover is manifested in the creation of the WUSA.
</P>
<P>
   ''With all the resources these companies have and all the
promotion you can have, we feel you need that directed focus and
energy that is solely behind the women's game,'' said Julie Foudy,
the other co-captain of the '99 U.S. team. ''We are totally
committed to playing for just the WUSA and hoping that is the
league that gets sanctioned.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
