<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 04:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Museum IDs Allegedly Stolen Art  </HEADLINE>
By CATHERINE IVEY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON (AP) -- ''Portrait of a Man and Woman in an Interior,'' a
centuries-old painting by Dutch artist Eglon van der Neer, has hung
in the Museum of Fine Arts for nearly six decades.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the Boston museum said that the painting, along with
six other European pieces of art it owns, may have been plundered
from their rightful owners by the Nazis during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   The museum has posted photographs of the paintings on its Web
site in hopes the public will help fill in the blanks of their
ownership history to help determine if they indeed represent looted
art.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are offering worldwide access to these paintings and hope
that others with information on their histories will come
forward,'' said Malcolm Rogers, the museum's director. ''Filling
the gaps in the provenance of these paintings could assist in the
identification and restitution of works that may have been looted
during the Holocaust and World War II.''
</P>
<P>
   The museum is the latest to publicly identify art possibly
stolen by Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   The National Museum Directors' Conference in Britain placed 350
questionable paintings on the Internet last month. On Monday, the
German government posted online its Lost Art Internet Database -- a
listing of 2,200 objects that may have been taken during World War
II.
</P>
<P>
   Three other major museums -- the J. Paul Getty Museum in Los
Angeles, the Chicago Art Institute and the Metropolitan Museum of
Art in New York City -- soon are expected to follow suit and
identify questionable paintings in their collections.
</P>
<P>
   The photographs of the paintings are accompanied on the museum's
Web site by the most recent research on their past. Museum
officials said although gaps in a piece's history are common, these
particular paintings raised questions because of when or where they
were obtained, or because of their previous owners were implicated
in looting art.
</P>
<P>
   The van der Neer work, for example, was in Paris until 1845 when
it was sold to a Brussels collector. In 1861 it returned to France
through its sale to a Parisian.
</P>
<P>
   After that, its history becomes murky.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers at the Museum of Fine Arts say a man named Robert
Lebel reported selling the painting to German collector Walter
Westfeld around 1937. Lebel said the German government arrested
Westfeld in 1938 and that his property was seized and sold through
the government.
</P>
<P>
   From there, records show only that it was owned by an American,
A. Silberman, in 1941. Silberman told the museum it was brought to
the United States by ''a refugee some time ago,'' but gave no
further information. The museum purchased the painting from
Silberman that same year.
</P>
<P>
   Museum officials said they could not be certain it wasn't seized
and sold by the Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   The World Jewish Congress, which has worked for the return of
Holocaust victims' assets from banks, insurers and art museums,
welcomed the posting of the paintings on the Web. But the group
said that was only a first step.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're pleased that the museum is taking its responsibility
seriously,'' said Elan Steinberg, the group's executive director.
''Now I think it is a matter of public obligation of the museum to
determine if the art belongs to someone else or to demonstrate
unequivocally that the museum has clear title.''
</P>
<P>
   The World Jewish Congress estimates that of the country's 750
art museums, 200 might hold questionable art.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Museum of Fine Arts site on painting's histories:
</P>
<P>
   www.mfa.org/research/list.htm
</P>
<P>
   The Lost Art Internet Database: www.lostart.de
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
