<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel's Sharansky Visits Ethiopia  </HEADLINE>
By SARI BASHI, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) -- Dressed in his finest -- a shiny
gray suit and tie -- 8-year-old Mulukan Alemu today proudly shook
hands with Israeli Interior Minister Natan Sharanky.
</P>
<P>
   After two years in an Addis Ababa transit camp, the boy and 21
relatives were given permission to move to Israel because his
grandfather has completed the lengthy process of converting to
Judaism, making the entire family eligible for Israeli citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   ''Now you are an Israeli citizen,'' Sharansky told Mulukan
during a meeting in a small briefing room at the Israeli embassy in
the Ethiopian capital.
</P>
<P>
   The Alemus, who were set to fly to Israel, are Falash Mura,
Ethiopian Jews who converted to Christianity. In all, about 26,000
Falash Mura are waiting to immigrate to Israel, including 18,000
who left their homes and are living in small mud huts surrounding
transit compounds in Addis Ababa and the northern city of Gondar.
</P>
<P>
   Sharansky toured the camps this week, but has told the Falash
Mura that not everyone would be brought to Israel to avoid setting
a precedent that would flood Israel with immigration requests on
hardship grounds.
</P>
<P>
   ''Suffering doesn't make someone Jewish,'' Sharansky said.
</P>
<P>
   Lobbyists for the community accused Sharansky of discriminating
against the Falash Mura while approving the immigration of hundreds
of thousands of non-Jews from the former Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   During a tour of the Addis Ababa compound Monday, Falash Mura
showed Sharansky their commitment to Judaism. Women, who have
crosses tattooed on their foreheads as is customary in Ethiopian
villages, baked matzah, unleavened bread used for the Jewish
holiday of Passover, over an open fire, while children sang Hebrew
songs and knitted ritual prayer fringes.
</P>
<P>
   Sharansky, wearing his trademark khaki cap and sneakers, visited
rickety shacks where children sat on wooden benches, studying
Hebrew.
</P>
<P>
   ''Why did you come here?'' he asked 15-year-old Fakato Tarke.
</P>
<P>
   ''To join my father in Israel,'' Tarke replied, telling
Sharansky in broken Hebrew that he has been waiting for two years.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Goldman, one of the compound organizers, said Israel was
deliberately stonewalling the Falash Mura because they are ''poor
and black.''
</P>
<P>
   Their absorption costs Israel a lot of money in stipends and
social services, and many Israelis oppose the immigration of a
group they consider to be non-Jewish.
</P>
<P>
   Shlomo Mula, an immigration official responsible for settling
Ethiopian Jews in Israel, said that race had nothing to do with it.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Falash Mura decided to be Jewish 10 years ago, when they
saw Ethiopian Jews coming to Israel,'' said Mula, who made the
dangerous trek from Ethiopia to the Sudan 15 years ago to reach
Israel.
</P>
<P>
   But expectations of reaching Israel have created irreversible
migration.
</P>
<P>
   Yenesewbeza Bitewa left her house and farmland in northern
Ethiopia two years ago, at the request of her married daughter, who
immigrated to Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ''We can't go back, because our land has been taken by the
people in the village,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-11-00 0524 </TRAILER>
