<HEADLINE> Baseball Today  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressSCOREBOARD:
Tuesday, April 11:
<TEXT>
<P>
   Los Angeles at San Francisco (4:05 p.m. EDT). The Giants'
brand-new ballpark, Pac-Bell Stadium, opens with an old rivalry.
STARS:
Monday:
</P>
<P>
   -- Johnny Damon, Royals, led off the bottom of the ninth with a
home run, lifting Kansas City to a 6-5 victory over Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   -- Shane Andrews, Cubs, hit a game-tying, three-run homer in the
ninth as the Cubs rallied for a 4-3 victory over Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   -- Jim Edmonds, Cardinals, went 4-for-4 with two doubles in St.
Louis' 8-7 victory over Houston.
</P>
<P>
   -- Travis Fryman, Indians, had four hits and four RBIs as
Cleveland routed Oakland 9-4.
SO YOUNG:
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati's Ken Griffey Jr. became the youngest player to hit
400 career home runs Monday when he connected in the Reds' 7-5 loss
to Colorado. At 30 years, 141 days, Griffey beat the previous mark
set by Jimmie Foxx, who was 30 years, 248 days old. Griffey's homer
came on the 50th birthday of his father, Reds coach Ken Griffey. It
its the fourth time Griffey has homered on his father's birthday.
SWAT MAN:
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis' Mark McGwire homered for the third straight game in
Monday night's 8-7 victory at Houston. McGwire raised his career
total to 525 -- nine behind Jimmie Foxx for ninth on the career
list. His first homer at Enron Field gave McGwire home runs in 35
major league ballparks, one behind the record held by Tampa Bay's
Fred McGriff.
SCHILLING'S REHAB:
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia's injured ace, Curt Schilling, allowed two hits in
four shutout innings for Clearwater of the Class-A Florida State
League in a rehab start Monday night. Schilling struck out nine
Daytona Cubs, throwing 63 pitches, 45 for strikes. His fastball
topped out at 94 mph.
STRONG START:
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim's Scott Schoeneweis, making his second major league
start, pitched a three-hitter as the Angels beat Toronto 6-0 Monday
night. It was the Angels' first complete-game shutout in almost two
years. Chuck Finley was the last Anaheim pitcher to accomplish the
feat, with a 5-0 win over Tampa Bay on April 17, 1998.
SOON GONE:
</P>
<P>
   Milwaukee played its final opening-day game at County Stadium on
Monday, beating Florida 4-3. Miller Park, scheduled to open this
season before a crane accident July 14 killed three ironworkers and
severely damaged the stadium, will open next year.
STRONG IN DEFEAT:
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's Kevin Millwood allowed six hits in seven scoreless
innings Monday, but the Braves lost to the Chicago Cubs 4-3.
SECOND HEAVEN:
</P>
<P>
   Colorado third baseman Jeff Cirillo had two doubles in a 7-5
victory over Cincinnati on Monday. Cirillo has five hits this
season, all doubles.
SERVING UP HOMERS:
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City has given up an AL-high 18 homers this season,
including a two-run shot in its 6-5 victory over Minnesota on
Monday.
SLICK FIELDING:
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota turned inning-ending double plays in the second,
third, fourth and eighth innings of its 6-5 loss to Kansas City on
Monday.
SLUGFEST:
</P>
<P>
   Arizona's Erubiel Durazo homered twice and Jay Bell, Steve
Finley and Kelly Stinnett also connected as the Diamondbacks beat
San Diego 8-4 Monday night. The five home runs matched an Arizona
club record.
SQUANDERED:
</P>
<P>
   The New York Mets wasted a four-run lead for the second straight
game in Monday night's 9-7 loss to Philadelphia.
STATS:
</P>
<P>
   Four of Andres Galarraga's six hits for Atlanta this season have
been homers. Four of J.D. Drew's five hits for St. Louis have been
long balls. ... Chuck Finley and three relievers combined to strike
out 16 Oakland batters as Cleveland beat the Athletics 9-4 Monday
night. ... In just the fourth game at Houston's new Enron Field,
the Cardinals and Astros combined for eight homers, two more than
the previous record for major league games in Houston. Each team
hit four home runs as St. Louis beat the Astros 8-7.
SPEAKING:
</P>
<P>
   ''It wouldn't be Philly if guys didn't run out on the field and
have fights in the upper deck.'' -- Philadelphia's Mike Lieberthal
on the raucous, opening-night crowd that saw the Phillies beat the
New York Mets 9-7 Monday night.
SEASONS:
April 11:
</P>
<P>
   1912 -- Rube Marquard of the New York Giants began a 19-game
winning streak with an 18-3 victory over the Brooklyn Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   1961 -- The Los Angeles Angels won their first major league game
with a 7-2 victory over the Orioles at Baltimore. Ted Kluszewski
had a pair of homers for the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   1962 -- The New York Mets lost their first game played, 11-4 to
the Cardinals in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   1969 -- The Seattle Pilots played their first game, with Gary
Bell shutting out the White Sox 7-0 at Sicks Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   1985 -- Seattle's Gorman Thomas hit three homers and drove in six
runs to lead the Mariners to a 14-6 victory over the Oakland A's.
</P>
<P>
   1990 -- Mark Langston made his Angels' debut by combining with
Mike Witt on a no-hitter as California beat the Seattle Mariners
1-0.
</P>
<P>
   1996 -- Greg Maddux's major league record of road victories ended
at 18 with a 2-1 loss to the San Diego Padres. He was 18-0 with an
0.99 ERA in 20 regular-season road starts since losing at Montreal
on June 27, 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Today's birthdays: Bret Saberhagen 36; Turner Ward 35; Sean
Bergman 30; Jason Varitek 28; Bobby M. Jones 28; Trot Nixon 26;
Todd Dunwoody 25; Kelvim Escobar 24.
</P>
