<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 05:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Addresses Elian Situation  </HEADLINE>
By JAMES HANNAH, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   VANDALIA, Ohio (AP) -- In a bid to win the hearts of a roomful of
undecided voters, Vice President Al Gore shared his views on the
custody dispute over a 6-year-old Cuban refugee, a controversial
incinerator in eastern Ohio and a host of other issues.
</P>
<P>
   About 250 people crowded into the library at Vandalia-Butler
High School on Monday night for the two-hour town meeting. The vice
president appeared relaxed and at ease with the audience, which
came armed with questions of every sort.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said the relatives of 6-year-old Cuban refugee Elian
Gonzalez should be allowed to try to work out among themselves the
escalating custody dispute over the boy.
</P>
<P>
   ''With tensions as high as they are and with both sides trying
to figure out a way to come to a resolution, I think that we need
to encourage the talks between the family members themselves,''
said Gore. ''Let the entire family, including the Florida
relatives, talk with one another without people from the U.S.
government or the Cuban government or lawyers on either side.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore was visiting Avondale Elementary School in Columbus today
while his Republican opponent, Texas Gov. George W. Bush, was
unveiling poverty initiatives in Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's campaign said he would deliver a speech emphasizing ways
to help those on the outskirts of poverty move up into the middle
class.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also was scheduled to tour El Barrio, an agency that
provides social services, including job training, high school
diploma classes and youth summer camp, to a mostly Hispanic
clientele.
</P>
<P>
   In his appearance Monday evening, Gore addressed President
Clinton's sex scandal involving Monica Lewinsky when asked what he
would do to bring respect to the office of the presidency. Gore
said he would bring his ''values of faith and family.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The president is my friend,'' said Gore. ''I explained my
disapproval of his personal mistakes. I'm running for president on
my own, on the basis of my own vision.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore said he has made no decision on a vice presidential
candidate or any other appointments should he be elected.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not drawing up a list, short or long, for a running mate,
Cabinet members or the Supreme Court,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was asked what he would do about the WTI hazardous-waste
incinerator near East Liverpool, Ohio. He said the administration
of former President Bush -- the current putative GOP nominee's
father -- granted an operating permit to the incinerator just before
Clinton assumed the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ''Most of the options available to us were taken away from us by
a last-minute decision by the Bush-Quayle administration,'' he
said. ''But I have asked EPA, and they have agreed, to do a
full-scale review of this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
