<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Higher, Tokyo Stocks Lower  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- The dollar rose against the yen today in Tokyo on
speculation that leading finance ministers will express concern
about the yen's strength at a meeting this weekend. Tokyo stocks
closed moderately lower on selling of Internet issues.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar bought 106.96 yen on the Tokyo foreign exchange
market in late trading today, up 0.90 yen from Monday and above its
late New York level Monday of 106.47 yen.
</P>
<P>
   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average fell 96.54 points,
or 0.47 percent, to close at 20,522.52 on the Tokyo Stock Exchange.
On Monday, the average rose 366.25 points, or 1.81 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In currency dealings, overseas investors bought dollars on
sentiment that the greenback would rise further if finance
ministers attending the Group of Seven meeting release a statement
saying that the yen has risen too high.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa said today he will
tell G-7 counterparts that Japan will not tolerate a strengthening
of the yen.
</P>
<P>
   ''You have seen for yourselves what we do when we feel that a
rapid strengthening of the yen is problematic,'' Miyazawa said at a
regular news conference, referring to dollar buying intervention in
currency markets by the Bank of Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials have said the yen's rapid rise against the
greenback could hurt Japan's unstable economic recovery by making
its exports more expensive on world markets, and cutting into the
earnings of export led companies.
</P>
<P>
   Finance ministers and central bankers from the G-7 the United
States, Japan, Britain, France, Italy, Canada and Germany will
gather in Washington this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   In other currencies, the euro was traded at 102.98 yen, up from
101.50 yen Monday in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   On the stock market, technology stocks pulled the market down.
Internet stocks fell in Tokyo following sharp losses Monday on the
technology focused Nasdaq Stock Market in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ''The market is seeking to determine the future course of high
flying U.S. Internet stocks which have given U.S. investors rich
gains and thereby helped them invest in Japanese stocks,'' said
Hiroyuki Negishi, manager of equities at Marusan Securities.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, the Nasdaq composite index fell 258.25 Monday to
close at 4,188.20, its second largest point drop ever. The Dow
Jones industrial average rose 75.08 to 11,186.56.
</P>
<P>
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange's first section, 828 issues fell,
with 439 issues finishing higher and 122 unchanged from Monday.
Volume on the first section is estimated at 586.81 million shares,
up from 519.81 million shares Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the
first section fell 15.65 points, or 0.92 percent, to close at
1,701.09. The TOPIX closed up 39.12 points, or 2.33 percent, on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond rose
to 1.7500 percent from Monday's finish of 1.7350 percent. Its price
fell 0.13 point to 101.29.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
