<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 06:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Talks Continue in Janitors Strike  </HEADLINE>
By GARY GENTILE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Striking janitors and the cleaning
contractors who employ them worked toward a compromise with the
help of Los Angeles' political leaders as the walkout entered its
second week.
</P>
<P>
   The latest wave of janitors walked off the job in Pasadena,
parts of Hollywood and the Wilshire corridor Monday night, bringing
those on strike to an estimated 8,500 since the walkout began April
3.
</P>
<P>
   Some 200 janitors marched and chanted slogans in downtown
Pasadena late Monday, clad in the red ''Justice for Janitors''
shirts that have become ubiquitous in local business districts.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Richard Riordan said he foresaw an end to the strike
''within 24 hours'' and predicted workers would receive ''somewhat
near what they are asking.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I wish it was going to be that simple,'' said Service
Employees International Union Local 1877 President Mike Garcia.
''We're still apart on the money.''
</P>
<P>
   But Garcia conformed that both sides were getting closer.
Building owners, union officials and political leaders met
throughout the weekend and more talks were underway Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   The 18 cleaning contractors that handle 70 percent of the
county's office space have scrambled to hire replacement workers.
Workers in San Diego, Chicago and New York have offered support to
the strikers.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinal Roger Mahony, archbishop of the Los Angeles Diocese,
celebrated Mass that culminated in a march by workers from the Arco
Towers in downtown to Our Lady Queen of Angels Church.
</P>
<P>
   Standing outside the church Monday, he called the janitors the
''invisible workforce'' and said they deserved a share of ''the
wonderful fruitfulness of our economy.
</P>
<P>
   ''They come in at night after the offices are closed,'' Mahony
said as he awaited the marching workers outside the church. ''They
are faceless, nameless, voiceless. Now they are visible, thanks be
to God.''
</P>
<P>
   About 500 workers carrying white carnations marched into the
church, some singing in Spanish a hymn of the labor movement, ''We
Shall Not Be Moved,'' and other singing more traditional church
hymns.
</P>
<P>
   The janitors earn $6.80 to $7.90 per hour with health benefits
and are seeking a $1 per hour raise for each of the next three
years. The cleaning contractors have offered a raise of 80 cents to
$1.30 over the same period.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: SEIU: http://www.seiu.org
</P>
<P>
   National Right to Work Legal Defense Foundation:
http://www.nrtw.org
</P>
</TEXT>
