<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 07:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Books and Authors: Ha Jin  </HEADLINE>
By AUDRA ANG, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Ha Jin is fatigued. Worn out. Dog tired.
</P>
<P>
   Since winning the National Book Award in November for his novel,
''Waiting,'' the author's quiet life has been pumped up by fame and
pummeled by interviews, readings and lectures.
</P>
<P>
   Fans approach him at airports, his home phone number is no
longer listed, e-mails deluge his inbox.
</P>
<P>
   ''Of course I'm tired of it,'' Jin says. ''On the other hand, I
can't be rude.''
</P>
<P>
   And he's not.
</P>
<P>
   Jin, an immigrant from China, is gracious and patient, a
soft-spoken man who weighs the nuances of his second language
carefully, often pausing for a moment before answering.
</P>
<P>
   ''I feel a little overwhelmed. ... People are treating me like a
celebrity. I don't think I'm a celebrity,'' he says. ''It's not
comfortable for me. When I go to a place, I would like to be
treated like a regular person.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he adds, it's a small price to pay for winning the $10,000
award, one of the literary world's most coveted. In recent days,
Jin has picked up another jewel for his literary crown, the
Pen/Faulkner prize, and there was much buzz that he was a strong
contender for a Pulitzer Prize.
</P>
<P>
   Jin, who came to the United States in 1985, stresses that the
road to success has been paved by countless hours of financial
worries and littered with numerous rejections from publishers.
</P>
<P>
   ''Nothing is easy,'' the author says from Boston, where he was
scheduled to give a lecture. ''It has been difficult all the time.
I think any good work has to be earned with some kind of effort and
sacrifice. That is the price we have to pay.''
</P>
<P>
   The son of a low-ranking army officer, the 44-year-old author,
whose given name is Jin Xuefei -- meaning golden flying snow -- was
born in northeast China's Liaoning province. When he was 10,
bonfires of books burned across the country and schools were shut
down in the wake of the anti-intellectual Cultural Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   In 1970, at age 14, he joined the People's Liberation Army where
he volunteered for the artillery and to work as a telegraph
operator near the Russian border for the next five years. His
military experiences provided much inspiration for future works,
especially ''Ocean of Words,'' his first collection of short
stories.
</P>
<P>
   ''Physically it was very hard. In the first few months, we
didn't have enough food ... and it was very cold. Mentally, it
wasn't too bad. I knew there might be a war and so we were ready
and knew if we had to die, we'd die,'' Jin says.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were not sad. We were quite happy ... because everything
was new: big guns and trucks. And I was young.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1972, Jin had his first, brief taste of Western literature --
a translation of ''Don Quixote'' passed around the barracks -- after
years of reading Mandarin versions of Marx, Lenin and Engels.
</P>
<P>
   When colleges were reopened five years later, Jin began
half-hour English lessons with the goal of reading the original of
Engels' ''The Condition of the Working Class in England in 1844.''
</P>
<P>
   He passed entrance exams to the Heilongjiang University in
Harbin (which inspired the first half of his pen-name) and
eventually earned his master's degree at Shandong University, and
his doctorate in English at Brandeis University in Boston in 1993.
He now teaches creative writing at Emory University in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The National Book Award came only 12 years after Jin began
writing in English, and it was not his first accolade. He already
had the Flannery O'Connor and PEN/Hemingway awards -- one for each
of his anthologies of short stories -- and three Pushcart Prizes for
poetry under his belt.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, ''success is only the byproduct of the writing, the
effort. It's almost accidental. It's not the goal,'' he notes. ''As
a writer, I think I'm no more than an instrument ... to make a book
as good as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics have likened Jin's work to that of Isaac Babel and Anton
Chekov. His prose is clear, but brilliantly detailed, sparkling
within his vignettes of life in rural Red China.
</P>
<P>
   An example: ''The air was still warm though the crimson sun was
approaching the indigo peak of the Great Emperor Mountain. Grass
had pierced the soil here and there, and the cornfields, sown a few
days before, looked like huge gray ribs stretching towards the end
of the green sky. Everything seemed sluggish and even the air made
one feel languid.''
</P>
<P>
   ''My goal is always to transform the story into literature from
history so that it can be shared by people emotionally,
psychologically,'' Jin says.
</P>
<P>
   The novel ''Waiting'' is based on a story he heard from his
wife's parents almost 20 years ago. ''Intuitively, at that moment,
I knew it could be a novel,'' he says. ''It's about three people's
whole lives and, besides, a love story is always a great subject.''
</P>
<P>
   The book follows the 18-year relationship between a married army
doctor and a nurse as each summer the doctor tries to divorce his
peasant wife. The characters, while constrained by the rules of the
Communist party, eventually get what they want -- but at a price far
higher than anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   ''My interpretation of the story is that this is a good man, a
decent man, a good-natured man. But emotionally, he's crippled and
because of the harsh situation, he never has the opportunity to
develop, to grow up emotionally,'' Jin says.
</P>
<P>
   While at Brandeis, Jin had planned to return to China to do
research and teach after getting his doctorate. But he changed his
mind in 1989, after hundreds of pro-democracy demonstrators -- many
of whom were students -- were killed by the military in Beijing's
Tiananmen Square.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Tiananmen massacre was beyond my imagination,'' Jin says.
''I didn't imagine that the government could do such a terrible
thing. ... It was a senseless, wasteful tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   He is currently working on another novel and a short story
collection; a book of poems is scheduled to be released next fall.
While speaking engagements and family life don't leave much time
for writing, he has to write every day, he said. ''Otherwise I'd be
bad-tempered,'' Jin admits with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   ''When I started, I didn't realize there was a lot of isolation,
frustration. Before, I could write academic papers but creative
writing required a different kind of ability, different levels of
diction, nuances, dialogue.''
</P>
<P>
   And the more he writes in English, the more he appreciates the
language.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is very unique in many ways. It ... has embraced authors
whose mother tongues are not English and their works have become
mainstream,'' he says. ''By comparison, most other languages don't
open themselves and offer that kind of possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   ''English is the language of the common people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
