<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 07:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> At the Movies: 'East is East'  </HEADLINE>
By HILLEL ITALIE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the spirit of screwball comedy, ''East is East'' begins with
a wedding gone wrong. An arranged Pakistani marriage is to take
place in London. We see the procession, the primping, the costumes,
the last-minute snags and unsnags. It's a long, nervous buildup to
a classic snap of wedding nerves: The groom turns and runs for his
freedom.
</P>
<P>
   In Hollywood, the escapee would have hurried into the arms of
his true love. But ''East is East,'' its title borrowed from the
Kipling poem about East-West conflict, tends to more practical
affairs. It's interested in the people left behind, a large,
rebellious mixed-raced family for whom life often feels like an
altar worth bolting from.
</P>
<P>
   Om Puri stars as George Khan, a patriarch soured by his own
double standards. Married for 25 years to a white woman (Linda
Bassett), he tries to bully their sons into marrying Pakistanis. He
demands their daughter wear a sari on Sundays, but sends her
weekdays to a Western school. He has the airs of a self-made man,
but depends on money from his wife's family.
</P>
<P>
   The year is 1971, a bad time for those accustomed to giving
orders. The Khan kids (seven in all) talk back, let their hair grow
and don't care much about Pakistani culture. The chants of the
Koran have been displaced by the beat of British pop.
</P>
<P>
   The film itself has a slacker's rhythm: informal, disorganized,
likable. It runs 96 minutes and takes half that time to present an
actual story: a double arranged marriage. Until then, it's an
assortment of vignettes about the family's life: a boy's tender
surgery, a girl's jokey dance with a broom, a young man's kisses
with his pretty white neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Damien O'Donnell, and adapted by Ayub Khan-Din from
his own play, ''East is East'' has had great success in the United
Kingdom. It was nominated for six BAFTA awards, Britain's version
of the Oscars, and was named best British picture by the London
Film Critics Circle.
</P>
<P>
   The appeal, however, doesn't quite translate. The script could
have used another draft. The subplots aren't developed and the
father's character especially feels underwritten, abruptly changing
from amiable grouch to hateful tyrant. Puri, playing a confused,
desperate man, did far better with a similar role in last year's
''My Son the Fanatic.''
</P>
<P>
   But weddings -- even the idea of them -- seem to inspire the
filmmakers. ''East is East'' peaks in the penultimate scene when
George and family are visited by a snobbish Pakistani clan, the two
daughters intended as brides for two younger Khan sons.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a disaster of manners worthy of old Hollywood --
the dinner party in ''Alice Adams,'' the clash of the two families
in ''You Can't Take it With You.'' The Khans couldn't behave for
all the money in England, thank goodness. They may be freaks in
their own world, but in movies they're part of a great comic
tradition.
</P>
<P>
   A Miramax Films release, ''East is East'' was produced by Leslee
Udwin. It's rated R, with violence, profanity and adult situations.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
</P>
<P>
   G -- General audiences. All ages admitted.
</P>
<P>
   PG -- Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
</P>
<P>
   PG-13 -- Special parental guidance strongly suggested for
children under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young
children.
</P>
<P>
   R -- Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
</P>
<P>
   NC-17 -- No one under 17 admitted.
</P>
</TEXT>
