<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 10:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IBF founder goes to trial, accused of taking bribes to rigrankings  </HEADLINE>
By JEFFREY GOLD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- Never a sport with a savory reputation,
boxing can expect to have more of its dirty laundry aired over the
next three months during the racketeering trial of IBF founder
Robert W. Lee.
</P>
<P>
   Testimony is expected to touch on some of the biggest names in
the sport, including promoter Don King and former heavyweight
champion George Foreman.
</P>
<P>
   Lee and others in the International Boxing Federation are
accused of taking $338,000 in bribes to rig its boxer rankings,
which play a big role in determining who a boxer fights and how
much he earns.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors maintain that King was a prime beneficiary of Lee's
manipulations and call him and other promoters unindicted
coconspirators. Foreman and 22 other boxers caught up in schemes
outlined in a November indictment also face no charges.
</P>
<P>
   In his opening statement today, federal prosecutor Jose Sierra
said Lee dashed the dreams of young boxers by taking no less than
32 bribes to rig the IBF rankings.
</P>
<P>
   He told the jury the case is about men who make ''hundreds of
thousands of dollars, or millions, without ever throwing a punch.''
</P>
<P>
   The trial was to start last week, but U.S. District Judge John
W. Bissell put it on hold for a hearing on defense objections to
undercover videotapes of three meetings between Lee and the FBI's
key informant, C. Douglas Beavers, the IBF's longtime rankings
chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Bissell was initially inclined to bar videos from two of the
meetings, agreeing with defense contentions that since Lee was to
sleep in the suite where those meetings took place, his Fourth
Amendment privacy rights were violated.
</P>
<P>
   But prosecutors convinced him that Lee could not expect privacy
in the sitting area of a hotel suite, where the camera had been
concealed.
</P>
<P>
   Bissell on Monday ruled that all of the videos were admissible.
He said the FBI took ''reasonable safeguards'' to avoid taping Lee
when Beavers was not in the parlor, and although ''there were
instances in which perfection was not achieved'' they were not
prevalent.
</P>
<P>
   Lee's schemes began shortly after starting the East Orange-based
IBF in 1983, prosecutors say. As one of the world's three major
sanctioning groups, its rankings have been the basis for many
important fights.
</P>
<P>
   Bissell has barred Lee, 66, of Fanwood, from any participation
in the IBF, pending outcome of the trial. At the request of
prosecutors, Bissell in January appointed a monitor to oversee the
group.
</P>
<P>
   The tapes stem from meetings on rankings Lee had with Beavers, a
Virginia boxing commissioner, at the Holiday Inn in Portsmouth,
Va., on June 9, 1997; Dec. 18, 1997; and Oct. 21, 1998. The first
two were in a suite that included a bedroom; the third was in a
conference room that adjoined a bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   Beavers wore a body wire during those meetings, but those
recordings failed, prosecutors said. He also recorded dozens of
telephone conversations with Lee, and is expected to testify for
several weeks. The U.S. attorney's office has granted Beavers
immunity.
</P>
<P>
   Lee's lawyer, Gerald Krovatin, said the hotel rooms were ''the
functional equivalent of your home'' and asserted that prosecutors
should have gotten a judicial order before videotaping.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said that since they already had a wired informant,
a judge would not have been likely to grant such a request.
</P>
<P>
   The audiotapes of phone calls with Beavers did not need such an
order because agents had the consent of one party -- Beavers -- so
Krovatin did not challenge those tapes.
</P>
<P>
   During the June 1997 meeting, Beavers and Lee discuss demanding
$25,000 to move heavyweight Joe Hipp up to the No. 6 contender
slot, according to a sworn statement from an FBI agent.
</P>
<P>
   In a tape from December 1997, Beavers is seen removing a package
of $5,000 from his ankle and giving it to Lee, according to the
statement. Investigators say the money is a payoff from a promoter.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 21, 1998, Beavers takes money from his ankle and gives
some to Lee and some to a former IBF official, Don Brennan, and Lee
puts an envelope on a table and says it is ''turkey'' from
''Fuzzy,'' the FBI said.
</P>
<P>
   In court papers, Beavers said that ''turkey'' was a payoff and
''Fuzzy'' was King.
</P>
<P>
   Although Lee was indicted with three other IBF officials, only
he and his son, Robert Jr., 38, of Scotch Plains, are on trial.
They face multiyear prison terms if convicted on conspiracy,
racketeering, fraud and tax charges.
</P>
<P>
   Francisco Fernandez of Colombia, the South American
representative of the IBF, remains at large.
</P>
<P>
   Brennan, 86, of Warsaw, Va., past president of the U.S. Boxing
Association, a group that became the IBF, was severed from the
trial due to ill health.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
