<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 10:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Missing rafters presumed dead  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   HANOVER, N.Y. (AP) -- Divers have recovered the body of one of
two whitewater rafters whose craft capsized Saturday on Cattaraugus
Creek, state police said.
</P>
<P>
   The body of John Tenz, 57, of Blasdell was recovered about 11:30
p.m. Monday from an island in the middle of the creek. Tenz's body
had been spotted earlier in the day by a pair of bird watchers
walking along the creek in Hanover on the Cattaraugus Indian
Reservation.
</P>
<P>
   State police said turbulent waters and the location of the
island, about 100 yards from the closest accessible point, made
recovery difficult. Tenz was pronounced dead at the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Still missing and presumed drowned was 48-year-old Daniel
Zelasko of Cheektowaga.
</P>
<P>
   The two men were among a group of eight on a whitewater rafting
trip Saturday when their 10-foot rubber raft hit rough waters at
the juncture of Cattaraugus and Zoar creeks.
</P>
<P>
   Two other people thrown from the capsized craft were rescued
when one grabbed on to a protruding tree limb and another managed
to stay afloat and hang on to the capsized raft.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said both Zelasko, a Buffalo high school teacher,
and Tenz, a volunteer firefighter, did not wear life jackets or
protective clothing.
</P>
<P>
   The sheriff's department used a helicopter and high-tech
infrared equipment in scouring the area over the weekend. The
searchers failed to find anything even though creek water levels
have dropped from 10 feet to under four feet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
