<DOCNO> APW20000411.0108 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 10:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Legal Group Protests $5 Cenus Bonus  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   VALDOSTA, Ga. (AP) -- Critics of using statistical sampling for
the Census are objecting to a city program offering people $5 for
filling out their forms.
</P>
<P>
   The City Council approved the program, in effect this week, in
hopes of improving the response, but the payments may violate the
state constitution's ban on ''gratuities'' to induce economic
activity for the general welfare, said Matthew Glavin, president of
the Southeastern Legal Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ''I strongly suggest before handing out any money that the city
get a formal opinion from the attorney general's office,'' Glavin
said in a letter Monday to Mayor Jimmy Rainwater.
</P>
<P>
   City Manager Larry Hanson said the proposal was approved by
regional Census Bureau officials. He said a number of other cities
around the country have provided financial incentives, including
utility credits, for returned census forms.
</P>
<P>
   Glavin was a plaintiff in a case last year in which the Supreme
Court ruled the federal government cannot use sampled data from the
Census Bureau as a basis of reapportioning House seats. Census
officials favor using statistical sampling, contending it accounts
for populations that are traditionally undercounted, such as
inner-city residents.
</P>
<P>
   ''I find it absolutely astonishing any city would go forward
with a program like this without review by legal counsel. It
suggests irresponsibility on the part of the City Council,'' Glavin
said of Valdosta's program.
</P>
<P>
   Hanson said the state constitution seems to be referring to
grants and payments to a private individual who, for example,
receives a large sum to bring an industry to town.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can't think of anybody, by any stretch of the imagination,
who would think of $5 as a grant,'' Hanson said.
</P>
<P>
   Just 15 residents took advantage of the $5 offer Monday,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The southern Georgia city hopes to be named a Metropolitan
Statistical Area -- a designation that makes a city attractive to
new business and clears the way for more government grants.
</P>
<P>
   Would-be metro areas must have populations of 50,000 in the main
city or 100,000 in the main county. Surrounding counties can be
included if cities can prove dramatic commuting patterns.
</P>
<P>
   The Census Bureau's 1998 population estimates showed Valdosta
with 41,390 residents and surrounding Lowndes County with 85,231.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-11-00 1056 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
