<HEADLINE> Rep. Moran Confronted by Boy  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) -- Rep. James Moran said today he has
nothing but affection for an 8-year-old boy who tried to steal his
car by claiming to have a gun and wishes he could adopt the
youngster.
</P>
<P>
   After talking with the boy, ''I just wanted to hug him,'' Moran,
D-Va., said on NBC's ''Today.''
</P>
<P>
   Police said Moran was picking up his two sons from an
after-school recreation center Friday when the boy approached him
in the parking lot, said he had a gun in his pocket and demanded
Moran's keys.
</P>
<P>
   Moran held out the keys but then grabbed the boy, police said.
The youngster had no weapon.
</P>
<P>
   Moran said the boy told him he learned to act like a thief from
his stepfather. Then the boy's mother arrived and yelled
obscenities, he said.
</P>
<P>
   He criticized the boy's parents and said he would love to adopt
the child, although he did not expect that to happen. He has a
daughter about the same age as the boy.
</P>
<P>
   Moran said he did not want the boy charged. Police had said they
would not press charges without the congressman's cooperation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
