<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Off 141.03; Dow Up 66.39  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Technology stocks fell sharply today, wiping out
the Nasdaq's gains for the year, as the volatile biotech sector
declined in response to a disappointing earnings report from
Biogen.
</P>
<P>
   In morning trading on Wall Street, the Nasdaq composite index
was down 141.03 at 4,047.17. The index is now 20 percent below its
peak of 5,048.62, which it reached March 10. At its peak, the
Nasdaq was up 24 percent for the year; today's decline leaves it at
a loss for the year.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were mixed. The Dow Jones industrial
average was up 66.39 at 11,252.95, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
index was down 8.73 at 1,495.73.
</P>
<P>
   Two downbeat earnings reports derailed stocks today. Biogen, a
leading biotechnology company, reported first-quarter earnings of
41 cents a share, below Wall Street expectations of 43 cents.
Biogen cited a slowdown in demand for its multiple sclerosis
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Biogen fell 10 15/16 to 54 1/16. Investors sold off other
biotech firms, and Genentech fell 5{ to 151.
</P>
<P>
   The broader technology sector declined after Motorola said it
expects second-quarter and full-year 2000 earnings to fall short of
analysts' views.
</P>
<P>
   Motorola, which makes cellular phones and semiconductors, said
it expects profit margins to shrink in the coming quarters. Late
Monday, Motorola released first-quarter earnings that had more than
doubled from the first quarter of 1999 due to robust demand for
cellular phones and strong growth in its chip business.
</P>
<P>
   Motorola shares plummeted 25 1/16 to 124 15/16. Rival Texas
Instruments fell 8{ to 147~ and chip-industry leader Intel lost 2\
to 128~.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's some concern that what's hurting Motorola could affect
the rest of the techs,'' said William Meehan, chief market analyst
at Cantor Fitzgerald.
</P>
<P>
   The corporate earnings reporting season begins in earnest this
week, and while profit growth for most companies is expected to be
quite strong, investors in a nervous market are proving unwilling
to tolerate any disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   In recent sessions, Wall Street strategists have been reminding
investors that many old-line companies in the energy, financial and
consumer sectors may reward investors seeking stable, growing
profits.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're definitely seeing continued rotation into more
reasonably priced stocks, many of which will also show strong
earnings,'' Meehan said.
</P>
<P>
   Exxon Mobil rose 1 5/16 to 79 9/16 and 3M rose 1 11/16 to 94
7/16.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 10-to-9 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 328.12 million
shares, ahead of Monday's quiet pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 11.12 to
507.54.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
