<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 12:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report Charts Student Progress  </HEADLINE>
By ANJETTA McQUEEN, AP Education Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A record number of children with disabilities
are being educated in classrooms alongside their nondisabled peers,
often without teachers specially qualified to instruct them, the
Education Department said today.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996-97, 46 percent of the nation's 5.9 million special
education students spent most of their time in a regular classroom,
up slightly from the previous year's 45.9 percent, the department
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The days of turning away the students with disabilities at the
schoolhouse door have ended,'' said Judith Heumann, assistant
secretary of the office of special education and rehabilitative
service. She said the record is a victory for disabled children's
inclusion in the nation's educational system, a goal of federal
education laws and many advocacy groups.
</P>
<P>
   The annual report to Congress also detailed some trouble spots:
Besides a shortage of teachers for students who need extra help,
there is a lack of state-provided services for youth in prison,
special-education preschoolers and blind children.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the nation's 330,000 special education teachers, once
isolated in small classrooms, now work daily with regular classroom
teachers, but 8 percent of the special-education teaching force is
improperly certified to work with disabled students, the report
said. Among general teachers, preparedness is worse: Four out of
five teachers with special education students in their classes feel
ill-prepared to teach them, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Teachers must be increasingly prepared to meet all children's
needs,'' said Paula Gardner, an associate professor at California
State University, Sacramento, which combines special
education-regular education training. Graduates usually go on to
teach in special education classrooms, but they are trained to
teach special education students in regular classes, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ''District administrations are seeing the value of this as a way
of educating future teachers,'' she said. ''We can't graduate them
fast enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the 1975 Individuals with Disabilities Education Act,
states receive money to help end discrimination against disabled
children, who previously were often put in institutions or separate
programs that provided little or no learning. The law requires that
disabled children be schooled with other students whenever
possible.
</P>
<P>
   The report considered children as included in a regular
classroom atmosphere if they spent at least 80 percent of their
time in regular classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   It also said more young prisoners are qualifying for special
education, but that jailed youth -- many with learning disabilities
or emotional disturbances -- are less likely to be helped if they
are treated as adults.
</P>
<P>
   All schools and 92 percent of juvenile halls and detention
centers instruct special-needs schoolchildren, the report said, yet
just a third of states report providing the same services in adult
prisons. A 1997 change in the special education law allows adult
prisons to limit special education services if they conflict with
security.
</P>
<P>
   The report also said:
</P>
<P>
   --The youngest special education children -- those age 2 and below
-- must receive services at home. Toddlers 3 to 5 years old have
programs they can attend at some schools.
</P>
<P>
   --Fewer college instructors are preparing teaching candidates to
work with blind students.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: The special education report will be available this
afternoon: http://www.ed.gov/offices/OSERS/OSEP/index.html/ -- click
on PUBS, click latest report under Annual Reports
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-11-00 1201 </TRAILER>
