<HEADLINE> New York's top court upholds state's Internet porn law  </HEADLINE>
By L. ANNE NEWELL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- The state's highest court today unanimously
upheld the constitutionality of a law designed to prevent adults
from using the Internet to induce or invite minors into having sex.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Foley, a 51-year-old radio engineer from Grand Island who
was one of the first people convicted under the 1996 state law, had
argued it was overbroad, vague and unconstitutional because it
restricted free speech and interstate trade.
</P>
<P>
   The Court of Appeals disagreed in today's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   The law ''is a pre-emptive strike against sexual abuse of
children,'' wrote Judge Richard Wesley for the seven-member court.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, he wrote, ''We are hard pressed to ascertain any
legitimate commerce that is derived from the intentional
transmission of sexually graphic images to minors for the purpose
of luring them into sexual activity.''
</P>
<P>
   The law took effect Nov. 1, 1996 and state police conducted a
sting operation beginning Oct. 28 and continuing through November
during which an officer posed as a 15-year-old Utica girl named
''Aimee.''
</P>
<P>
   Foley began a sexual conversation with the officer in a chat
room called ''Kids of Family Sex.'' Foley then sent the officer
several pictures of preteen girls engaged in sexual acts with men.
He also told ''Aimee'' that he wanted to have sex with her and the
two made preliminary plans to meet.
</P>
<P>
   Foley was arrested during his fifth and final chat with
''Aimee'' on Nov. 22, when police executed a search warrant and
found him typing on his computer.
</P>
<P>
   He was convicted of two counts each of attempting to disseminate
indecent materials to minors and promoting a sexual performance by
a child and sentenced to two to six years in prison.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
