<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oil Cos. Plan Procurement Exchange  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS (AP) -- A group of 14 of the largest oil and petrochemical
companies plan to launch an electronic exchange to link buyers and
suppliers of goods and services.
</P>
<P>
   The 14 companies spend more than $125 billion each year on
procurement, they said in a joint announcement Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Other industries, including transportation, have recently
announced similar procurement exchanges, designed to improve
efficiency and supply-chain management.
</P>
<P>
   An independent company would be created to own and operate the
exchange. The founding oil companies said they would own at least
three-fourths of the exchange operator but would eventually prepare
to sell its stock to the public.
</P>
<P>
   The founding members of the exchange would be Royal Dutch-Shell
Group of Cos., BP Amoco PLC, Conoco Inc., The Dow Chemical Co.,
Equilon Enterprises LLC, Mitsubishi Corp., Motiva Enterprises LLC,
Occidental Petroleum Corp., Phillips Petroleum Co., Repsol YPF,
Statoil SA, Tosco Corp., TotalFinaElf and Unocal Corp..
</P>
<P>
   The companies said about 40 percent of their procurement
spending occurs in North and South America, another 40 percent in
Europe and Africa, and about 20 percent in Asia Pacific and the
Middle East.
</P>
</TEXT>
