<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 13:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 'Corner' Focuses on Baltimore Family  </HEADLINE>
By KATHY GAMBRELL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE (AP) -- Gary McCullough pushed carts of copper pipes
and aluminum screen doors that were stripped from abandoned houses
to the United Iron and Metal Company, where he got a few dollars
for his next heroin fix.
</P>
<P>
   It is a far cry from the $50,000-a-year job he once held, from
the two Mercedes and the home he once owned.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Corner,'' HBO's six-part mini-series that will air Sundays
at 10 p.m. EDT beginning April 16, chronicles the story of
McCullough, his ex-wife Fran Boyd, and their son DeAndre McCullough
as they became caught in the grip of drug addiction and street
corner sales.
</P>
<P>
   The project is based on the David Simon and Edward Burns book,
''The Corner: A Year in the Life of an Inner City Neighborhood,'' a
gritty, critically acclaimed view of how drug addicts live.
</P>
<P>
   Fran and Gary were a classic middle-class couple. Gary owned
investment properties and was a partner in a development and
drafting company. Fran worked for the phone company. They
considered moving to the Baltimore suburbs. Then, as Fran was
grieving at her sister's wake, a family member offered her some
drugs. That's when their lives began spiraling out of control.
</P>
<P>
   ''Gary's Blues,'' the first segment of the series, opens with
Gary and a girlfriend shooting heroin in a boarded-up flophouse.
They spend their days shuffling from one side of the street to the
other in a desperate search for quick cash for their next fix, or
for a generous soul willing to give up a stash for free.
</P>
<P>
   Simon, the force behind the defunct ''Homicide: Life on the
Street,'' and Burns, a former Baltimore police officer, spent six
days a week in 1993 on a west Baltimore corner observing the drug
culture and its effects on the McCullough family.
</P>
<P>
   The movie was filmed in west Baltimore row houses, crack houses,
and on corners a few blocks from where the story actually unfolded.
</P>
<P>
   Charles ''Roc'' Dutton, who won a Golden Globe for his
performance in August Wilson's ''The Piano Lesson,'' was chosen as
the director for his introspectiveness and his Baltimore roots.
</P>
<P>
   ''With a white director, some of the nuances would be lost,''
said Simon, who served as co-producer with David Mills (''ER,''
''NYPD Blue'') and Robert Colesberry (''Mississippi Burning'').
</P>
<P>
   ''He's an actor's actor,'' Simon said. ''He grew up in East
Baltimore. We knew if we could get him working on performances, we
knew it would be something electric.''
</P>
<P>
   Cast members agreed. Comedian T.K. Carter (''A Rage in
Harlem''), who portrays Gary, said Dutton did not want the typical
movie caricature of a drug addict, but rather a portrait of a
person who has fallen into a situation he can't escape.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Corner'' is important, Dutton said, because viewers should
understand that drug addiction is a disease that needs to be
treated.
</P>
<P>
   ''I see it as a health problem,'' Dutton said. ''I've had a lot
of family and friends afflicted with this disease.''
</P>
<P>
   But Dutton, who starred in the Fox comedy series ''Roc,'' had to
be persuaded to take on the project.
</P>
<P>
   ''When I was first approached, I hadn't read the book. I thought
it was another urban documentary -- written badly and acted badly,''
said Dutton. ''But I was impressed with the script and the book.''
</P>
<P>
   Dutton says the mini-series tells the story of a neighborhood
from the point of view of the addict.
</P>
<P>
   Cast members spent time with their real-life counterparts to
better understand their journey.
</P>
<P>
   When actress Khandi Alexander (''ER'') met with Fran Boyd to
talk about the role or just to hang out, she never asked Boyd about
her choices.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am sure she had reasons for some of the things she had to
do, but I never asked her about them. It wasn't my place,''
Alexander said.
</P>
<P>
   Although self-destructive, Fran had boundaries when it came to
her 15-year-old dropout son, who mastered the intricacies of
peddling drugs. She would not hold DeAndre's drugs, or hide his
guns, or teach him how to cut dope or stretch a package for higher
profit.
</P>
<P>
   She eventually became a drug counselor.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the people mentioned in the book appear in the film,
Simon said. He cast the real DeAndre, who has not made the same
transformation as his mother, as a police officer arresting his
screen self, played by Sean Nelson (''The Wood'').
</P>
<P>
   ''Part of it was amusing, but it was also my way of making a
point to DeAndre,'' Simon said. ''I wanted to make a point.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in television ...
</P>
<P>
   GOING TO 'PIECES': ''Picking Up the Pieces,'' Alfonso Arau's
black-humored comedy starring Woody Allen, has been acquired by
Cinemax, the cable network announced. It will premiere May 26 as
part of the network's ''First on MAX'' series. The latest project
from the director of such critically acclaimed movies as ''Like
Water for Chocolate'' and ''A Walk in the Clouds,'' the film also
stars Maria Grazia Cucinotta, Cheech Marin, David Schwimmer, Kiefer
Sutherland and Sharon Stone. It was shot by three-time Academy
Award-winning cinematographer Vittorio Storaro.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-11-00 1301 </TRAILER>
