<HEADLINE> Strike Shuts Finnish Paper Industry  </HEADLINE>
By MATTI HUUHTANEN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HELSINKI, Finland (AP) -- Finland's pulp and paper industry
ground to a halt Tuesday when 30,000 workers went on strike after
all-night contract talks with employers broke down.
</P>
<P>
   Disagreement about wages and working hours was so great that the
government-appointed mediator, Juhani Salonius, said he was unable
to offer a compromise proposal.
</P>
<P>
   The Finnish Paper Workers Union demanded a two-year labor
agreement with wage hikes of 4.6 percent during this year and 4.1
percent in 2001. It also wanted a decrease in working hours
amounting to seven days per year.
</P>
<P>
   The Finnish Forest Industries Federation offered a three-year
agreement with a 3.1 percent raise this year, and rejected any
shortening of working hours.
</P>
<P>
   No timetable for a resumption of talks was given.
</P>
<P>
   It is the first time a strike closed down the whole pulp
industry in Europe's third-largest paper producer behind Germany
and Sweden. Industry estimates are that it will cost an estimated
$32 million per day in lost export earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Workers on Monday began to shut down machines at plants in
anticipation of the strike that began Tuesday afternoon and
involves some 100 machines at 30 plants.
</P>
<P>
   The strike was unlikely to affect consumers immediately as
stockpiles of newsprint and other paper were expected to last
several weeks. But the chemicals industry was likely to suffer as
demand stalls for chemicals used in paper and pulp production.
Also, the transport sector would be affected when cargos of raw
materials and paper cease.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
