<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 13:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Aetna Ends Doctor Incentive System  </HEADLINE>
By SUSAN PARROTT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS (AP) -- Health insurer Aetna U.S. Healthcare settled a
lawsuit with Texas today, promising to give doctors more power over
medical treatments and removing financial incentives for doctors to
limit care. Officials said they hoped the deal would become a
national precedent, helping settle other suits around the country
against managed care companies alleging that they harm patients in
the name of profits.
</P>
<P>
   ''This settlement puts medical decisions precisely where they
belong, and that is in the hands of patients and their
physicians,'' Texas Attorney General John Cornyn said at a news
conference this morning.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Brown, Aetna regional manager, said the agreement would not
force the HMO to increase costs. ''We believe we can do this
without significantly adding to the cost of doing business.''
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn's predecessor, Dan Morales, sued Aetna and five other
HMOs two years ago, accusing them of illegally compensating doctors
who limited patients' medical care and penalizing those who didn't.
</P>
<P>
   Aetna, under the settlement, is prohibited from fining doctors
who exceed medical budgets or giving them bonuses for staying
within limits. The state's largest HMO also will have to report if
doctors' groups in its plan do give such financial incentives.
</P>
<P>
   ''We believe this agreement sets the industry standard, not just
to our state borders but to a national level,'' Cornyn said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It'll get all over the country real fast,'' said Rocky Wilcox,
chief counsel of the Texas Medical Association.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement contains no finding of fault, fines or penalties.
And Aetna denies any wrongdoing in the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ''A lot of what is embodied in the agreement is not new business
practices,'' Arthur Leibowitz, Aetna's chief medical officer, said.
''This is partially the attorney general's desire to solicit other
plans to fit within this business model.''
</P>
<P>
   The agreement didn't please everyone. A consumer group, Texans
for Public Justice, said the deal ''appears to be a sweetheart
agreement for the state's biggest HMO,'' because it doesn't impose
any penalties on Aetna.
</P>
<P>
   If the other HMOs named in the lawsuit do not agree to the same
terms, the attorney general said, he will bring them to trial. The
HMOs are Humana Health Plans of Texas, PacifiCare of Texas, NYLCare
Health Plans of the Southwest and NYLCare Health Plans of the Gulf
Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Aetna said it decided to settle the lawsuit and accept state
regulatory oversight because it will help restore the public's
trust in managed care, said David Simon, the company's chief legal
counsel.
</P>
<P>
   The company has 960,000 Texans in its HMO and 2.4 million
members enrolled in all of its health-care programs.
</P>
<P>
   ''We felt like if we could achieve this landmark settlement with
Aetna, then Aetna's competitors would then know this would set the
standard for them as well,'' Cornyn said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.aetna.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
