<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 14:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mass. Hospital Sells Used Scrubs  </HEADLINE>
By JEFF DONN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLYOKE, Mass. (AP) -- Intent on confining cuts to the operating
room, Holyoke Hospital will sell you the very shirt off its
doctors' backs.
</P>
<P>
   The little hospital is selling its used -- but sanitized -- scrubs
as leisure wear to those who crave comfort or more surgical swank
than they can soak up just by watching ''E.R.'' on television.
</P>
<P>
   Kathy Buckley, the hospital's vice president of marketing,
concedes that some have reacted with squeamishness at the thought
of wearing pajamas that once assisted in setting a broken leg.
</P>
<P>
   Buckley acknowledged that some people say, ''Oh, my God, that's
so disgusting, because they had blood on them!''
</P>
<P>
   ''But that's the cool part,'' she added. ''Don't you get it?''
</P>
<P>
   Scrubs, the loose V-neck tops and drawstring pants worn by
medical personnel, have long packed an appeal outside the
profession. New scrubs, often in bright colors and floral patterns,
are sold by hospital gift shops, uniform stores in shopping malls,
and even department stores. They are worn for comfort during home
and yard projects, or even double as pajamas.
</P>
<P>
   ''The ''Chicago Hopes'' and ''E.R.s'' potentially could have
made it a little more cool than it had been,'' said Craig
Freebersyser, a manager at scrub manufacturer Angelica Image
Apparel in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   But officials at several national hospital associations said it
is very unusual to resell scrubs actually worn in surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ''Most of the waste from hospitals you wouldn't want to sell,''
said Steve Goetz, director of the Health Care Resource Management
Society in Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   The 200-bed independent hospital in Holyoke began selling its
scrubs last fall to staff who wanted comfortable togs to wear away
from work. Earlier this year, it launched a Web site dedicated to
selling its surgical scrubs to ordinary consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The unisex scrubs come in a range of sizes, blue or green, and
cost $24.95 for either shirt or pants. They are more expensive than
some new scrubs sold elsewhere, but those have ''never seen real
action,'' said Buckley.
</P>
<P>
   Once worn in surgery by a doctor, nurse or technician, the
scrubs are laundered at a high temperature with chlorine bleach to
clean and disinfect, just as when they are reissued to medical
staff. They are sent to an outside shop where the trademarked
Realscrubs logo is applied with silk screen.
</P>
<P>
   The hospital, which skirted layoffs but reduced hours of some
personnel last summer, hopes Realscrubs will supply a continuing
source of cash to help cover expenses. Buckley says some other
hospitals have asked about licensing a similar business at their
sites.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.realscrubs.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-11-00 1458 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000411.0143 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 14:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rep. Returns to Capitol After Rehab  </HEADLINE>
By JENNIFER LOVEN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Illinois Rep. Phil Crane has returned to his
congressional duties after completing a 21-day treatment program
for alcoholism, receiving warm applause from colleagues on the
House floor Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Crane, the most senior House Republican and a former
presidential candidate, declared he is back and ''in good health.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I feel better, mentally and physically,'' said Crane, a
16-term congressman from Chicago's northwest suburbs. ''I look
forward to the hard work. ... This has been a deeply humbling
experience for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Crane returned to the House in time for a series of votes Monday
evening.
</P>
<P>
   The 69-year-old conservative announced last month he was taking
a leave of absence to enter a treatment program in Maryland. At the
time, he said his growing dependance on alcohol ''has taken a toll
on my health and other aspects of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Many believed the death of his daughter, Rachel, more than a
year ago contributed to his decline.
</P>
<P>
   Crane's wife, Arlene, said her husband's decision to undergo
treatment was made in large part to help his bid to become chairman
of the powerful House Ways and Means Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Crane now holds the second-ranking slot on the tax-writing
committee and heads its trade subcommittee. His seniority places
him in line to take over the panel next year after the current
chairman, Rep. Bill Archer of Texas, retires. But he faces a stiff
challenge from Rep. Bill Thomas of California, the third-ranking
Republican and chairman of its health subcommittee.
</P>
<P>
   Crane has fervently promoted freer trade and is a longtime
supporter of a flat tax. In recent months, Crane has spent more
time raising money for colleagues in an attempt to cement his
chances for the chairmanship.
</P>
<P>
   Political observers have split over whether Crane's disclosure
of alcoholism will help or hurt his chances.
</P>
</TEXT>
