<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 14:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bodies of Marines Being Recovered  </HEADLINE>
By MICHELLE RUSHLO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARANA, Ariz. (AP) -- Military investigators began the slow and
gruesome task today of removing the remains of 19 Marines who died
in the fiery crash of an MV-22 Osprey aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   Recovery of the remains was expected to take several days with
identification likely to involve DNA, fingerprints and other
records, said Lt. Mark Carter, a spokesman for the Marine Corps Air
Station in Yuma, where the flight originated Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ''The process is a slow process because it's a detailed
operation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Workers in white jumpsuits and wearing masks could be seen
loading what appeared to be a body bag into a semitrailer this
morning. Their movements were largely masked by the trailer and
tarps suspended in front of the wreckage.
</P>
<P>
   Officials spent Monday taking measurements, examining pieces of
the charred wreck and trying to ensure that investigators could
remove the remains safely, Carter said.
</P>
<P>
   All 19 Marines aboard the Osprey were killed Saturday when it
crashed during an evacuation training exercise at Marana Northwest
Regional Airport, about 30 miles north of Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   The victims were four crew members from Quantico, Va., 14
Marines from Camp Pendleton, Calif., and one from Marine Corps Air
Station-Miramar in San Diego County.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. James Jones, commandant of the Marine Corps, said today
that the blast from the crash of the Osprey rocked a second Osprey
hovering nearby, causing it to experience a hard landing.
</P>
<P>
   Jones also said the crash was witnessed by the crew chief of the
surviving Osprey. He said this witness' description of what he saw
was likely to play an important role in the accident investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators still hadn't determined the cause of the wreck as
of early today, but Capt. Aisha Bakkar-Poe, a spokeswoman at the
Pentagon Marine Corps headquarters, said a preliminary cause could
be released in the next week or two.
</P>
<P>
   She said the Marines remain confident of the safety of the
innovative Osprey, which is intended as a replacement for the
corps' aging fleet of CH-46 Sea Knight helicopters.
</P>
<P>
   By tilting their large rotors, Ospreys can take off like
helicopters and then fly like airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   The Marines' other four Ospreys were not flying after the crash,
but Bakkar-Poe said that mostly was out of respect for the victims'
families and the other Osprey crews.
</P>
<P>
   ''We really don't feel there's a design flaw,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She said the Osprey that crashed had flown more than 135 hours
since it was delivered on Jan. 17. It averaged 40 hours a month in
the air, about twice as much as most Marine aircraft, but the extra
flight time should not have been a factor in the crash, Bakkar-Poe
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Osprey was introduced in September. The Marines have ordered
360 at a cost of $44 million each, said Pentagon spokesman Capt.
Rob Winchester.
</P>
<P>
   The mother of one of the victims, Keoki Santos, 24, of Grand
Ronde, Ore., said her son had concerns about riding in the Osprey.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was really, really nervous about the whole thing,''
Christina Mercier said. ''He was a beautiful, high-spirited, true
Marine. He didn't want to just go into the service for four years.
He enlisted to be a career man. And they killed him. They wanted
him to be a guinea pig for these new airplanes.''
</P>
<P>
   The Marine Corps lists two other crashes during the Osprey's
development: A 1991 Delaware accident blamed on gyro wiring
problems and a 1992 Virginia crash that killed all seven people on
board after an engine caught fire.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Camp Pendleton: http://www.cpp.usmc.mil/jpao/home.htm
</P>
<P>
   Navy Osprey Web site: http://www.navair.navy.mil/v22
</P>
</TEXT>
