<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 15:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Up 136.74; Nasdaq Down 59.85  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Technology stocks fell today as the volatile
biotech sector declined in response to a disappointing earnings
report from Biogen. Blue-chip issues once again drew money away
from the technology sector.
</P>
<P>
   With an hour remaining in Wall Street's regular session, the
Nasdaq composite index was down 59.85 at 4,128.35. The choppy
trading that has characterized the market in the past two weeks
returned again, with the Nasdaq paring an earlier loss of 178
points to fewer than 10 before heading lower again.
</P>
<P>
   After weeks of tumultuous selling, the Nasdaq is now up only
slightly during 2000 and is 19 percent below its peak of 5,048.62,
which it reached March 10.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were mixed. The Dow Jones industrial
average was up 136.74 at 11,323.30, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
index was down 1.18 at 1,503.28.
</P>
<P>
   Two downbeat earnings reports hurt stocks today. Biogen, a
leading biotechnology company, reported first-quarter earnings of
41 cents a share, below Wall Street expectations of 43 cents.
Biogen cited a slowdown in demand for its multiple sclerosis
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Biogen fell 13\ to 51}. Investors sold off other biotech firms,
with Genentech tumbling 16 to 140{.
</P>
<P>
   The broader technology sector declined after Motorola said it
expects second-quarter and full-year 2000 earnings to fall short of
analysts' views.
</P>
<P>
   Motorola, which makes cellular phones and semiconductors, said
it expects profit margins to shrink in the coming quarters. Late
Monday, Motorola released first-quarter earnings that had more than
doubled from the first quarter of 1999 due to robust demand for
cellular phones and strong growth in its chip business.
</P>
<P>
   Motorola shares plummeted 26 9/16 to 123 7/16. Rival Texas
Instruments fell 3~ to 152{ and Advanced Micro Devices fell 4| to
69|.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's some concern that what's hurting Motorola could affect
the rest of the techs,'' said William Meehan, chief market analyst
at Cantor Fitzgerald.
</P>
<P>
   Meehan said nervous investors are continuing to shed technology
stocks that may not be worthy of their valuations, which are
generally much higher relative to earnings than the industrial
stocks that dominate the Dow.
</P>
<P>
   ''More than a few portfolio managers found themselves
overexposed to technology last quarter,'' he said. ''Some are
getting out, and some are just sitting on their hands waiting for
the market to settle down.''
</P>
<P>
   The corporate earnings reporting season begins in earnest this
week, and while profit growth for most companies is expected to be
quite strong, investors in a nervous market are proving unwilling
to tolerate any disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   In recent sessions, Wall Street strategists have been reminding
investors that many old-line companies in the energy, financial and
consumer sectors may reward investors seeking stable, growing
profits.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're definitely seeing continued rotation into more
reasonably priced stocks, many of which will also show strong
earnings,'' Meehan said.
</P>
<P>
   General Electric rose 3] to 162 13/16 and 3M rose 3| to 96].
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues and decliners were even on the New York Stock
Exchange, where volume came to 786.72 million shares, ahead of
Monday's quiet pace. On the Nasdaq, decliners were ahead by a
3-to-1 margin.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 7.22 to 511.44.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
