<HEADLINE> Recent Legal Actions Against HMOs  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Some other HMO controversies:
<TEXT>
<P>
   -- 25 states have enacted laws prohibiting managed-care plans
from using financial incentives that compensate doctors for
ordering or providing ''less than medically necessary and
appropriate care,'' according to the National Conference of State
Legislatures Health Policy Tracking Service.
</P>
<P>
   --The attorneys general of Connecticut and Missouri also have
filed lawsuits against HMOs, though not for problems involving
doctor compensation. Missouri's suit alleges that two HMOs
committed fraud by accepting Medicaid payments for services they
denied; Connecticut's accuses a managed-care company of
discouraging access to medically necessary drugs.
</P>
<P>
   --Texas, California, Georgia and Washington have passed laws
permitting lawsuits against managed-care companies.
</P>
<P>
   -- The federal Health Care Financing Administration issued
guidelines prohibiting federally regulated managed-care plans from
using financial incentives that act as an ''inducement to reduce or
limit'' referrals for medically necessary services. The regulations
apply only to Medicaid and Medicare plans.
</P>
<P>
   -- A federal patients' rights bill is before a conference
committee attempting to work out differences in House and Senate
versions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
