<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN's Holbrooke Talks To Congress  </HEADLINE>
By TOM RAUM, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Getting the United Nations to agree to reduce
the assessment it charges the United States will be tough, U.N.
Ambassador Richard Holbrooke told Congress on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   And, while there is some sentiment in the world organization to
go along with lowering the U.S. general assessment, getting a
reduction in peacekeeping costs will be even more difficult,
Holbrooke said.
</P>
<P>
   Congress last year linked payment of back dues to the United
Nations to a variety of structural changes, including reducing the
U.S. share of general U.N. operations from the present 25 percent
to 22 percent; and the peacekeeping budget from 31 percent to 25
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nation's peacekeeping operations are already
''stretched way too thin for the problems they face,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Getting the General Assembly to go along with any reductions in
the U.S. share may be more trouble than its worth, suggested
Holbrooke, even though he said he would continue to work hard to
follow the terms of the U.S. law
</P>
<P>
   Testifying before a House Appropriations subcommittee, Holbrooke
said that of the 189 nations in the world body, ''not everyone in
New York is equally committed'' to reform -- or lower U.S. payments.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's going to be tough,'' he testified.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations puts back U.S. dues at $1.7 billion -- a
figure the United States disputes.
</P>
<P>
   Congress last year voted to pay $926 million of the arrears over
three years, with a $100 million first installment.
</P>
<P>
   But to get the balance, the United Nations must meet about a
dozen conditions drafted by Senate Foreign Relations Committee
Chairman Jesse Helms, R-N.C., and Sen. Joseph Biden of Delaware,
the panel's senior Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Those terms generally have not been well received in New York,
although Holbrooke said one of them -- no inflation-adjusted
increase in the U.N.'s budget -- is being met.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile the discrepancy between the $1.7 billion the United
Nations claims the United States owes and the roughly $1 billion
the United States calculates it owes will continue, Holbrooke said.
</P>
<P>
   ''They are neither going to take it off the books -- nor are we
going to pay it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke's appearance comes 1{ weeks after he and other members
of the U.N. Security Council visited Washington at the invitation
of Helms and Biden, including an appearance before Helms'
committee.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Senate Foreign Relations Committee:
http://www.senate.gov/(tilde)foreign/
</P>
<P>
   U.N. Security Council: http://www.un.org/Overview/Organs/sc.html
</P>
</TEXT>
