<HEADLINE> Business News in Brief  </HEADLINE>
By MARIA CODER, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIDS IN CHARGE: Planning to go on a business trip? You might
want to check with your child first.
</P>
<P>
   A survey by Sheraton Hotels &AMP; Resorts found that more than
two-thirds of the parents who took part have refused to go on a
business trip because of conflicts with their children's
activities. Forty-one percent of the 300 men and women who
responded to the online survey said they would cut a trip short
because of a birthday or child's illness. Nearly a third wouldn't
travel if there's a school event. And 5 percent said they would
cancel altogether if their children were upset about their leaving.
</P>
<P>
   ''The playroom wins over the boardroom,'' said John Greenleaf a
vice president at Sheraton parent Starwood Hotels &AMP; Resorts
Worldwide. ''This study showed us just how far a business traveler
will go to preserve the delicate balance between work and family
life.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   GIFT ALERT: Want to make your secretary or assistant feel
appreciated? Give them a day at the spa but please, pass on the
Chia Pet.
</P>
<P>
   With Secretaries Day set for April 26, OfficeClick.com polled
more than 1,500 office managers, administrative assistants and
secretaries to see what gifts they'd most like to receive.
</P>
<P>
   Among the top choices: a gift certificate to a day spa, a day
off and a gift certificate for two to a local restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 10 percent of the respondents said not being recognized
was the worst possibility. Almost as bad were skimpy gifts such as
Chia Pets or a ''bouquet of dying flowers at 4:30 p.m,'' as one
respondent put it.
</P>
<P>
   Sue Fox, author of ''Office Etiquette for Dummies,'' advises
bosses, ''Your gift celebration needs to speak for itself. It needs
to say 'I recognize, and truly appreciate the hard work you do to
help make our business successful.'''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   SHOW ME THE MONEY: As CEO pay points toward a record-breaking
year, shareholders are urging companies to share profits with
employees.
</P>
<P>
   Members of Responsible Wealth, a network of business people and
investors, have requested shareholder votes at several big U.S.
companies seeking a link between CEO and worker compensation. Scott
Klinger, co-director of Responsible Wealth, said ''companies that
make CEOs megamillionaires and billionaires while shortchanging
most employees on quicksand.''
</P>
<P>
   The group noted that even at companies where thousands of
employees have lost their jobs, CEOs continued to earn in the tens
of millions of dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-11-00 1535 </TRAILER>
