<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 15:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Civil Rights Commission Speaks Out  </HEADLINE>
By MICHELLE MITTELSTADT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The U.S. Commission on Civil Rights denounced
policies in California, Texas and Florida that replace affirmative
action in public universities with guaranteed admission for top
high school graduates.
</P>
<P>
   The plans are ''no substitute for strong race-conscious
affirmative action,'' the commission said in a 10-page statement
approved last week and made public Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Other states should move ''warily'' to adopt similar plans, and
then preferably only as a complement to existing affirmative action
programs, commission Chairwoman Mary Frances Berry said at a news
conference.
</P>
<P>
   ''If a state has affirmative action, the commission believes
that if it can ... keep it, it ought to,'' Berry said.
</P>
<P>
   Florida Gov. Jeb Bush, a Republican, dismissed the
Democrat-dominated commission's finding as a ''purely political
statement.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas and California crafted new admissions policies after
affirmative action in public university admissions was outlawed in
1996 -- in Texas by a federal court and in California by voters.
</P>
<P>
   The Florida plan, pushed by Bush, has yet to be implemented.
</P>
<P>
   Texas was the first state to embrace a percentage plan, enacting
a law that guarantees admission at state colleges and universities
to Texas students in the top 10 percent of their high school
graduating class.
</P>
<P>
   While minority enrollment systemwide has rebounded from the lows
that resulted when affirmative action was ended, the commission
found the admittance rate for black and Hispanic students at the
University of Texas at Austin is down.
</P>
<P>
   California promises admission to the top 4 percent of its high
school students. But since that plan was implemented, the minority
enrollment at its flagship state universities -- UCLA and Berkeley --
has plummeted.
</P>
<P>
   Minority enrollment in graduate and professional programs, in
particular, has suffered.
</P>
<P>
   ''The major problem with the percentage plans is their
inattention to law schools, medical schools and other graduate and
professional schools, where ending affirmative action is
devastating,'' the commission said.
</P>
<P>
   In Florida, Bush moved earlier this year to end affirmative
action in admissions and state contracting, offering the One
Florida plan that promises admission to students graduating in the
top 20 percent of their class. The plan drew protests and a sit-in
in the lieutenant governor's office.
</P>
<P>
   Defending the One Florida plan, Rep. Charles Canady, R-Fla.,
accused the commission of engaging in a ''partisan attack'' and
said its members are ''fixated'' on affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   ''They prefer a system that uses race-conscious measures even to
a system that will provide more benefits to members of
minorities,'' Canady said. ''That is an ideological position that's
indefensible.''
</P>
<P>
   Berry denied any political calculus in criticizing plans in
states led by two high-profile Republicans: Jeb Bush and his
brother George, the governor of Texas and GOP presidential
nominee-in-waiting.
</P>
<P>
   The statement was approved by the commission's six Democrats,
who include a campaign adviser to Vice President Al Gore but was
rejected by its two Republican members. The GOP commissioners
issued a written dissent, saying the statement was ''littered with
inaccuracies and half-truths.''
</P>
<P>
   The commission issued the statement because other states
weighing percentage plans asked the panel for its views, Berry
said. The panel, created in 1957, has no regulatory power.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-11-00 1544 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000411.0153 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 15:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Award-Winning Film To Be Altered  </HEADLINE>
By DINA KRAFT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- Several graphic pictures showing the bodies of
slain Israeli athletes will be blurred in an Academy Award-winning
documentary on the massacre at the 1972 Munich Olympics, a producer
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The filmmakers agreed to the changes at the request of the
families of the athletes who were upset by the pictures, said
Arthur Cohen, who produced the documentary.
</P>
<P>
   It is fairly unusual to change a film after it has been
released, but Cohen said that despite misgivings, the filmmakers
owed it to the families to make the alterations in ''One Day in
September.'' The film won the Academy Award last month for best
feature documentary.
</P>
<P>
   The film documents the raid on September 5, 1972, when
Palestinian militants took over a dormitory housing Israeli
athletes. Following a 20-hour standoff, nine Israelis died in a
bungled rescue attempt after the Palestinians killed two others. A
German policeman and five Palestinian militants also were killed.
</P>
<P>
   ''We made a film against terror,'' Cohn told The Associated
Press in a telephone interview, ''It is very difficult to make a
document of terror if the photos are softened. We were reluctant
but agreed to it out of respect for the families.''
</P>
<P>
   Ankie Spitzer, whose husband Andre, the fencing coach for the
Israeli team, was among those killed, said she was horrified to see
the unaltered forensic pictures used in the original film.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer said her daughter, who was 5 weeks old when her father
was killed, has not been able to sleep since seeing the movie at a
private screening.
</P>
<P>
   ''We said there are enough other pictures even of the room
itself where they (the athletes) were kept hostage which are so
horrifying that they should be enough,'' Spitzer said. ''The story
is shocking enough that we don't need to see the dead mutilated
bodies of our husbands and fathers,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer last saw her husband on television, when he appeared at
the window of the dormitory room where the Israeli athletes were
held hostage, acting as a go-between for the gunmen and German
authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Hands bound behind his back, he reported in German that all the
hostages were fine except for one -- and was promptly hit on the
head with a rifle butt and whisked from sight.
</P>
<P>
   After the ordeal, Spitzer visited the blood-drenched room where
her husband and the others were tied to furniture while they
watched weightlifter Yossi Romano die.
</P>
<P>
   Romano had tried to overpower his well-armed captors with a
kitchen knife. They shot the weightlifter four times and left him
to slowly bleed to death on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   The militants, members of the terror group Black September,
demanded the release of 200 prisoners jailed in Israel and safe
passage for themselves out of Germany. Israel refused to negotiate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-11-00 1557 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000411.0154 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 15:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chase Manhattan To Buy Fleming  </HEADLINE>
By BRUCE STANLEY, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Chase Manhattan Corp. is paying $7.6 billion in
cash and stock for Robert Fleming Holdings Ltd., a British
investment bank and asset management group, in a bid to help it
become a bigger player in global investment banking.
</P>
<P>
   Chase, the third-largest U.S. bank with $406.1 billion in assets
as of the end of 1999, has agreed to pay $4.1 billion in cash and
$3.5 billion in common stock for Robert Fleming, one of Britain's
last independent financial companies. The deal requires regulatory
approval.
</P>
<P>
   Credit Lyonnais Securities analyst Julian Bird attributed the
value of the deal to Chase's eagerness to expand into the
high-growth field of asset management and to the reluctance of the
Fleming family to sell its majority of shares in the company.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's quite a full price,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Chase chief executive William Harrison said the buyout would
benefit clients of both firms through the delivery of a wider range
of investment banking products and services.
</P>
<P>
   Chase would obtain one of the ''premier asset management
brands'' in Asia and Europe, Harrison told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ''These are two markets we think are significant growth markets
that we want to be larger in.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrison added that Robert Fleming is also strong in the
securities business in Asia, particularly in the state-owned
sector, where Chase has been weak.
</P>
<P>
   Fleming chief executive William Garrett said the decision to
forgo the British bank's independence was driven by its need for
greater size in order to compete.
</P>
<P>
   ''The emergence of a number of powerful global houses has
changed the competitive landscape over the last few years,''
Garrett said.
</P>
<P>
   ''While we have responded successfully to this and have just
completed a record year for the Flemings Group, we recognize that
global markets require global reach.''
</P>
<P>
   By linking up with Chase, Robert Fleming could expand its reach
in North America and other regions.
</P>
<P>
   The buyout marks the latest step in Chase's evolution away from
pure commercial banking. Last year, Chase purchased the investment
bank of Hambrecht &AMP; Quist for $1.35 billion.
</P>
<P>
   By acquiring Fleming, New York-based Chase follows in the tracks
of rival Citigroup Inc. Earlier this year, Citigroup purchased the
investment banking business of Schroders, another independent
British financial company.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Fleming dates to 1873, when its founder set up a trust to
invest in the booming U.S. railroad industry. Among the railroads
he helped finance were the Union Pacific, Pennsylvania, and
Atchison, Topeka &AMP; Santa Fe lines.
</P>
<P>
   Another Fleming family member was the creator of secret agent
James Bond, author Ian Fleming, who was groomed for a career at the
bank but never worked there.
</P>
<P>
   The deal was initially valued at $7.7 billion, but shares of
Chase dipped $2.75 to $85.37{ in trading on the New York Stock
Exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-11-00 1558 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
