<HEADLINE> Uproar Over Aid to India's Tigers  </HEADLINE>
By GEORGE MWANGI, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) -- Wildlife experts have recommended that
financial support be cut off to tiger conservation programs in
India, sparking warnings Tuesday that halting aid would further
endanger the world's shrinking tiger population.
</P>
<P>
   Despite millions of dollars in help, India's wild tiger
population -- the world's largest -- is being heavily poached,
apparently by gangs of organized and well-funded hunters, according
to a report prepared for the U.N. Convention on International Trade
in Endangered Species, or CITES.
</P>
<P>
   The report, to be presented in Nairobi in the next few days to
the 11th CITES conference, recommends that financial support be cut
off until India shows it is efficiently spending the money already
set aside to protect the cats.
</P>
<P>
   ''We need to save tigers before it is too late,'' said Willem
Wijnstekers, the CITES secretary general. ''There is a lot of hurry
in this process.''
</P>
<P>
   But Suresh Sharma, the head of the Indian delegation to the
CITES conference, warned that if financial aid is blocked, the
mission that prepared the report ''will be responsible for killing
tigers.''
</P>
<P>
   The wild tiger population, under severe threat from habitat loss
and poaching, has plummeted from over 100,000 in the 19th century
to just 5,000 to 7,000 today, ranging from India and Russia to
China and Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
   While tiger hunting is now illegal everywhere and international
trade in tigers and tiger products is banned under CITES, tigers
and tiger parts used for decorations or traditional medicines are
available on black markets.
</P>
<P>
   India's tiger program, among the most high-profile in the world,
is riddled with problems, the report said, including funds not
reaching desperately ill-equipped and underpaid field workers and
poorly coordinated anti-poaching programs.
</P>
<P>
   Forest guards in parts of India patrol without radios, modern
weapons and decent vehicles, the report said, and some guards have
not been paid in 21 months.
</P>
<P>
   It said that while some officials were dedicated to saving the
tigers, ''varying levels of apathy, complacency and bureaucracy
seem to stifle or frustrate good work and good intentions.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharma, however, felt the report painted an unfairly bleak
picture of tiger conservation in India. ''Our country has generally
gone beyond what CITES has recommended,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   About 2,000 delegates from 151 countries and scores of
non-governmental conservation and environmental organizations are
participating in the Nairobi conference, which began Monday and
ends April 20.
</P>
<P>
   Country delegations often include members of non-governmental
organizations lobbying for adding or removing certain species from
the CITES listing, which regulates trade in endangered species.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-11-00 1608 </TRAILER>
