<HEADLINE> Ex.-Sen. Heads Harvard Institute  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) -- Former Arkansas Sen. David Pryor has
been named director of the Institute of Politics at Harvard
University's John F. Kennedy School of Government.
</P>
<P>
   Pryor, a Democrat, replaces former Sen. Alan Simpson, R-Wyoming,
who has held the post for two and a half years. Simpson will return
to Wyoming to teach at the University of Wyoming.
</P>
<P>
   The Institute was established in 1966 in honor of President
Kennedy. It sponsors a resident fellows programs, organizes
conferences and lectures and manages the Forum, Harvard's main
stage for public affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Pryor, 65, served for six years in the House of Representatives
and for four years as governor of Arkansas. He was elected to the
U.S. Senate in 1979 and served for 18 years. Since retiring from
the Senate in 1996, he has been a Fulbright Distinguished Fellow of
Law and Public Affairs at the University of Arkansas.
</P>
</TEXT>
