<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Ends Down 132; Dow Up 100  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Technology stocks fell sharply today, wiping out
the Nasdaq composite index's gains for the year. The volatile
biotechnology sector was the latest catalyst for the steady decline
of the index that just recently seemed unstoppable.
</P>
<P>
   Blue-chip issues once again drew money away from the technology
sector, pulling the Dow Jones industrials to their highest levels
since January.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index fell 132.32 to close at 4,055.88. The
choppy trading that has characterized the market in the past two
weeks returned, with the Nasdaq paring an early loss of 178 points
to fewer than 10 before heading lower again.
</P>
<P>
   After weeks of tumultuous selling, the Nasdaq is now
fractionally lower for the year and is nearly 20 percent below its
peak of 5,048.62, which it reached March 10. Still, the index is up
a stunning 56 percent from a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were mixed. The resurgent Dow Jones
industrial average rose 100.52 to close at 11,287.08, its highest
level since Jan. 20, when it closed at 11,351.30.
</P>
<P>
   the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 fell 3.88 to 1,500.58.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 10-to-9 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with 1,530 up, 1,456 down and 481
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   NYSE volume totaled 967.15 million shares as of 4 p.m., vs.
850.19 million in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 8.95 to 509.71.
</P>
<P>
   ''The rotation continues,'' said Larry Rice, chief investment
officer at Josephthal &AMP; Co., referring to investors' turn away from
high-tech and back to old reliable stocks like the Dow issues.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's fast and it's volatile, but it's really becoming the
norm.''
</P>
<P>
   Two downbeat earnings reports derailed the technology sector
today. Biogen, a leading biotechnology company, reported
first-quarter earnings of 41 cents a share, below Wall Street
expectations of 43 cents. Biogen cited a slowdown in demand for its
multiple sclerosis treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Biogen fell steeply. Investors sold off other biotech firms,
with Genentech tumbling.
</P>
<P>
   The broader technology sector declined after Motorola said it
expects second-quarter and full-year 2000 earnings to fall short of
analysts' views.
</P>
<P>
   Motorola, which makes cellular phones and semiconductors, said
it expects profit margins to shrink in the coming quarters. Late
Monday, Motorola released first-quarter earnings that had more than
doubled from the first quarter of 1999 due to robust demand for
cellular phones and strong growth in its chip business.
</P>
<P>
   Motorola shares plummeted. Rivals Texas Instruments and Advanced
Micro Devices also fell.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's some concern that what's hurting Motorola could affect
the rest of the techs,'' said William Meehan, chief market analyst
at Cantor Fitzgerald.
</P>
<P>
   Meehan said nervous investors are continuing to shed technology
stocks that may not be worthy of their valuations, which are
generally much higher relative to earnings than the industrial
stocks that dominate the Dow.
</P>
<P>
   ''More than a few portfolio managers found themselves
overexposed to technology last quarter,'' he said. ''Some are
getting out, and some are just sitting on their hands waiting for
the market to settle down.''
</P>
<P>
   The corporate earnings reporting season begins in earnest this
week, and while profit growth for most companies is expected to be
quite strong, investors in a nervous market are proving unwilling
to tolerate any disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   In recent sessions, Wall Street strategists have been reminding
investors that many old-line companies in the energy, financial and
consumer sectors may reward investors seeking stable, growing
profits. Today, General Electric and 3M rose.
</P>
<P>
   But Rice pointed out that breadth, the difference between rising
and falling stocks, remains very narrow, with just a handful of Dow
issues driving the index higher today. Most investors are
continuing to shift money from sector to sector on a daily basis,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The narrowness of the rally in blue-chips is disconcerting,''
he said. ''It shows you just how nervous the market is.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
