<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 16:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Official Accused in Campaign Case  </HEADLINE>
By MATT KELLEY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The director of an Environmental Protection
Agency regional office broke election laws by soliciting money for
a Montana congressional candidate, prosecutors told a federal
employment board Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Yellowtail, director of the region covering Colorado, Utah,
Wyoming, Montana, North Dakota and South Dakota, is the
highest-ranking federal official to face such a charge since at
least 1995, said Jane McFarland, spokeswoman for the U.S. Office of
Special Counsel that is prosecuting the case.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors allege Yellowtail broke the law by allowing his name
to be attached to a 1998 letter seeking campaign donations for
Robert ''Dusty'' Deschamps, a Democrat running for Montana's lone
U.S. House seat. ''Contributing now to Dusty's campaign is
absolutely critical,'' the letter said.
</P>
<P>
   Yellowtail, a former Montana state senator, resigned from his
EPA post to make an unsuccessful run for the Montana House seat in
1996. He was reappointed to the EPA job in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Rich Lathrop, a spokesman for the regional EPA office, said the
agency has not decided whether to take any action against
Yellowtail.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't know anything more than is in the (Office of Special
Counsel) press release. ... These are serious charges,'' Lathrop
said.
</P>
<P>
   Yellowtail did not return a phone call seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   The petition with the federal Merit Systems Protection Board
accuses Yellowtail of violating the Hatch Act, a federal law
banning campaign activity by government workers.
</P>
<P>
   If the board agrees Yellowtail broke the law, it could order his
firing, McFarland said. The minimum penalty for a Hatch Act
violation is a 30-day suspension, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Office of Special Counsel, an independent agency of federal
prosecutors, brings about four Hatch Act cases a year, McFarland
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-11-00 1653 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000411.0165 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 17:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Baker Cuts Short North Africa Trip  </HEADLINE>
By NICOLAS MARMIE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   RABAT, Morocco (AP) -- Former U.S. Secretary of State James Baker
III cut short his tour of North Africa for health reasons Tuesday
after talks aimed at finding a way to resolve the dispute over the
Western Sahara.
</P>
<P>
   Baker, personal envoy to U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan, flew
to Spain on a military plane on Tuesday afternoon rather than head
to Mauritania as scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   At Rabat airport, Baker said he was leaving ''on doctor's
orders.'' U.N. spokesman Farhan Haq said Baker was suffering from
bronchitis, sinisitis and a high fever.
</P>
<P>
   Haq said Baker was to see Spanish Foreign Minister Abel Matutes
before flying to Paris on Wednesday for a meeting with President
Jacques Chirac.
</P>
<P>
   Baker told reporters that he had telephoned President Mouaouya
Ould Taya of Mauritania. William Eagleton, the special
representative for the Western Sahara, will go to Mauritania soon,
Baker said.
</P>
<P>
   Baker's trip, which started in Algeria on Saturday, was designed
to clear the way for a U.N. referendum to resolve whether the
Western Sahara will gain independence or be integrated with
Morocco.
</P>
<P>
   In Algeria, Baker met with government leaders and members of the
Polisario Front, the guerrilla movement that battled Morocco for
more than 15 years for the Western Sahara's independence. Baker
then met with King Mohammed VI in Morocco.
</P>
<P>
   The Western Sahara independence referendum has been stalled for
years, chiefly over disagreement on how to count potential voters.
In a report in February, Annan expressed doubts about whether the
referendum would proceed and how the results could be implemented.
</P>
<P>
   The Western Sahara is a stretch of desert along Africa's
Atlantic coast. Morocco claims the territory. The Polisario Front,
traditionally backed by Algeria, seeks independence.
</P>
<P>
   War broke out in 1976 after Spain abandoned the territory and
Morocco annexed it and moved in settlers. The war ended in 1991
with a U.N.-negotiated cease-fire.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-11-00 1717 </TRAILER>
