<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 17:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Group Targets Heartburn Medication  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A consumer advocacy group urged the government
Tuesday to move faster to stop sales of Propulsid, a popular
heartburn drug scheduled to be pulled off the market this summer
because it may cause deadly irregular heartbeats.
</P>
<P>
   The Food and Drug Administration last month announced that
Propulsid was too dangerous for continued routine prescription, and
worked with manufacturer Janssen Pharmaceutica to create an unusual
program allowing Propulsid to be taken only by a limited number of
patients with serious illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, Janssen, a subsidiary of Johnson &AMP; Johnson, will
quit marketing Propulsid on July 14 and remove it from pharmacies
in mid-August. But certain patients -- adults and infants -- with
serious medical conditions can apply for the special program to get
the drug after general sales end.
</P>
<P>
   As of Dec. 31, the FDA cited 80 deaths and 341 other heartbeat
abnormalities linked to Propulsid.
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday, the consumer group Public Citizen announced it had
counted an additional 23 Propulsid-related deaths reported to the
FDA this year, bringing the toll to 103.
</P>
<P>
   Waiting until summer to end Propulsid sales is too long, Public
Citizen said in petitioning the FDA to order Propulsid off the
market within two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA will evaluate the request, said gastrointestinal drugs
chief Dr. Florence Houn.
</P>
<P>
   But the agency agreed to let Propulsid continue selling through
summer because it will take Janssen some time to establish the
special-access program -- and then take doctors a while to enroll
eligible patients, she explained.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Janssen will mail letters to 800,000 physicians
explaining the program, said spokesman Greg Panico. Eligible
patients include adults with severe gastroesophagul reflux disease,
or heartburn, not helped by other drugs, and a few other conditions
including gastroparesis, a sometimes lifethreatening inability to
properly digest food. Babies with reflux or another serious feeding
problem also may be enrolled.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
