<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 17:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greenspan: More Job Training Needed  </HEADLINE>
By ALICE ANN LOVE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan joined
Labor Secretary Alexis Herman on Tuesday in a call for better job
training and recruitment programs to satisfy a shortage of skilled
workers.
</P>
<P>
   ''We do have a lot of untapped potential in this labor market,''
said Herman, who hosted a conference on job skills on the campus of
Howard University, a historically black college in the nation's
capital.
</P>
<P>
   With unemployment near 4 percent, the lowest in three decades,
U.S. jobs are plentiful and some companies report having trouble
finding qualified workers to fill positions. However, many
unskilled workers are still encountering barriers to finding a job
-- or one with good wages and benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is not enough to create a job market that has enabled those
with few skills to finally be able to grasp the first rung of the
ladder of achievement,'' said Greenspan, the keynote speaker at the
gathering. ''We must ensure that our whole population receives an
education that will allow full and continuing participation in this
dynamic period of economic history.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite prosperous times, about 6 million Americans remain
unemployed, 3 million part-time workers would prefer full-time
jobs, and another 4 million people say they would seek jobs if not
for impediments such as lack of transportation and childcare,
according to the Labor Department.
</P>
<P>
   ''What we need to do is to dig deeper into the wells of all
three of these groups,'' Herman said in an interview. ''This
economy needs their talents.''
</P>
<P>
   Among industries most desperate for workers are health care,
high tech, construction, finance and manufacturing. Representatives
from companies, unions and training programs in those fields
attended Tuesday's conference to brainstorm solutions.
</P>
<P>
   Among ideas already being tried:
</P>
<P>
   --A Maine organization called Women Unlimited is among several
groups recruiting and training women for jobs in which they are
underrepresented, including construction trades, auto repair and
truck driving.
</P>
<P>
   --Home Care Associates of Philadelphia increased its pool of
applicants by purchasing 10 cars for employees to use to get to and
from job assignments.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan said that even with the strong economy and low
unemployment, swift technological changes mean American businesses
and workers will continue to face insecurity unless worker training
opportunities keep pace.
</P>
<P>
   ''The rapidity of innovation and the unpredictability of the
directions it may take imply a need for considerable investment in
human capital,'' Greenspan said.
</P>
<P>
   Businesses should not expect academic institutions alone to
create the pool of skilled workers they need, he said. Business
partnerships with community colleges and public agencies,
''distance learning'' over the Internet and corporate universities
play an increasingly important role, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Department of Labor: http://www.dol.gov
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan speech text:
http://www.federalreserve.gov/boarddocs/speeches/2000
</P>
</TEXT>
