<P>
   Motorola Shares Sink
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Investors dismissed a strong first-quarter
performance by Motorola Inc. and sent shares tumbling almost 18
percent today after the company warned that lower prices for mobile
phones were squeezing profits and would cause it to miss
second-quarter earnings expectations. Shares in the world's No. 2
maker of cellular phones were down 27 to 124. Motorola said profits
for the three months ending March 31 were up 144 percent on booming
sales of both cellular phones and semiconductor products. The
results beat analysts' expectations by a penny.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan: More Job Training Needed
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan said
today that despite the strong economy and low unemployment, rapid
technological changes mean there must be improvements in job
training if U.S. businesses and workers are to avoid insecurites.
Addressing an all-day conference on job skills, hosted by the Labor
Department on the campus of Howard University, the central bank
chairman also said, however, that fears that workers would be
displaced by new technology have proven largely unfounded.
</P>
<P>
   Study Finds Oil Prices Will Fall
</P>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Increased OPEC oil production and a mild winter
that eased consumer demand for heating oil are contributing to at
least temporary relief from painfully high crude prices, a
respected industry study said today. Oil prices have fallen since
OPEC members agreed last month to open the spigots on exports,
adding 500,000 new barrels per day and giving refineries an
incentive to buy more of the oil they need to make gasoline, the
International Energy Agency reported. However, any relief at the
pump for motorists in oil-importing nations could be brief, the
study said, noting that even more oil will be needed during the
peak driving season in industrialized nations.
</P>
<P>
   Oil Cos. Plan Procurement Exchange
</P>
<P>
   DALLAS (AP) -- Fourteen of the largest oil and petrochemical
companies plan to launch an electronic exchange to link buyers and
suppliers of goods and services. The 14 companies spend more than
$125 billion each year on procurement, they said in a joint
announcement today. Other industries, including transportation,
have recently announced similar procurement exchanges, designed to
improve efficiency and supply-chain management. An independent
company would be created to own and operate the exchange. The
founding members range from Royal Dutch-Shell Group of Cos., to BP
Amoco PLC, to The Dow Chemical Co.,
</P>
<P>
   Group Rips Microsoft on Standards
</P>
<P>
   SEATTLE (AP) -- The latest version of Microsoft Corp.'s Web
browser, due out later this year, does not adequately support the
software standards on which the World Wide Web was built, the head
of a nonprofit Web developer group said today. Jeffrey Zeldman,
head of the Web Standards Project, said that Internet Explorer
version 5.5, which will be bundled with Microsoft's upcoming
Windows Millennium operating system, will introduce a number of
new, proprietary technologies, but has yet to properly implement
the standards that developers use when creating Web-based
applications or building pages.
</P>
<P>
   Chase Manhattan Buying Fleming
</P>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Chase Manhattan Corp. is paying $7.6 billion in
cash and stock for Robert Fleming Holdings Ltd., a British
investment bank and asset management group, in a bid to help it
become a bigger player in global investment banking. Chase, the
third-largest U.S. bank with $406.1 billion in assets as of the end
of 1999, has agreed to pay $4.1 billion in cash and $3.5 billion in
common stock for Robert Fleming, one of Britain's last independent
financial companies. The deal requires regulatory approval.
</P>
<P>
   Scripps' 1Q Earnings Rise
</P>
<P>
   CINCINNATI (AP) -- The E.W. Scripps Co.'s first-quarter earnings
increased by 5 percent to $33.6 million, propelled by fast-growing
revenues at Home &AMP; Garden Television and the Food Network. The
earnings were equivalent to 43 cents per share and included
expenses from the company's venture capital funds and gains from
sold-off operations. Without those one-time factors, earnings would
have been 45 cents a share. In the same quarter a year ago, Scripps
earned $32 million, or 40 cents per share. Revenues increased 9
percent to $410.9 million from $376.3 million a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Newspaper Settles Immigrants' Suit
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- The Atlanta Journal-Constitution agreed to pay
more than $80,000 in back pay and penalties to settle charges it
discriminated against two immigrants by asking for extra
documentation during hiring. Under the settlement reached yesterday
with the U.S. Justice Department, the newspaper hired the two, who
had earlier been denied jobs after the company refused to accept
their valid documentation. It also agreed to pay them $4,996 in
back pay, correct hiring policies, receive training from the
Justice Department and pay $76,925 in civil penalties. John
Mallott, the newspaper's general manager, said it cooperated fully
with the Justice Department when the situation was brought to its
attention.
</P>
<P>
   Delta To Start Santiago Flights
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- Delta Air Lines said today it will begin flying
to Santiago, Chile, on Nov. 1 as it continues to expand its Latin
American operations. The flights, on Boeing 767 jumbo jets, will be
from Delta's main hub in Atlanta. The airline is also seeking
government permission to begin serving Bogota, Colombia; Buenos
Aires, Argentina; and Montevideo, Uruguay.
</P>
<P>
   Europe Stocks Close Mostly Lower
</P>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Telecommunications and technology shares dragged
down European bourses today. The Dow Jones Euro Stoxx Index was
down 107.9 points at 5,174.4. The Dow Jones Stoxx Index of shares
in European companies fell 7.92 points to 384.96. Some analysts
said they were worried by the lack of volume in recent trading, and
noted many investors seemed to be waiting on the sidelines. In
domestic markets, London's FTSE-100 Share Index fell 2.3 percent to
6,379 as investors bailed out of high tech stocks. Frankfurt's
Xetra DAX Index fell 0.9 percent to 7,442.66. Milan's MIBtel Index,
heavily weighed in technology stocks, experienced losses of 2.3
percent today to 30,673.
</P>
