<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Allegations Prompt Bush Criticism  </HEADLINE>
By CHRIS WILLIAMS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- A church-run home for troubled teen-agers
has been accused of abuse, prompting criticism of Gov. George W.
Bush's push to exempt such religious child care centers from some
state oversight.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has encouraged faith-based groups to provide alternatives
to social services traditionally provided by the government. He
pushed for a law in 1997 that gave church child care centers a
separate licensing procedure from other businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Two people have been arrested in connection with abuse
allegations at the Roloff Homes, run by People's Baptist Church in
Corpus Christi. The center is one of six religious youth facilities
approved under the 1997 law.
</P>
<P>
   Critics worry that church-run centers may not face as many
inspections as government programs would and say their records are
not open to public scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   ''The problem is that there are no accountability measures,''
said Samantha Smoot, executive director of the Texas Freedom
Network, which monitors the religious right. ''They feel they are
protected from regulator oversight.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush is calling for a full investigation of the abuse
allegations.
</P>
<P>
   Roloff Homes superintendent Allen Smith, 42, was arrested on
Friday on charges of unlawfully restraining and injuring two men,
ages 18 and 17, last month. He is free on a $10,000 bond. His
lawyer, Grant Jones, said he would be cleared because state law
gives custodial care facilities the right to use force in some
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Rev. Wiley Cameron Sr., pastor of People's Baptist and chief
executive of the Roloff Homes, was arrested on charges of failing
to provide records requested by a grand jury. His lawyers provided
the records shortly afterward and Cameron was released. No charges
were filed.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators were not sure if the 17-year-old man allegedly
injured was staying in one of the adult homes on the 500-acre
property, or one of the homes reserved for minors.
</P>
<P>
   Only the homes for juvenile boys and girls received the
alternative accreditation. Nueces County Sheriff Larry Olivarez
said deputies are investigating seven other allegations of abuse in
the adult homes.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Department of Protective and Regulatory Services is
investigating the allegations regarding the two men, said agency
spokeswoman Marla Sheely. The Roloff Homes are also appealing a
previous negative finding against its operation, she said,
declining to elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Under the 1997 law, the state approves private, faith-based
accrediting bodies that can then license individual child-care
providers. Only one accrediting body, the Texas Association of
Christian Child-Care Agencies Inc., has been approved.
</P>
<P>
   David Blaser, president of the association, said it forces the
six child-care groups its regulates to follow the same standards as
those licensed by the state, including submitting to periodic
inspections.
</P>
<P>
   However, several child-care advocates said the directors of most
child care centers do not also sit on the boards of their
regulators, as Cameron does with Blaser's association.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Noble, an attorney for Texans Care for Children, a
nonprofit group, said the arrangement looked like a conflict of
interest. ''I think that is sort of obvious,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-11-00 1754 </TRAILER>
