<HEADLINE> FBI Moves on Stewart Investigation  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANFORD, Fla. (AP) -- The FBI executed search warrants at Sunjet
Aviation Inc. on Tuesday as part of its investigation into the
Learjet crash in October that killed golfer Payne Stewart and five
others.
</P>
<P>
   ''This was in connection with an ongoing investigation into
possible violations of federal laws pertaining to maintenance and
record keeping,'' said agent Brian Kensel.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI served the warrants on three buildings and four aircraft
at SunJet's facilities at Orlando Sanford Airport.
</P>
<P>
   Kensel said authorities confiscated a number of Sunjet records,
though he could not say how many.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 25, 1999, Stewart's plane crashed into a South Dakota
pasture four hours after it left Orlando on a flight to Texas,
flying 1,400 miles apparently on autopilot before it ran out of
fuel.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials suspect the jet lost cabin pressure soon
after taking off, causing all six on board to die or lose
consciousness from lack of oxygen.
</P>
<P>
   No one at Sunjet answered phone calls early Tuesday evening
seeking comment.
</P>
