<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former female ABC sportscaster alleges discrimination  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY NEUMEISTER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- A 52-year-old, two-time Olympic gold medalist
who set 18 world swimming records before setting out on a 30-year
broadcasting career has sued ABC Sports, saying she was
discriminated against because of her age.
</P>
<P>
   Donna deVarona filed the $50 million lawsuit in U.S. District
Court in Manhattan late Monday, saying ABC terminated her most
recent employment with ABC Sports because of her age and gender.
</P>
<P>
   ABC responded to the lawsuit with a statement, saying: ''As a
result of the change in events covered by ABC Sports, including the
loss of the Olympics, deVarona's role had diminished greatly over
the years.
</P>
<P>
   ''Ms. deVarona and her representatives were advised of this fact
over the years and she was encouraged to look for work elsewhere.
We believe Ms. deVarona was treated fairly and that this suit has
no merit,'' the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   In the lawsuit, deVarona alleged ABC signed her to a free-lance
agreement as a sportscaster in 1991 and then treated her in an
''intentional, calculated, callous and opportunistic'' way to
appeal to a younger audience.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit said she was frequently frustrated by discriminatory
conduct during her initial broadcasting stint from 1965 through
1976, when she quit because she was ''unable to break the
discriminatory barriers facing a pioneering female sports
broadcaster.''
</P>
<P>
   She later returned to ABC, serving in 1980 as the first female
host of Olympic coverage at the games in Moscow and in 1983 as a
sportcaster and as an assistant to then-President of ABC Sports and
News Roone Arledge, a job she said she was reluctant to take
because of past discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   After signing the 1991 contract, deVarona began receiving fewer
assignments, often of inferior quality, and was paid less as ABC
Sports tried to reach younger television viewers with younger
sportscasters, the lawsuit said.
</P>
<P>
   She was advised by ABC executives that her age was detrimental
to her career advancement, the lawsuit said.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, it added, ABC Sports executives told her as she
pitched one of her programming ideas that the sports department was
focusing ''on younger demographics for all sports.''
</P>
<P>
   She said a woman who was a former vice president of ABC Sports
programming told her ABC Sports was eager to recapture the ''young
18 to 39 male market'' and that she should consider looking for
work elsewhere because her age was catching up to her.
</P>
<P>
   DeVarona began her sportscasting career at age 17 when she
agreed after the 1964 Tokyo Olympics to participate in a live
telecast at the Senior Men's National Swimming and Diving
Championships.
</P>
<P>
   Subsequently, she covered ABC's Summer Olympic telecasts in
1968, 1972, 1976 and 1984 as well as Winter Olympic telecasts in
1984, 1988 and 1994.
</P>
<P>
   By 1986, deVarona was working as an on-air host, writer and
producer and in 1991 won her first Emmy as a producer for a Special
Olympics presentation.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, she was the lead reporter covering the Winter Olympics
ice skating battle between Nancy Kerrigan and Tonya Harding.
</P>
<P>
   Other assignments sometimes included the Indy 500, the Super
Bowl, figure skating, gymnastics, track and field and the New York
City Marathon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-11-00 1802 </TRAILER>
