<DOCNO> APW20000411.0192 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Holocaust Historian Lost Libel Suit  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Historian David Irving, the author of nearly 30
books, disputes that the systematic slaughter of millions of Jews
in gas chambers at Nazi concentration camps ever took place.
</P>
<P>
   Irving argues that killing 6 million Jews during World War II
would have been logistically impossible and claims more people died
in Allied bombing raids than in concentration camps.
</P>
<P>
   The 62-year-old Briton, who lost a libel suit Tuesday, also
argued that most fatalities in concentration camps were due to
disease and starvation, not poison gas, and that the British made
up the accounts of the gas chambers as anti-German propaganda.
</P>
<P>
   In public statements, Irving claimed there were no gas chambers
at Auschwitz. But during a hearing on his libel suit, which a
British judge dismissed Tuesday, Irving conceded that gassing of
Jews had taken place ''on some scale.''
</P>
<P>
   But he continued to cast doubt on many pieces of evidence of the
Holocaust, including the diary of Anne Frank. He also claimed that
Adolf Hitler opposed the liquidation of the Jews and did not know
about the ''Final Solution'' until 1943.
</P>
<P>
   Irving was born in the southern English county of Essex in 1938,
the son of a naval commander and writer. He developed a fascination
with Germany and as a young man spent a year laboring in the Ruhr
steelworks in West Germany before returning to England to write
historical articles.
</P>
<P>
   Irving sued U.S. scholar Deborah Lipstadt and her publisher,
Penguin Books, over a 1994 book that he said damaged his academic
reputation and accused him of playing down the horrors of the
Holocaust. He seemed to revel in the controversy that followed.
</P>
<P>
   ''My views are independent and sometimes unorthodox, but never
antidemocratic,'' he told the High Court. ''I am not
anti-Semitic.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-11-00 1805 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000411.0193 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Big Movers in the Stock Market  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks that moved substantially or traded
heavily Tuesday on the New York Stock Exchange and Nasdaq Stock
Market.
</P>
<P>
NYSE
</P>
<P>
Motorola Inc., down 26} at 123{
</P>
<P>
   After posting a strong profit report late Monday, Motorola said
in a conference call today that operating profits in its cellular
phone division will come under pressure in coming quarters because
of falling prices and rising advertising costs, particularly in
Europe.
</P>
<P>
Rite Aid Corp., up 1| at 7 5/16
</P>
<P>
   The drug store chain received a commitment from Citibank N.A.
for a $1 billion credit facility. Also, a principal lender, J.P.
Morgan, agreed to convert $200 million of existing bank debt into
Rite Aid common stock at a price of $5.50 each. The transactions
will relieve some of the struggling company's debt problems.
</P>
<P>
Genrad Inc., down 3 3/16 at 10
</P>
<P>
   The company said it expects to earn 6 cents to 8 cents per share
in the first quarter, below analysts' forecasts of 15 cents per
share. The company, a hardware and software provider, cited higher
prices of components.
</P>
<P>
Station Casinos Inc., up 2 5/16 at 27 5/16
</P>
<P>
   The company earned 53 cents per share in the first quarter,
reversing a loss of 11 cents per share in the first quarter of
1999. Station Casinos owns and operates casinos and hotels.
</P>
<P>
NASDAQ
</P>
<P>
Biogen Inc., down 12 at 53
</P>
<P>
   The company posted operating earnings of 41 cents a share, below
analysts' forecasts of 43 cents per share. Biogen said overseas
sales of Avonex, its flagship drug, slipped amid seasonal weakness
and price declines. PaineWebber and Prudential Securities cut their
ratings on Biogen stock.
</P>
<P>
ViroPharma Inc., down 48{ at 23\
</P>
<P>
   In three late-stage trials, the company's drug pleconaril failed
to meet objectives. The drug was intended to treat the common cold
and viral meningitis. J.P. Morgan analyst Franklin Berger said the
results make it doubtful that pleconaril will be commercially
viable.
</P>
<P>
Rare Hospitality International Inc., up 4 21/32 at 27 11/16
</P>
<P>
   The restaurant franchiser expects to post first-quarter
operating earnings of 55 cents per share, up 62 percent last year's
first quarter. The company said it saw strong growth in its
LongHorn Steakhouse, Bugaboo Creek and Capital Grille units.
</P>
