<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sens. Push Transplant Proposal  </HEADLINE>
By JENNIFER LOVEN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A bipartisan group of senators hinted Tuesday
they would block any legislation that allows the nation's limited
supply of donated organs to continue to be distributed to the
closest transplant patients rather than the sickest.
</P>
<P>
   The group, led by Sens. Peter Fitzgerald, R-Ill., and Charles
Schumer, D-N.Y., unveiled a proposal that would base organ
distribution on medical need and require broader sharing of organs
among geographic areas.
</P>
<P>
   The bill also would strengthen the Department of Health and
Human Services' authority over the private company, United Network
for Organ Sharing, it hired to run the distribution system.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal largely mirrors changes the Clinton administration
has sought.
</P>
<P>
   Under the current system, patients who live in the same area as
donors get the first crack at organs, even if a sicker patient
lives just outside the area.
</P>
<P>
   ''Your zip code has a lot more to do with your receiving an
organ than your state of health,'' said Sen. Dick Durbin, D-Ill.,
who joined Fitzgerald, Schumer and Sen. Rick Santorum, R-Pa.
''That's just wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   United Network and many transplant centers -- particularly
smaller hospitals -- fear eliminating geographic barriers would
siphon away locally donated organs to other centers and jeopardize
their programs.
</P>
<P>
   At stake is which side should have the power to write rules
governing the distribution of organs, and what those rules should
be. Rather than a partisan issue, it generally pits lawmakers from
major recipient states that have large transplant centers against
those from high-donor states where patients now get transplants
fairly quickly.
</P>
<P>
   The Fitzgerald-Schumer measure is meant as an alternative to a
bipartisan effort led by Sen. Bill Frist, R-Tenn., a former heart
and lung transplant surgeon.
</P>
<P>
   Frist's still-evolving proposal, scheduled for committee action
on Wednesday, would allow the transplant network to write
allocation policy. But if Health and Human Services and the private
contractor cannot agree, an expert committee would make the final
policy decisions, based on a set of guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   HHS has not signed on to the proposal because it wants those
guidelines to explicitly call for broader sharing of organs over
larger geographic areas -- as the Fitzgerald-Schumer bill would do.
</P>
<P>
   Frist met Tuesday with HHS Secretary Donna Shalala and Sen.
Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., to try and work out the final details of a
compromise. No deal was reached, although Senate staff planned to
continue talking Tuesday night. On Wednesday, the Senate Health,
Education, Labor and Pensions Committee was set to consider Frist's
bill, with or without a compromise.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the House has backed United Network, passing
legislation that would strip HHS of its authority to set policy and
overturn its proposed new rules. The Clinton administration has
promised a veto.
</P>
<P>
   The senators said they would wait to see what Frist's final bill
looks like before deciding on a strategy. But they said that
anything that does not increase public accountability is
unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will pass a good bill in the United States Senate, or we
will pass no bill,'' Santorum said.
</P>
<P>
   More than 4,800 people die each year -- about 13 per day --
waiting for organ transplants. There currently are 68,530 people
waiting for transplants.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: United Network for Organ Sharing:
http://www.unos.org
</P>
<P>
   HHS Division of Transplantation: http://www.hrsa.gov/osp/dot
</P>
</TEXT>
