<HEADLINE> Bond Prices Fall on Blue-Chip Rally  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Government bonds tumbled Tuesday as money flowed
into corporate and other categories of bonds as well as into
blue-chip stocks. Yields rose sharply from Monday's 11-month lows.
</P>
<P>
   The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond plunged 1 15/32
points, or $14.69 per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves
in the opposite direction, shot up to 5.76 percent from 5.66
percent late Monday, which had been the lowest level since May 3,
1999.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, Wall Street strategists have been reminding
investors that many old-line companies in the energy, financial and
consumer sectors may reward investors seeking stable, growing
profits. The Dow industrials rose more than 100 points Tuesday to
its highest close since Jan. 20.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, with long-term Treasury yields sinking, traders
sought higher returns from other categories of bonds, including
corporate debt and agencies such as Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac.
</P>
<P>
   In the broader bond market, short-term notes fell 5/32 point to
7/32 point, while intermediate notes fell ] point to } point,
reported Bridge Telerate, a financial information service.
</P>
<P>
   Yields on three-month Treasury bills were 5.84 percent as the
discount fell 0.01 percentage point from Monday's auction to 5.67
percent. Six-month yields were 6.10 percent, as the discount fell
0.03 percentage point from the weekly auction to 5.83 percent.
One-year yields were 6.12 percent as the discount rose 0.02
percentage point from late Monday to 5.79 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the
discount is the interest at which they are sold.
</P>
<P>
   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between
banks, fell to 5.75 percent from 6.06 percent Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively
traded municipal bonds fell 1/16 at 95 29/32. The average yield to
maturity was 5.91 percent, up from 5.90 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
