<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Falls 132.30; Dow Up 100.52  </HEADLINE>
By EILEEN GLANTON, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The Nasdaq composite index fell sharply Tuesday,
wiping out all of its gains for the year as volatile biotechnology
stocks became the latest high-tech segment to falter. Blue-chip
issues benefited once again from the technology slump, and the Dow
Jones industrials reached their highest levels since January.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index fell 132.30 to close at 4,055.90. The
choppy trading that has characterized the market in the past two
weeks returned, with the Nasdaq paring an early loss of 178 points
to fewer than 10 before heading lower again.
</P>
<P>
   After weeks of tumultuous selling, the Nasdaq is now
fractionally lower for the year and nearly 20 percent below its
peak of 5,048.62, which it reached March 10. Still, the index is up
a stunning 56 percent from a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were mixed. The resurgent Dow Jones
industrial average rose 100.52 to close at 11,287.08, its highest
level since Jan. 20, when it closed at 11,351.30.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 fell 3.87 to 1,500.59.
</P>
<P>
   ''The rotation continues,'' said Larry Rice, chief investment
officer at Josephthal &AMP; Co., referring to investors' turn away from
high-tech and back to old reliable stocks like the Dow issues.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's fast and it's volatile, but it's really becoming the
norm.''
</P>
<P>
   Two downbeat earnings reports derailed the technology sector.
Biogen, which has stronger earnings than most biotech companies,
said it earned 41 cents a share in the first quarter, below Wall
Street expectations of 43 cents. Biogen cited a slowdown in demand
for its multiple sclerosis treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Biogen fell 12 to 53 and dragged down other biotech firms.
Genentech tumbled 20 to 136{.
</P>
<P>
   Also Tuesday, Motorola said it expects second-quarter and
full-year 2000 earnings to fall short of analysts' views due to
price cuts that are shrinking profit margins.
</P>
<P>
   The warning from Motorola, which makes cellular phones and
semiconductors, deflated enthusiasm from its strong first-quarter
earnings report, released late Monday. Motorola shares plummeted
26| to 123|, dragging many other technology companies with it.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's some concern that what's hurting Motorola could affect
the rest of the techs,'' said William Meehan, chief market analyst
at Cantor Fitzgerald.
</P>
<P>
   Meehan said nervous investors are continuing to shed technology
stocks that may not be worthy of their valuations, which are
generally much higher relative to earnings than the industrial
stocks that dominate the Dow.
</P>
<P>
   ''More than a few portfolio managers found themselves
overexposed to technology last quarter,'' he said. ''Some are
getting out, and some are just sitting on their hands waiting for
the market to settle down.''
</P>
<P>
   Some high-profile Nasdaq stocks fell for no fundamental reason,
analysts said. Cisco Systems fell 2 9/16 to 70, Oracle fell 5[ to
77] and JDS Uniphase fell 7 15/16 to 102 3/16.
</P>
<P>
   The corporate earnings reporting season begins in earnest this
week, and while profit growth for most companies is expected to be
quite strong, investors are proving unwilling to tolerate any
disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   In recent sessions, Wall Street strategists have been reminding
investors that many old-line companies in the energy, financial and
consumer sectors may reward investors seeking stable, growing
profits. Tuesday, General Electric gained 1 15/16 to 161] and Alcoa
rose 2 11/16 to 70].
</P>
<P>
   But Rice pointed out that breadth, the difference between the
numbers of rising and falling stocks, remains very narrow, with
just a handful of Dow issues making sharp gains Tuesday. Most
investors are continuing to shift money from sector to sector on a
daily basis, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The narrowness of the rally in blue-chips is disconcerting,''
he said. ''It shows you just how nervous the market is.''
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 10-to-9 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume totaled 1.19 billion
shares, compared with 1.05 billion in the previous session. On the
Nasdaq, decliners led by a 3-to-2 margin.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 8.53 to 510.13.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 0.5 percent.
Germany's DAX index fell 1.0 percent, Britain's FT-SE 100 lost 2.4
percent, and France's CAC-40 fell 1.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
