<HEADLINE> Dollar Edges Higher Vs. Currencies  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar edged higher against other major
currencies on Tuesday, but traders remained hesitant before some
major economic reports and financial policy meetings later in the
week that could move the market.
</P>
<P>
   In late New York trading, dollar was quoted at 107.09 Japanese
yen, up from 106.47 yen at the same point on Monday, while the euro
was quoted at 95.97 cents, down from 96.16 cents.
</P>
<P>
   For the second day in a row, there were no government reports on
the U.S. economy to guide the market, which has been handcuffed in
advance of the monthly inflation readings due on Thursday and
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Investors were also said to be worried about Thursday's meeting
by the European central bank, which could produce another
euro-boosting increase in short-term interest rates, and a weekend
gathering by the Group of Seven industrial nations, where officials
are expected to discuss the ongoing threat of a strong yen on
Japan's fragile economy.
</P>
<P>
   In other trading Tuesday, the dollar was quoted at 1.6397 Swiss
francs, up from 1.6382 on Friday, and 1.4638 Canadian dollars, up
from 1.4612. The British pound rose to $1.5848 compared with late
Friday's quote of $1.5848.
</P>
<P>
   The currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are
no longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed
rate. Based on Tuesday's euro rate, the dollar was worth: 2.0376
German marks, up from 2.0344 on Monday; 6.8336 French francs, up
from 6.8229; and 2,017.18 Italian lire, up from 2,014.01 lire.
</P>
</TEXT>
