<HEADLINE> CSX Corp. President Resigns  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   RICHMOND, Va. (AP) -- CSX Corp. said Tuesday that its president,
Ronald J. Conway, has resigned and his duties will be assumed by
John W. Snow, the company's chairman and chief executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   CSX, headquartered in Richmond, operates the largest rail
network in the eastern United States and also provides intermodal,
container shipping and contract logistics services.
</P>
<P>
   Conway, who joined CSX from Conrail in 1998 and was named
president in 1999, resigned to pursue other interests, the company
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are grateful to Ron for his contributions, most notably for
leading CSX Transportation through the complex integration of
Conrail properties into our network,'' Snow said. ''I am pleased
that he will be staying with us as a consultant.''
</P>
<P>
   Conway's resignation comes as CSX faces a financial squeeze from
its takeover of Conrail.
</P>
<P>
   It has high debt and has seen profits tumble as a result of
freight congestion and other problems stemming from the merger.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, federal officials earlier this month reported
serious track defects on several key CSX routes as well as a lack
of quality control in the company's track-maintenance and
inspection programs.
</P>
</TEXT>
