<HEADLINE> Takeover Report Lifts Ben &AMP; Jerry's  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTPELIER, Vt. (AP) -- Ben &AMP; Jerry's stock price rose Tuesday
following a report on attempts to buy out the company built on
quirky ice cream flavors and social activism.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Ben &AMP; Jerry's Homemade Inc. were up $1.18} to $34.93}
at 4 p.m. Tuesday on the Nasdaq Stock Market. The shares have
surged nearly 70 percent since the company first disclosed it was a
possible acquisition target in early December.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, The Wall Street Journal reported that a group of
investors who follow a socially responsible agenda, led by company
co-founder Ben Cohen, had pulled out of the bidding for the South
Burlington company.
</P>
<P>
   That development appeared to leave two large competitors working
against each other to buy the company.
</P>
<P>
   None of the principals in the several deals being considered by
the Ben &AMP; Jerry's board would comment Tuesday. Ben &AMP; Jerry's
officials refused to confirm reports the company's board was
meeting Tuesday to consider the remaining offers.
</P>
<P>
   Dreyer's Grand Ice Cream Inc. of Oakland, Calif., and Unilever
NV, a Dutch and English conglomerate that's also in the ice cream
novelty business, have both made offers to the Ben &AMP; Jerry's board
to buy the company.
</P>
<P>
   Unilever also was part of the group that teamed up with Cohen in
a bid organized through the Meadowbrook Lane Capital to buy the
company and take it private.
</P>
<P>
   That $38 a share offer was withdrawn late last week, in part
because it would have saddled Ben &AMP; Jerry's with too much debt, the
Journal reported, citing people familiar with the situation.
</P>
<P>
   The offer was withdrawn after Dreyer's, which also produces a
premium ice cream under the trade names Edy's Grand and Edy's
Dreamery, sweetened its buyout offer to $35 to $38 in stock, the
newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
   Meadowbrook hoped to make another bid involving Social Venture
Network members and Unilever might be interested in reconfiguring
that coalition, the Journal said.
</P>
<P>
   Unilever, which makes such ice cream brands as Breyer's and
Klondike, still has a separate bid for $43 a share in cash for Ben
&AMP; Jerry's.
</P>
</TEXT>
