<HEADLINE> Ford CEO Received $10M in 1999  </HEADLINE>
By JUSTIN HYDE, 
V0991-----
r f *1310AP-Ford-Salaries     04-11 0708
*1310 AP-Ford-Salaries,0707   
Ford CEO Received $10M in 1999   
By JUSTIN HYDE
AP Auto Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT (AP) -- With sales and profits at record highs, Ford
Motor Co. has rewarded its top executive with a boost in pay.
</P>
<P>
   Ford said Tuesday that president and chief executive Jac Nasser
was paid $10.2 million in salary, bonus and dividends in 1999.
That's a 48 percent raise from his $6.9 million package in 1998,
when he was head of Ford's automotive operations.
</P>
<P>
   Nasser also received stock options worth $7 million, cashed in
$802,740 in previously granted options and received $2.9 million in
stock under a long-term executive incentive program.
</P>
<P>
   The 1999 pay packages for Ford's top executives were disclosed
in the automaker's annual proxy statement filed with the U.S.
Securities and Exchange Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Top executive pay at Ford is determined in part by formulas that
calculate how the automaker met financial and management goals for
the year or, in the case of stock options, over several years.
</P>
<P>
   Compensation can vary widely from year to year based on the
amount of previously granted stock options the executive decides to
cash in and the extent to which the company's financial performance
affects the long-term incentive plans.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, retiring Ford chairman Alex Trotman cashed in $30.1
million in stock options on top of $14.9 million in salary, bonus
and dividends.
</P>
<P>
   In its proxy, Ford's executive compensation committee said Ford
met most of its financial goals for the year. In 1999, Ford earned
$7.2 billion, or $5.86 per share, up 22 percent over operating
earnings of $5.9 billion, or $4.72 a share, in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But the committee also said compensation was reduced slightly
because the company failed to meet an unspecified target for
quality, based on vehicle warranty repairs and customer
satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   Nasser holds $20.2 million in Ford stock options that he can
cash in at any time, as well as $10.5 million in options that he
cannot exercise yet.
</P>
<P>
   Ford Chairman William Clay Ford Jr. was paid $1.5 million in
restricted stock options for his job as chairman. Ford is the
great-grandson of founder Henry Ford.
</P>
<P>
   The other Ford executives and their reported compensation
include:
</P>
<P>
   -- W. Wayne Booker, vice chairman, who received $3.5 million in
salary, bonus and dividends, as well as $2.5 million in stock under
the long-term incentive plan. Booker also exercised options for a
gain of $735,964 and received new options worth $1.75 million.
</P>
<P>
   -- John M. Devine, Ford's former executive vice president who
retired Sept. 1, received $3 million in salary, bonus and
dividends, $2.6 million in stock under the long-term incentive plan
and new options worth $1.75 million. Devine exercised no options.
</P>
<P>
   -- Richard Parry-Jones, group vice president for product
development, received $1.8 million in salary, bonus and dividends;
$1.2 million in stock under the long-term incentive plan; exercised
options for a gain of $380,315 and received new options worth
$876,500.
</P>
<P>
   -- Peter J. Pestillo, vice chairman, received $3.3 million in
salary, bonus and dividends; $2 million in stock under the
long-term incentive plan; exercised options for a gain of $155,687
and received new options worth $1.75 million.
</P>
<P>
   -- Robert L. Rewey, group vice president for marketing, sales and
service, received $2.5 million in salary, bonus and dividends; $2
million in stock under the long-term incentive plan; exercised
options for a gain of $3.1 million, and received new options worth
$1 million.
</P>
<P>
   General Motors Corp. said last week that chairman and CEO Jack
Smith was paid $6.9 million in salary, bonus and dividends, and
cashed in $6 million in stock options. He was also given $5.25
million in stock under a long-term executive incentive plan and was
granted an estimated $7.9 million in stock options.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler AG does not file a proxy statement with the SEC,
since it is incorporated in Germany.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
