<HEADLINE> Media General Profits Surge in 1Q  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   RICHMOND, Va. (AP) -- Media General's profits jumped 27 percent
in the first quarter on strong growth in its publishing and
television operations, the company said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The company earned $14.4 million, or 55 cents per share, for the
first three months of the year, up from $11.3 million, or 42 cents
per share, in the same period the previous year.
</P>
<P>
   The earnings matched analysts' projections for the quarter and
reflect a $13.6 million cut in interest expense and an $8.2 million
increase in interest income, both aided by the October sale of the
company's cable television division.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue increased 4 percent, to $199 million from $191.8 million
in the first quarter of 1999. Television revenues increased 9
percent, to $40.4 million from $37 million, and publishing revenues
climbed to $132 million from $127.9 million the previous year, up 3
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The newsprint division, however, posted an operating loss of
$5.3 million for the first quarter compared with income of $3.1
million for the same period a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Media General's chairman and chief executive, J. Stewart Bryan
III, said he expects that newsprint operations will show an
improvement as market conditions change.
</P>
<P>
   ''The major (newsprint) producers are trying to raise their
prices this month, and if they are successful, the performance of
our newsprint division should improve substantially in the second
half of the year,'' Bryan said.
</P>
<P>
   Media General is an independent, publicly owned communications
company with interests in newspapers, television, interactive
media, recycled newsprint production and diversified information
services primarily in the southeastern United States.
</P>
</TEXT>
