<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cold, Meningitis Drug Disappoints  </HEADLINE>
By DANIEL Q. HANEY, AP Medical Editor
<TEXT>
<P>
   A drug that appeared promising as a cure for the common cold and
viral meningitis showed disappointing results in three large-scale
studies released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Word of the results released by ViroPharma Inc., the makers of
pleconaril, sent its stock price plummeting, but officials of the
small company said they are confident they can prove the drug
works.
</P>
<P>
   Pleconaril has been closely watched because of early studies
suggesting it is effective against both the common cold and viral
meningitis.
</P>
<P>
   While the just-completed studies offer hints that pleconaril
eases symptoms, they failed to produce the kind of clear-cut
evidence of effectiveness that is usually needed to win Food and
Drug Administration approval.
</P>
<P>
   ''We continue to have great confidence in pleconaril, especially
for treating viral respiratory disease'' -- the common cold, chief
executive Claude Nash told investors and analysts in a conference
call Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Investors disagreed, sending shares of ViroPharma down $48.50 to
$23.25 on the Nasdaq Stock Market.
</P>
<P>
   In an earlier study, pleconaril shortened the duration of a
common cold by about 3{ days. This time, using a somewhat different
definition of a cold's conclusion, the drug shortened the misery
from 9.4 days to 7.7 days.
</P>
<P>
   In the new study, pleconaril also significantly reduced users'
nasal secretions and coughing and improved their sleep.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think if pleconaril continues to show some benefit for
picornavirus-related colds, eventually it may well have a role,''
said Dr. Ronald Turner, a cold expert at the Medical University of
South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Mark A. McKinlay, ViroPharma's research director, said the
Exton, Pa., company expects to start two more large cold studies
this year and seek FDA approval for such uses by 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The latest cold study was directed by Dr. Frederick G. Hayden of
the University of Virginia, who was in Argentina and could not be
reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, the company said it hoped to get pleconaril on the
market for treating viral meningitis by the end of this year. But
now it says that is likely to be delayed.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the new studies looked at pleconaril for viral meningitis
in children and adults. Severe headache is the major symptom of the
illness, which strikes an estimated 500,000 American a year.
</P>
<P>
   In children, the drug had no significant overall effect on the
duration of headaches. The company said that was because, for
reasons they could not explain, many of the children had extremely
short bouts of illness, regardless of whether they got the
medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Pleconaril also did not seem to help much across the board in
adults, either, though it did shorten headaches from 10 days to
seven in the most severe cases.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Mark H. Sawyer of the University of California at San Diego
said many pediatricians hope the drug will win approval so it can
be used for newborns with rare, overwhelming enterovirus
infections, which were not a subject of the latest studies.
</P>
<P>
   Pleconaril appears to be potentially lifesaving in such cases,
and ''the prospect of having an antiviral drug to intervene with in
these patients is very exciting,'' Sawyer said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-11-00 1827 </TRAILER>
