<DOCNO> APW20000411.0209 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 18:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lawmakers Split Over Ethanol Issue  </HEADLINE>
By PHILIP BRASHER, AP Farm Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Farm-state lawmakers were split Tuesday over
whether Congress should repeal a clean-fuels standard that requires
gasoline sold in many cities to contain an oxygen-enhancing
additives such as MTBE and corn-based ethanol.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration last month said it planned to ban
MTBE because it has been found to be contaminating underground
water supplies and proposed that Congress eliminate the oxygenate
standard.
</P>
<P>
   To ensure a continued market for ethanol, which is more
expensive than MTBE, the administration suggested replacing the
oxygenate standard with a requirement that gasoline refiners
continue using a minimum amount of ethanol and other fuels made
from renewable resources.
</P>
<P>
   The ethanol industry risks a public backlash if the oxygenate
standard is not repealed, said Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle,
a South Dakota Democrat who backs the administration's position.
</P>
<P>
   ''Support for the oxygenate rule is guaranteed to weaken even
more over time,'' Daschle told the Senate Agriculture Committee.
</P>
<P>
   But other lawmakers say it would be a mistake for ethanol
supporters to go along with eliminating the oxygenate requirement
since it guarantees that there would be demand for ethanol when
MTBE can no longer be used.
</P>
<P>
   The oxygenate rule ''has produced astounding benefits in
reducing air pollution, and ... it makes no sense to gut the Clean
Air Act simply because one of the oxygenates -- MTBE -- is
contaminating water,'' Sen. Charles Grassley, R-Iowa, said in a
letter Tuesday to Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman.
</P>
<P>
   The ban on MTBE would raise farm income by $1 billion, or more
than 2 percent a year, if it is replaced by ethanol, according to
Agriculture Department projections.
</P>
<P>
   Congress is under pressure from Northeast states to do away with
the oxygenate standard so they don't have to use either ethanol or
MTBE. California, which is banning MTBE on its own, has asked the
Environmental Protection Agency for a waiver from the rule.
</P>
<P>
   ''The economic impact of mandating the use of ethanol in the
Northeast, California and the Gulf Coast is simply unknown,'' said
Jason Grumet, who represents the air-control agencies of eight
northeastern states.
</P>
<P>
   The 1990 Clean Air Act led to widespread use of MTBE, or methyl
tertiary butyl ether, by requiring gasoline in areas with serious
air pollution to contain at least 2 percent oxygen by weight.
</P>
<P>
   As many as 9,000 community water wells near leaking underground
storage tanks in 31 states may be affected by contamination from
MTBE, according to a recent study. MTBE is now used in one-third of
the gasoline sold in the United States, primarily in areas with
smog problems.
</P>
<P>
   The oil industry opposes both the oxygenate rule and the
proposed renewable fuels standard.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-11-00 1827 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000411.0210 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 18:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> RETRANSMITS to ADD photo tag  </HEADLINE>
By TIMOTHY WILLIAMS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- What do you do when the date of the Yankees home
opener falls on the same day as an important campaign swing to
Rochester and Buffalo? If you are Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, there's
no question: Cancel the upstate trip.
</P>
<P>
   That's right, despite slacking poll numbers and complaints from
some upstate Republicans that Giuliani is doing little to show that
he wants to represent them in the U.S. Senate, the Yankees-mad
mayor is trading Buffalo for the Bronx to take in opening day on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about it at a press conference Tuesday, Giuliani
burst out laughing and pulled on a special commemorative Yankees
cap that read ''1999 World Champions, Team of the Century.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Long before I was a politician, I was a Yankee fan, what can I
tell you? This is me. I'm a Yankee fan. I love the Yankees. I
haven't missed an opening day since I've been the mayor.''
</P>
<P>
   And where will Hillary Rodham Clinton, his rival for the U.S.
Senate and herself a self-proclaimed Yankees fan be that day? She's
opting for Buffalo, thank you very much.
</P>
<P>
   When Clinton was asked about Giuliani's schedule change, she
managed a good natured dig at the mayor's campaign and slipping
poll numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's had a tough couple of weeks. It might be good for him to
go to a game,'' Clinton said while campaigning in Albany on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's scheduling conflict arose after forecasts predicted
snow and rain for the city and baseball officials canceled
Tuesday's home opener against the Texas Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor, like all die-hard Yankees fans, waited all winter for
the game and even cleared his schedule in anticipation. This year's
opener is to include a celebration of the team's World Series
victory last year.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, the weather didn't cooperate and the mayor's schedule was
redone. He postponed appearances before a women's group in
Rochester and a fund-raiser in Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   The trip was seen as key because Giuliani has been criticized
lately for his lack of upstate campaign appearances. Recent polls
show that the mayor has surrendered his lead over Clinton and the
race has slipped into a dead heat.
</P>
<P>
   But on Tuesday, Stephen Minarik III, the Republican Party
chairman in Monroe County, which encompasses Rochester, said he
understood Giuliani's choice of a baseball game uptown instead of a
campaign event upstate.
</P>
<P>
   ''He is the mayor of the city of New York (and) the New York
Yankees are an institution within the city of New York, so let's
cut the guy some slack,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Davis, Erie County's Republican Party chairman, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's doing the right thing,'' said Davis. ''I'm a big baseball
fan, I understand. People understand. Buffalo is a Yankees town
too.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis added that the postponement of Giuliani's trip to Buffalo
gives him an opportunity to take in a home opener of his own: The
Buffalo Bisons, the Triple-A affiliate of the Cleveland Indians.
</P>
<P>
   Davis did have one minor regret. ''I wish he had invited me to
sit next to him at the Yankees game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
