<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jenny Craig Drops Lewinsky  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO (AP) -- Monica Lewinsky has been shed as a spokesmodel
by struggling weight loss business Jenny Craig Inc., which had been
criticized by some of its franchises for selecting the former White
House intern for its ads.
</P>
<P>
   Jenny Craig began running new television ads this week featuring
noncelebrity clients, and officials of the San Diego-based company
would not say whether Lewinsky will appear in future campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   ''We just want the emphasis to be on the program as opposed to
any one individual client,'' said Jenny Craig spokeswoman Jeanne
McDougall.
</P>
<P>
   Ads featuring testimonials from Lewinsky had a five-week run
that began Jan. 2. Some privately owned franchises, criticizing the
selection as inappropriate, kept running older ads rather than
using the Lewinsky campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky remains a client of Jenny Craig, but McDougall declined
to discuss specifics of the financial relationship or plans for the
future.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky was not available for comment Tuesday, McDougall said.
In addition, a call to a publicist for Lewinsky was not returned.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with USA Today, Lewinsky said that Jenny Craig's
promotional campaign might ''be a lot easier without me there.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky has been devoting attention to promoting a line of
high-end handbags. The bags, made of silk, velvet and other
fabrics, have a label on the outside that says ''Made especially
for you by Monica.''
</P>
<P>
   She first started stitching the bags while being cooped up at
home during the White House scandal in which President Clinton was
impeached on perjury and obstruction of justice charges in 1998.
The Senate voted not to remove him from office.
</P>
<P>
   Using the Jenny Craig program, Lewinsky lost 31 pounds since
last summer and has kept the weight off. The company won't provide
her current weight.
</P>
<P>
   Patti Larchet, Jenny Craig's president and chief operating
officer, told USA Today that the company might ''revisit her'' if
she reaches her new goal to lose an additional 10 or 15 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Jenny Craig has struggled in the face of a trend toward
do-it-yourself dieting. The company posted a net loss of $7.6
million last quarter and announced plans in November to close 86
underperforming weight-loss centers and trim 15 percent of the
staff at its headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   The company expects to report its latest financial earnings in
late April or early May.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
