<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 18:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Boy Tells Clinton To Break Law  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANNAPOLIS, Md. (AP) -- Standing in a throng of children,
President Clinton couldn't help but laugh at the little boy's
question: Is he still president?
</P>
<P>
   ''I have to leave in January,'' Clinton replied. He explained
that the law limits him to two terms in office.
</P>
<P>
   So the boy offered a solution: Break the law, or at least change
it so he can stay.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton roared with laughter.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can't do that. But I'll be around,'' the president said.
''I'll try to do something useful.''
</P>
<P>
   The anonymous little questioner was in a group of children who
encountered Clinton on a street outside the Maryland statehouse
Tuesday, just after the governor signed a new gun safety law that
Clinton supports.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton then ducked into the Aurora Gallery, an arts and crafts
shop, and bought a few cat pins and a ceramic candy bowl decorated
with cat figures.
</P>
<P>
   He climbed into his limousine to head back to Washington.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-11-00 1832 </TRAILER>
