<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Alleged Cancer Conspiracy Eyed  </HEADLINE>
By JUSTIN POPE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON (AP) -- Doctors in at least seven states are being
investigated for allegedly administering free samples of an
expensive cancer drug and then billing their patients' insurance
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Only one doctor has been charged in the allege scheme, but
papers filed by federal prosecutors in U.S. District Court claim
the conspiracy spread to the drug company's employees and doctors
in Massachusetts, Maine, Connecticut, Kentucky, South Carolina, New
York and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Attorney's spokeswoman Samantha Martin declined to say how
many doctors might have been involved.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors allege that the producer of the prostate cancer drug
Lupron Depot gave free samples to physicians as an inducement for
them to use the drug -- as well as ''to provide the physician with a
source of money ... to pay (any) past-due balance'' owed to the
company.
</P>
<P>
   The average cost of a monthly dose of Lupron was $566 in 1998,
according to an industry reference book. The drug, which must be
administered by a physician, is also among Medicare's largest
out-patient drug expenditures, costing the government $467 million
in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Lupron is a product of Illinois-based TAP Pharmaceuticals Inc.,
a joint venture of Abbott Labs and Takeda Chemical Industries.
</P>
<P>
   TAP spokeswoman Kim Modory on Tuesday confirmed that Lupon
marketing practices are being investigated and said the company is
cooperating. She declined further comment.
</P>
<P>
   The company had $2.5 billion in sales last year, about a third
of that from Lupron.
</P>
<P>
   In the only charges filed so far, Dr. Rodney Mannion, a
urologist in northeast Indiana, is accused of conspiracy to defraud
for allegedly accepting between $40,000 and $70,000 from insurers
billed for 60 one-month doses of the drug between 1993 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   An employee at Mannion's office said the doctor would not
comment on the allegations. Mannion's attorney did not immediately
return phone calls seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   The charge was outlined in a federal information paper, a
document often filed before a plea agreement.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted as charged, Mannion could face up to five years in
prison and a $250,000 fine. His arraignment is scheduled April 25.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-11-00 1843 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000411.0218 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tenn. Court Lifts Stay of Execution  </HEADLINE>
By MICHELLE WILLIAMS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Tennessee's first execution in 40 years
is back on track for the fourth time.
</P>
<P>
   The 6th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals on Tuesday lifted a stay
of execution for Robert Glen Coe, who a week ago was set to die by
injection for the 1979 murder and rape of 8-year-old Cary Ann
Medlin.
</P>
<P>
   The Tennessee Supreme court has set April 19 for the execution --
the fourth date set for Coe since October.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court had delayed Coe's execution to consider
motions questioning his mental competence and the state's process
for determining it. A 1986 U.S. Supreme Court ruling bars the
execution of insane inmates.
</P>
<P>
   The court on Tuesday found that Coe is competent and the state
gave him a fair competency hearing, which lasted several days and
allowed his lawyers to question mental health experts.
</P>
<P>
   ''It would serve no jurisprudential purpose to discuss these
claims any further,'' the justices wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Mickey Stout, Medlin's stepfather, said the family has grown
weary of two decades of legal wrangling, especially in the last six
months.
</P>
<P>
   Each time Coe's death was near, Cary Ann's family prepared to
leave their West Tennessee home for Nashville to witness the
execution, only to learn of a last-hour stay of execution. Stout
said the family hopes this is the last time.
</P>
<P>
   ''We'll just wait to see what goes from here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Coe's lawyers still have several appellate options. One of Coe's
lawyers, Jim Walker, wouldn't discuss which option the legal team
would choose, adding that the appeals are not meant ''in anyway to
minimize the pain and loss of Cary Ann Medlin's friends and
family.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Her death was a tragedy, but when Tennessee is seeking to
accelerate its first execution in 40 years, I do not think the
execution of a severely mentally ill man, for whom there are
substantial, lingering questions regarding his guilt, should be the
person executed,'' Walker said.
</P>
<P>
   Coe's lawyers say he becomes mentally unstable under stress, a
condition that will worsen as he nears execution. They believe once
in the death chamber, he will not be mentally competent for
execution.
</P>
<P>
   Coe, who turns 44 on Saturday, told police when he was arrested
in 1979 that he lured the girl from a church parking lot into his
car and raped her. After she told him, ''Jesus loves you,'' he said
he decided to kill her.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee has not put anyone to death since 1960. The U.S.
Supreme Court reinstated capital punishment in 1976.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-11-00 1843 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000411.0219 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 18:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Transportation plan reduces borrowing but also lacks permanentfunding  </HEADLINE>
By RALPH SIEGEL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- The Whitman administration has proposed a
system of paying for new highway and rail projects that provides
only 12 months of financing, but lawmakers on Tuesday did not seem
to mind.
</P>
<P>
   And most motorists probably will not mind either since the plan
provides a record $1 billion in transportation projects to reduce
traffic congestion, and there is no talk of raising the gasoline
tax to pay for it.
</P>
<P>
   But critics said the proposal provides only a short-term
solution for the Transportation Trust Fund, which finances the
state's projects and which in the past has been given a stable
source of revenue to pay its bills year after year.
</P>
<P>
   Assemblywoman Barbara Buono, D-Middlesex, the ranking Democrat
on the Assembly Budget Committee, said, ''I am disappointed that
the governor hasn't come up with a long range plan, that she hasn't
proposed a dedicated source of funding to fund the Transportation
Trust Fund over the long haul.''
</P>
<P>
   ''This is really for just one fiscal year, as I see it,'' Buono
said. She said she would have preferred a permanent dedication of
more gasoline and oil-products taxes over a longer term.
</P>
<P>
   While Gov. Christie Whitman's plan may be short-term, it does
have a new feature that appeals to many lawmakers, Buono added. For
the first time, Whitman is proposing to pay for more than a quarter
of the work in cash, limiting the amount that the Trust Fund
authority will have to borrow through bond issues.
</P>
<P>
   In most years, 90 percent to 95 percent of the money needed for
new projects was borrowed through the sale of bonds. In the fiscal
year beginning July 1, only 73 percent of the money needed will
have to be borrowed. The rest of the cost will be paid with $266
million in cash.
</P>
<P>
   Transportation Commissioner James Weinstein appeared before the
Budget committee for four hours Tuesday to discuss his department.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Legislature has been complaining about a too heavy
reliance on debt. It is good economic times, so there's money in
the budget, and we are making the shift,'' Weinstein said. ''If you
can (pay cash) as opposed to issuing debt, if you have that option,
then I think you are going to get support from both parties.''
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman Leonard Lance, R-Hunterdon, chairman of the budget
committee, spoke for his GOP colleagues. ''I favor pay-as-you-go to
the greatest extent possible,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For the past two decades, most of the Transportation Trust
Fund's money has been coming from the gasoline tax, but under a
1995 law most of the gas tax revenue will go to pay off existing
debts starting this year and so will be unavailable to pay for new
work.
</P>
<P>
   Because of this, many had believed a higher gas tax would be
necessary this year. Whitman proposed a 4-cent increase two years
ago to prepare for this date but it died in the Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   Weinstein on Tuesday said this option is now out of the
question.
</P>
<P>
   ''In light of what is happening with gasoline prices, there is
not any sense in talking about a gas tax,'' he said. ''There are
times to do things and there are times not to do things. This is
not a time to talk about gas tax increases.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-11-00 1848 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000411.0220 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rite Aid Stock Rises on Pact  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMP HILL, Pa. (AP) -- Rite Aid Corp.'s shares soared nearly 29
percent Tuesday after the drugstore operator announced it had a new
financing pact that its chief executive said will be key to
rebuilding the financially troubled company.
</P>
<P>
   The operator of the nation's third largest drugstore chain said
it had received a commitment for $1 billion in secured credit from
Citibank.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, it said J.P. Morgan agreed to convert $200 million
of existing bank debt into Rite Aid common stock at a price of
$5.50 each.
</P>
<P>
   After completing the transactions, Rite Aid said it will have
virtually no debt maturing prior to August 2002.
</P>
<P>
   In trading on the New York Stock Exchange, Rite Aid shares were
up $1.62{ a share at $7.31\.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Miller, who was named Rite Aid's chairman and chief
executive last December, said the new financing commitment and debt
modifications ''are a cornerstone of our turnaround plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Rite Aid said the financing will provide it with more than $600
million for general working capital purposes, repaying debt and
paying expenses.
</P>
<P>
   The $1 billion credit facility will be secured with inventory,
accounts receivable and certain other assets owned by Rite Aid
units PCS Health Systems and drugstore.com.
</P>
<P>
   Rite Aid has been trying to recover after financial woes sent
its stock tumbling by more than 80 percent in a year. The company
has switched auditing firms and a restatement of its earnings for
the past three years was expected to result in a $500 million
reduction.
</P>
<P>
   The Camp Hill-based company had been looking to sell PCS to help
pay off $1.3 billion in debt due Nov. 1. Rite Aid bought the
pharmacy benefits management business for $1.5 billion last year
from Eli Lilly &AMP; Co., which paid $4 billion for it in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think what this means is that Rite Aid wasn't able to sell
PCS at the right price, and banks, when forced with the choice of
forcing Rite Aid into Chapter 11 bankruptcy or refinancing, it went
for the financing structure,'' said Mark Husson, analyst with New
York-based Merrill Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you're a Rite Aid shareholder, (the financial pact) is
better than bad news,'' he said. ''It looks like Rite Aid will
survive. It now has a good shot, an opportunity to turn itself
around.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-11-00 1849 </TRAILER>
