<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 19:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Targets Rare Species Killers  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   OTTAWA (AP) -- A new law proposed Tuesday by Environment Minister
David Anderson would set large fines and five-year prison terms for
people or corporations that kill endangered species.
</P>
<P>
   Under the measure, which requires approval by parliament,
corporations could be fined up to $685,000 and their officials
imprisoned for five years, while individuals could face fines of
$171,000 and five years in prison for killing an animal considered
an endangered species or destroying its habitat.
</P>
<P>
   Fines could be doubled for a second conviction. The bill also
would allow compensation for landowners who suffer financial losses
because they have endangered species on their property, preventing
development or other uses.
</P>
<P>
   ''Canadians want all species at risk protected,'' Anderson said.
''By combining incentives with strong legal protections and the
ability of the federal government to act alone when necessary, the
government of Canada is creating a workable species protection
system that will achieve concrete results.''
</P>
<P>
   Environmental groups support increasing protection of endangered
species, but they oppose a provision in the measure that allows the
Cabinet to decide which species get designated as endangered.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are very disappointed,'' said Stewart Elgie of the Sierra
Legal Defense Fund. ''This bill will do little to ensure that
endangered species and their habitat are protected -- it leaves
everything up to political discretion.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
