<HEADLINE> Elian's Dad Prepares for Son  </HEADLINE>
By REBECCA SINDERBRAND, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BETHESDA, Md. (AP) -- Juan Miguel Gonzalez will treat his son
Elian to a hot dog and scrambled eggs -- the 6-year-old Cuban boy's
favorite foods -- when they are reunited, but other than that ''he's
not making any grand plans,'' a National Council of Churches
representative said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   After meeting with Gonzalez, the Rev. Joan Brown Campbell,
former general secretary of the council, said he ''is strongly
convinced he will see his son very soon.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the meantime, she said, he is worried that Elian looks
thin in the pictures he has seen. She said he tried to call the boy
at the home of the Miami relatives who are caring for him three
times during her visit but wasn't even able to leave a message
because the answering machine was full.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the House Republican leadership and two
Cuban-American members of Florida's congressional delegation
invited Gonzalez to a private meeting Wednesday in the Capitol.
''We want to be sure that you are aware of all the options
available to you as you make your decision,'' they wrote in a
letter delivered by representatives of House Majority Whip Tom
DeLay, R-Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ''We want you to have the freedom to express your true feelings
during your visit without coercion and without intimidation,'' the
letter said.
</P>
<P>
   In a written statement, DeLay told reporters he wanted to
determine whether the elder Gonzalez ''is free from Castro's
intimidation while he is staying in the shadow of the United States
Capitol.''
</P>
<P>
   In Bethesda, Campbell said Gonzalez told her he would go to
Florida if he must to reclaim custody of his son, although he is
hoping that someone will bring Elian to the Washington area. He
said he would not go to the home of the Miami relatives who have
cared for his son since his rescue Thanksgiving Day.
</P>
<P>
   ''He'll do whatever he has to do short of meeting with
relatives,'' she said. ''He does not wish to meet with the
relatives until he has Elian in his arms.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Once he has his son, then the adults can work on their
relationships,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Elian's great-uncle, Lazaro Gonzalez, is fighting the attempt by
the boy's father to gain custody and return with him to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell hosted Elian's grandmothers on their visit to the
United States lobbying for the return of Elian to Cuba and
accompanied Juan Miguel Gonzalez's lawyer on the trip to Havana to
arrange for the father's trip to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting took place at the Bethesda home of a Cuban diplomat,
where Gonzalez has been staying since his arrival in Washington
last week.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what Gonzalez planned to do when he finally meets his son,
Campbell said, ''He's going to give him a hot dog and scrambled
eggs because those are his favorite foods. He's not making any
grand plans at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Tuesday, Gonzalez went to the Cuban Interest Section for
a meeting with members of the Alliance for a Responsible Cuba
Policy, which advocates Elian's return to Cuba and also seeks the
establishment of normal relations between the United States and
Cuba.
</P>
</TEXT>
