<HEADLINE> USDA Resurrecting Loan Program  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Farmers will be able to get low-interest
government financing to build grain storage facilities on their
property in time for this fall's harvest, Agriculture Department
officials said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   USDA is resurrecting a loan program that was discontinued in
1982 after studies showed that there was sufficient storage
available. Now some farmers have nowhere to store grain, because
local elevators are full, department officials said. Others want
additional storage so that they can keep genetically engineered
crops separate from conventional varieties.
</P>
<P>
   Without sufficient storage space, farmers are sometimes forced
to sell their crops when commodity prices are low rather than
waiting until they rebound.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have got to have a much better on-farm storage
infrastructure than we have right now,'' Agriculture Secretary Dan
Glickman said at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   The department is working on rules for the program and plans to
issue them in time for farmers to obtain the storage they need for
this year's crop, said aides to Glickman. USDA has come under
criticism from some lawmakers for not moving quicker on the
program.
</P>
<P>
   The loans can be repaid in five or 10 years and will carry an
interest rate of 6 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
