<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 19:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cops Review Tape of Kennedy, Guard  </HEADLINE>
By RACHEL ZOLL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) -- An airport security guard is
misrepresenting a confrontation with Rep. Patrick Kennedy to make
money off his famous name, the state Democratic Party chairman said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''She started to look at this thing and heard cash register
sounds in her head,'' said William Lynch, who discussed the
incident with Kennedy two days ago. ''He's resigned to the fact
that because his name is Kennedy, these types of things that
ordinarily wouldn't mean anything are totally blown out of
proportion.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy does not deny having some ''inadvertent contact'' with
Della Patton, 58, at Los Angeles International Airport last month,
but he did not grab or shove her, as she claims, Lynch said.
</P>
<P>
   Detectives have reviewed a surveillance video of the incident,
but have not made it public.
</P>
<P>
   ''It shows there appears to have been physical contact between
Ms. Patton and Mr. Kennedy,'' Los Angeles police Lt. Horace Frank
said. ''She said she was battered at a preboard checkpoint.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy released a brief statement Tuesday night denying
Patton's allegations.
</P>
<P>
   ''When all the facts become public, people will see that the
press reports don't reflect what actually happened,'' Kennedy said.
''I apologized for this unfortunate incident at the time and
continue to regret that it occurred. I sincerely hope that this
matter can be resolved soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Patton, reached at her home Tuesday, said she was in pain but
declined to comment and referred calls to her attorney, Paul Trump.
He did not return calls.
</P>
<P>
   Patton has accused Kennedy of grabbing and pushing her at 11:35
p.m. on March 26 when she told him his bag was too big to fit in an
X-ray scanner.
</P>
<P>
   The congressman, son of Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., then
allegedly grabbed Patton's arm and cursed at her while ordering her
out of the way. Patton complained of injuries to her left shoulder.
She filed a battery complaint with police on or about April 1.
</P>
<P>
   Frank said the case was being handled by detectives in the
robbery-homicide division because of its high-profile nature.
</P>
<P>
   No charges have been filed against the Rhode Island Democrat.
Misdemeanor battery carries a maximum penalty of one year in jail
and a $2,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, 32, has hired defense attorney Abbe Lowell, who served
as chief investigative counsel for House Democrats in President
Clinton's impeachment proceedings. Lowell did not return calls to
his office.
</P>
<P>
   Patton filed a worker's compensation claim and remains at home
on paid leave while her claim is being reviewed.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy is head of the Democratic Congressional Campaign
Committee, the party's chief fund-raising arm in the House.
</P>
<P>
   He was traveling from Los Angeles to Rhode Island to deliver a
civil rights speech the next day at a Providence church at the time
Patton said they scuffled.
</P>
<P>
   Patton told airport security supervisor Michael Cobb that
Kennedy tried to lift the metal gate on the X-ray scanner and cram
through a bag that didn't fit. The congressman told her he had a
speech to make and there was a physical confrontation, Cobb told
The Providence Journal.
</P>
<P>
   When Patton didn't budge, he allegedly returned to the ticket
counter to check his bag and apologized to the security guard on
his return through the checkpoint, Cobb said.
</P>
<P>
   Lynch said the congressman did tell her he was running late, but
peacefully went to check the bag at a ticket counter when she
wouldn't let him through. Lynch said it was his understanding the
guard, not Kennedy, was the antagonist.
</P>
<P>
   The National Enquirer broke the story in its April 18 edition,
based on a tip from a freelance writer, said John South, an
Enquirer senior reporter. He would not say whether the tabloid paid
Patton.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't reveal that information, but it is common knowledge
that we do pay for stories,'' South said.
</P>
<P>
   Lynch said Patton's cooperation with the Enquirer shows she was
trying to trade on the Kennedy name.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's outrageous,'' Lynch said.
</P>
</TEXT>
