<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two men joined by a common affair face trial together  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY NEUMEISTER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- One defendant is the former chief executive
officer at a prestigious Wall Street firm, the other a businessman
and novice gambler. Their common romantic interest -- an X-rated
movie star -- has united them in an insider trading trial.
</P>
<P>
   Through their lawyers, James McDermott Jr. and Anthony Pomponio
have both admitted to a relationship with Kathryn Gannon, a
Canadian woman who the jury is getting to know by order of Judge
Kimba Wood only as a ''model, dancer and actress who appeared in
films under the screen name, Marylin Star.''
</P>
<P>
   McDermott, the former chief executive officer at Keefe, Bruyette
&AMP; Woods, and Pomponio, a New Jersey man who built his own quartz
and glass cutting company, knew Gannon as the star of such movies
as ''Sins of the Flesh,'' ''The Passion Potion'' and ''The
Violation of Marylin Star.''
</P>
<P>
   But the men say they did not know about each other until shortly
before their arrests. Throughout pretrial hearings and the start of
the trial, they have remained largely separate in court, bonded
only by their extramarital affairs with Gannon.
</P>
<P>
   Their fates rest in part on the jury's perception of their
relationship with Gannon, a Canadian citizen who remains in her
Canadian home out of the reach -- so far -- of U.S. efforts to
extradite her.
</P>
<P>
   A jury in U.S. District Court in Manhattan began hearing and
seeing evidence in the case on Monday, including a simple headshot
photograph of Gannon, described by a prosecutor as a ''28-year-old
blonde, an attractive woman.''
</P>
<P>
   They have listened to witnesses from a brokerage where Gannon
opened her first account after meeting McDermott, and from
representatives of McDermott's company. The witnesses are giving
the jury a crash course on how information about stocks reaches the
public and how Gannon and Pomponio traded in stocks that
prosecutors allege earned them $170,000 in illegal profits.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors say McDermott, 48, of Briarcliff Manor, enamored
with Gannon, fed her secret information about pending mergers and
acquisitions of six regional banks and a credit card company,
allowing her to profit illegally. She then allegedly gave the
information to Pomponio.
</P>
<P>
   McDermott's lawyer, Scott Muller, so far has encouraged jurors
to believe that McDermott and Gannon were so close that it would be
impossible to conclude he might not have recommended the six stocks
before they went on a secret list at his company prior to major
public announcements about them.
</P>
<P>
   He said McDermott and Gannon spoke to each other several times a
day from 1996 through 1999, when the couple allegedly committed
conspiracy and securities fraud, along with Pomponio.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's thousands, literally, of opportunities, face-to-face
and on the phone ... for them to have discussed it legitimately,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said there was no reason for McDermott, an executive earning
nearly $4 million annually, to risk his flourishing career by
giving stock secrets illegally to Gannon when he could afford to
just send her checks, which he did in amounts that nearly added up
to $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   Pomponio's lawyer, Thomas Dunn, told the jury that his
45-year-old client did nothing wrong except engage in an
extramarital affair.
</P>
<P>
   When the Securities and Exchange Commission interviewed him,
Pomponio confessed everything about the relationship, including how
he met her in an Atlantic City casino when she was at a trade show,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''He had gotten involved with this good looking woman and now
he's realizing that it was an immoral thing and how it's going to
impact on his family,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn said his client also had been successful, leaving high
school early to build a company, North Jersey Diamond Wheel, which
makes diamond wheels that cut the ''hardest material in the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   Dunn said his client also is a chief executive officer, living
in North Caldwell, N.J., with his wife, Bonnie, and a young
daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ''In a sense, his business success is that of the American
dream,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The trial continues Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
