<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Algerian's Hearing in Canada Set  </HEADLINE>
By JACK BRANSWELL, 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL (AP) -- Canada will begin extradition hearings in June
against an Algerian wanted by the United States for alleged links
with a bombing plot on U.S. soil, a court ruled Tuesday after the
FBI filed evidence in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Mokhtar Haouari is accused of supporting a terrorism plot in
connection with the case of Ahmed Ressam, another Algerian arrested
in December as he crossed the border from Canada into Washington
allegedly with a carload of bomb-making equipment.
</P>
<P>
   A third Algerian, Abdel Ghani Meskini, was arrested in New York
City soon after Ressam, on charges of providing support to
terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   Haouari, 31, faces no charges in Canada, but has been held since
Jan. 10 on a U.S. extradition request.
</P>
<P>
   Canada on Monday ordered the extradition hearing to go forward
after the FBI turned over evidence. A court on Tuesday scheduled an
extradition hearing for June 13-15.
</P>
<P>
   Haouari attended Tuesday's hearing in handcuffs, but said
nothing. His lawyer previously has said Haouari was innocent.
</P>
<P>
   U.S authorities have not disclosed any potential targets of the
alleged plot or the scope of who might be involved.
</P>
<P>
   The evidence submitted Tuesday detailed links between Haouari,
Meskini and Ressam, including telephone calls and written
addresses. The FBI says telephone calls taped after Ressam's Dec.
14 arrest implicate Meskini and Haouari in the alleged plot.
</P>
<P>
   In one call, Meskini, 31, says Ressam and Haouari were part of a
well-organized network, according to the court documents. They also
include statements by Meskini after his arrest in December that he
and Haouari had ''several conversations about Jihad (holy war) and
about how to become a martyr.''
</P>
<P>
   The court documents said U.S. authorities would consider
granting Meskini limited immunity from prosecution to testify
against Haouari.
</P>
<P>
   The January grand jury indictment against Haouari and Meskini
accuses them of conspiring since October 1997 to support members
and associates of a terrorist group.
</P>
<P>
   According to the indictment and the court documents filed
Tuesday, Haouari provided various forged identification documents
while Meskini went to Seattle to assist Ressam.
</P>
<P>
   Haouari and Meskini are also accused of conspiring to transfer
fake or stolen U.S. immigration identity cards and passports of
other countries. They were also accused of using fake credit and
bank cards over the last year to buy $1,000 or more worth of
merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   Haouari has said that he fled to Canada in 1993 because he was
wanted by military police in Algeria for his involvement with the
fundamentalist Islamic Salvation Front. He said he had left the
group a year earlier because he was opposed to its use of violence.
He has said he knew Ressam and Meskini but denied any involvement
in a terrorist plot,
</P>
<P>
   Ressam, 32, who has pleaded innocent to nine charges including
possessing and transporting explosives with the intent to cause
damage or injury, had Meskini's phone number in his pocket when he
was arrested.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
