<HEADLINE> Weinstein: Reports of cost overruns will not delay E-ZPass start  </HEADLINE>
By RALPH SIEGEL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- Possible demands for extra cash from the
firms installing the E-ZPass electronic toll collection system will
not delay the work, state Transportation Commissioner James
Weinstein said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Weinstein said E-ZPass, already in operation at Garden State
Parkway toll plazas in Middlesex County and north of there, will be
operational in Monmouth County toll plazas by summer and throughout
the parkway by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   As for the New Jersey Turnpike, which is already three months
behind schedule, E-ZPass is expected to be operational sometime in
August. While parkway toll plazas can convert to E-ZPass one at a
time, the turnpike must implement the system all at once at all of
its toll plazas.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to reports in The Star-Ledger of Newark, Weinstein
told lawmakers at the Assembly Budget Committee Tuesday that a
reported demand by one of the E-ZPass construction contractors for
an additional $75 million has not been formally filed and will not
be accepted.
</P>
<P>
   He said there were contingencies in the $43 million contract to
install E-ZPass that will allow for some cost overruns, but that
such a massive amendment to the contract would not be considered.
</P>
<P>
   ''What's fiction is that there is serious consideration being
given to a subcontractor's piece of paper that says the cost to
this has to be $75 million. It is fiction, it is a pipe dream, it
will not happen,'' Weinstein said.
</P>
<P>
   However, when pressed on details, Weinstein said higher
''discretionary'' costs could be involved as E-ZPass contractors
document work they have done or need to do that was not specified
in the original contract, such as repairing old toll-plaza
structures. Additional work yet to be done could include protecting
the E-ZPass systems from lightning damage.
</P>
<P>
   Weinstein confirmed the Star-Ledger's report of increased
spending by construction firms that had been hired as
subcontractors by the prime E-ZPass contractor, Adesta
Communications, and further that talks were occurring with Adesta
officials about contract changes.
</P>
<P>
   But Weinstein ruled out a change in the contract to raise the
price to more than $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers questioned Weinstein about the financial stability of
Able Telcom, the parent company of Adesta Communications.
</P>
<P>
   The state originally awarded the $43 million contract to install
E-ZPass plus the $500 million contract to operate the multistate
system to a subsidiary of WorldCom, which last year sold the
subsidiary to Able Telcom.
</P>
<P>
   Able Telcom earlier this year ran into debt problems that
threatened to drive it into bankruptcy, although Weinstein on
Tuesday said new corporate financing has resolved the emergency. He
said at no time did any of the fiscal turmoil interfere with the
progress of work on the toll roads.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.state.nj.us/turnpike
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
