<HEADLINE> Sheppard Case May Go to Jury Soon  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN AFFLECK, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND (AP) -- Forensic evidence like DNA shows Dr. Sam
Sheppard did not beat his wife to death in 1954 and also validates
his son's long fight to clear his father's name, an attorney said
in closing arguments Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you follow your common sense and follow your instincts and
use your intellect, I think that you will come up with the only
conclusion that is possible,'' Terry Gilbert said. ''Sam did not
commit this crime.''
</P>
<P>
   Gilbert's client, Sam Reese Sheppard, has sued the state of Ohio
claiming his father was wrongfully imprisoned for his mother's
slaying in the case that inspired ''The Fugitive'' television
series and film.
</P>
<P>
   Jurors were expected to begin deliberating Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Cuyahoga County prosecutors, who have been defending the state,
told jurors Tuesday that authorities had the right man all along.
</P>
<P>
   ''It may just be that you are being asked to reward the killer's
son for the killer bludgeoning his wife,'' Prosecutor William Mason
told jurors.
</P>
<P>
   Sheppard was convicted of murder and spent almost a decade in
prison before the U.S. Supreme Court overturned the verdict in a
landmark ruling on the effects of pretrial publicity. Sheppard was
acquitted at a retrial in 1966 and died four years later.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors described Sheppard as a cheating husband who killed
his wife because he felt trapped in his marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Sheppard was found lying in a pool of blood on her bed
early on July 4, 1954, at the couple's home on Lake Erie.
</P>
<P>
   Gilbert told jurors that Sheppard never varied from his alibi:
that he was sleeping downstairs at the time of the killing and
awoke to his wife's cries. He ran upstairs to help her but was
knocked out. Upon waking up, he chased the killer -- whom he
identified as a bushy-haired man -- down to the beach outside the
house but was knocked unconscious again.
</P>
<P>
   He reviewed testimony from scientific experts who indicated
through DNA and blood evidence that a third person bled in the
Sheppards' bedroom. That person must be the killer, Gilbert said.
</P>
<P>
   The DNA evidence ''excludes the critical parties in this case,''
Gilbert said. ''It's not from Sam and it's not from Marilyn.''
</P>
<P>
   Sam Reese Sheppard, who was 7 at the time of the killing, has
worked since the late 1980s to try to clear his father's name.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
