<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Court refuses child killer access to DNA 12 years after trial  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- He didn't make it an issue at his 1988
trial. He didn't mention it in any of his earlier appeals.
</P>
<P>
   And now a convicted child killer can't use DNA evidence to
possibly overturn his double-murder conviction.
</P>
<P>
   A state appeals court ruled Tuesday that the evidence is off
limits for the Plainfield man who killed his girlfriend's two
children after he sexually assaulted one of them, a 7-year-old
girl.
</P>
<P>
   In the 11-page opinion, the court recognized the growing use of
DNA evidence and the growing improvements in testing those
materials.
</P>
<P>
   ''However, every defendant cannot forever seek to have
post-judgement tests conducted in the hopes that something
beneficial may result, even assuming that the evidence to be tested
remains available,'' wrote appellate division Presiding Judge Edwin
H. Stern.
</P>
<P>
   Byron Halsey, who had faced the death penalty at his trial, is
now serving two life sentences for the murders and assault.
</P>
<P>
   Included in the testimony against Halsey were his two
confessions to police and the results of a polygraph test he failed
before his arrest. He did not testify before the jury, but his
attorney presented claims that Halsey was intoxicated.
</P>
<P>
   Halsey appealed his initial sentence as well as the conviction,
beginning in 1991. It wasn't until May 1997 that he asked the state
to turn over evidence collected during an exam of the child as well
as ''semen on the victim's panties'', according to the appeal.
Prosecutors presented no scientific evidence using that evidence at
the trial that linked Halsey to the killings, the court noted.
</P>
<P>
   In this appeal, Halsey's public defender simply said an analysis
of the clothing and the DNA ''will undoubtedly prove that he is
innocent.''
</P>
<P>
   That was simply not enough of a reason ''in light of the
overwhelming evidence of the defendant's participation in the crime
and the nature of the defense,'' the court wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ''There has been no showing of what defendant believes the
testing will reveal, the basis for such a belief, and why defendant
did not present a defense at trial which the testing he now seeks
would support,'' Stern said in the opinion.
</P>
<P>
   The court however did leave a door open for Halsey. Defendants
can appeal at any time for a new trial based on the claim of newly
discovered evidence. And prosecutors are required to maintain
physical evidence in homicide cases throughout the appeals process
and in some cases beyond.
</P>
<P>
   ''We only hold that this defendant has not shown enough to
compel testing of whatever evidence may remain available at this
late date,'' the court said.
</P>
<P>
   But attorney Matthew Astore said Halsey maintains his innocence
and repeatedly challenged his confessions and the polygraph test.
</P>
<P>
   ''The state should at least turn over the evidence so we can
test it. Why would they not want to know,'' Astore asked.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-11-00 1951 </TRAILER>
