<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Houston Trades Bako to Florida  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON (AP) -- Backup catcher Paul Bako was traded Tuesday from
the Houston Astros to the Florida Marlins for cash and a player to
be named.
</P>
<P>
   The move allows Houston to keep rookie Mitch Meluskey on the
roster. Bako, acquired in a trade with Detroit last year, likely
would not have cleared waivers had the Astros tried to demote him
to the minors.
</P>
<P>
   Bako, 27, hit .256 with 17 RBIs in 215 at-bats in 1999. As the
club's third catcher this season behind Tony Eusebio and Meluskey,
Bako was 0-for-2 in the first seven games.
</P>
<P>
   ''This was a tough thing for me to do because Paul is a major
league quality player,'' Astros general manager Gerry Hunsicker
said. ''You always try to protect yourself against injury and depth
is something you always want. But having Paul as the third catcher
was not a productive situation. It's difficult to carry three
catchers.''
</P>
<P>
   To replace Bako, the Astros promoted infielder Julio Lugo from
their Triple-A team at New Orleans. Outfielder Matt Mieske
eventually is expected to take the roster spot, when he returns
from the disabled list, possibly as early as Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But Astros officials said the health of third baseman Ken
Caminiti could change that. Caminiti has missed the last two days
with a slight hamstring pull and he is day-to-day.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're not sure what we'll do when Mieske comes off,'' manager
Larry Dierker said. ''Because we don't know what we're going to
have to do with Caminiti, if he'll be ready. Lugo can play both
infield and outfield so that's why we brought him up now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
