<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Sportscaster Sues ABC  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY NEUMEISTER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- An Olympic gold medalist who spent three decades
in sports broadcasting is suing ABC, saying the network dropped her
because of her age and gender.
</P>
<P>
   Donna deVarona, 52, who set 18 world swimming records, filed the
$50 million lawsuit in U.S. District Court late Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit alleges ABC paid deVarona less than other
broadcasters and gave her fewer assignments, often of inferior
quality, because it was trying to appeal to younger viewers by
using younger sportscasters.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, the lawsuit says, a former vice president of ABC
Sports programming told deVarona ABC Sports was eager to recapture
the ''young 18 to 39 male market'' and that she should consider
looking for work elsewhere because her age was catching up to her.
</P>
<P>
   Her freelance contract, signed in 1991, was terminated two year
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ABC responded to the allegations Tuesday, saying that changes
over the years in the events covered by ABC Sports, including the
loss of the Olympics, had reduced deVarona's role.
</P>
<P>
   ''Ms. deVarona and her representatives were advised of this fact
over the years and she was encouraged to look for work elsewhere.
We believe Ms. deVarona was treated fairly and that this suit has
no merit,'' the network said in the statement.
</P>
<P>
   DeVarona joined ABC in 1965 but quit 11 years later because she
was ''unable to break the discriminatory barriers facing a
pioneering female sports broadcaster,'' the lawsuit said. She later
returned to ABC and in 1980 was the first female host of Olympic
coverage at the games in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Her lawsuit alleges that after signing her freelance agreement
1991, ABC treated her in an ''intentional, calculated, callous and
opportunistic'' way in its efforts to appeal to a younger audience.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
