<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Trial begins in shooting death of man who tried to intervene  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN CURRAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   MAYS LANDING, N.J. (AP) -- Alex Crawford was just trying to help.
</P>
<P>
   The 24-year-old truck driver was in the parking lot of a
Pleasantville bar when he saw a gunman shoot another man in the
chest during an argument.
</P>
<P>
   He died trying to intervene, a prosecutor told jurors Tuesday in
the murder trial of the gunman.
</P>
<P>
   ''Alex Crawford got caught in a bad situation, being in the
wrong place at the wrong time, being a good Samaritan,'' Assistant
Atlantic County Prosecutor Cary Shill said in opening arguments.
</P>
<P>
   Carnell Gibbs, 24, of Pleasantville, is accused of murder,
attempted murder, conspiracy and weapons charges in the Oct. 22,
1998 shootings of John Byrd, 25, and Crawford.
</P>
<P>
   Avenging earlier bad blood with Byrd, Gibbs pulled a 9-mm
handgun and shot Byrd during a chance encounter outside Wash's Inn
in Pleasantville, prosecutors say.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd was shot several times, but survived.
</P>
<P>
   Crawford, who wasn't involved in the feud, approached Gibbs as
Gibbs walked away from Byrd.
</P>
<P>
   ''He had his hands up,'' Crawford's brother, Cory Crawford, 20,
testified. ''He was just regular walking, he had his hands up. He
asked (Gibbs) what he was doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Gibbs then fired two shots at Crawford, killing him, according
to Shill.
</P>
<P>
   Gibbs and his alleged accomplice, cousin Thomas Allen, 22, fled
after the shooting and remained on the lam for three months before
turning themselves in.
</P>
<P>
   Allen has since pleaded guilty to aggravated manslaughter and is
awaiting sentencing. If convicted, Gibbs could get life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorney Scott Becker acknowledged that Gibbs shot the
men, but said it was not premeditated and therefore wasn't murder.
He says it was self defense: Gibbs believed Byrd was reaching for a
pistol, and then shot Crawford when Crawford ran toward him,
screaming.
</P>
<P>
   ''He is guilty,'' Becker said. ''The question is, is he guilty
of first-degree murder?''
</P>
<P>
   Among those in the gallery in Superior Court Judge Robert
Neustadter's courtroom were Crawford's parents, two of his aunts
and his 3-year-old son, Alex Crawford Jr.
</P>
<P>
   One of his aunts, Edna Munns of Pleasantville, described
Crawford as a friendly guy who helped her and her husband with yard
work. She said she wasn't surprised when she learned how he died.
</P>
<P>
   ''I could understand it. That was just like him,'' Munns said.
</P>
<P>
   Crawford's mother, Katherine Crawford, 50, said the start of the
trial gave her mixed emotions.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's good to see him (Gibbs) being brought to justice, but
it's still hard to be here,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
