<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 20:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wounded Ore. Teens Receive Funds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SPRINGFIELD, Ore. (AP) -- Twenty-five students wounded when Kip
Kinkel opened fire in the Thurston High School cafeteria two years
ago and the siblings of the two students killed in the attack will
share $150,000 in donations collected after the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   John Lively, chairman of the Thurston Healing Fund's executive
committee, said letters have gone out to the families telling them
of the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Each wounded student is to receive $4,000 from the fund, and the
five siblings of Ben Walker and Mikael Nickolauson will each
receive $10,000. A date for delivering the money has not been set.
</P>
<P>
   The fund has collected $476,000 in donations and interest since
the shooting May 22, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   About $130,000 has been paid out to cover victims' medical
expenses, travel and other costs related to the shooting. The
remaining $195,000 will be kept in the fund for five more years to
cover any continuing medical or mental health treatment the
survivors might need. Money remaining at the end of 2005 will be
split among the wounded students and families of the slain
students.
</P>
<P>
   Kinkel, now 17, was convicted of murder last year and is serving
a life sentence in prison.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
