<DOCNO> APW20000411.0258 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 20:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Trying To Deflect Criticism  </HEADLINE>
By EDITH M. LEDERER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Russia's U.N. Mission on Tuesday
circulated an appeal by 21 prominent Russians against Western
attempts to isolate Moscow or impose sanctions because of its
military campaign in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   It was distributed as allegations of widespread Russian abuses
in Chechnya were being debated at the U.N. Human Rights Commission
in Geneva.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists and cultural figures asked the Russian and
international media to remember that the military action is aimed
at combatting terrorism -- and that the Russian people backed the
campaign by electing President Vladimir Putin on March 26.
</P>
<P>
   ''We call on everybody, both our partners and opponents, to take
this will into account,'' the appeal said.
</P>
<P>
   Russia sent troops into Chechnya for a second time last
September, after militants based in the territory invaded the
neighboring region of Dagestan. Chechens also are blamed for four
apartment bombings in Russia in September that killed 300 people.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and the European Union have been sharply
critical of what they call excessive use of force by Russian
troops, widespread civilian suffering, and reports of human rights
abuses in the campaign against Chechen separatists.
</P>
<P>
   The 21 Russians said soldiers in Chechnya were ''literally
guarding the sound sleep'' of their countrymen and should have been
supported by the world community which is spending huge resources
to fight terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   ''Introduction of sanctions against Russia, declaration of an
international embargo on trade with our country, as well as
suspension of Russia's membership in a number of international
organizations are being discussed in earnest on a high level,'' it
said.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists who signed include Yuri Osipov, president of the
Russian Academy of Sciences, and Alexander M. Prokhorov, winner of
the 1964 Nobel Prize in physics.
</P>
<P>
   In the cultural field, signatories included directors Nikita
Mikhalkov, who won an Oscar in 1994 for Best Foreign Film with
''Burnt by the Sun,'' and Karen Shakhnazarov whose film ''The Day
of Full Moon'' was screened at last year's Cairo International Film
Festival. Irina Antonova, director of the Pushkin State Museum of
Fine Arts, pianist Nikolai Petrov, and singer Alexander Gradsky,
also signed the appeal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
