<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil's Senate OKs Spending Limits  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) -- The government won a key victory in its
campaign for fiscal austerity Tuesday when the Senate approved
strict spending limits for federal, state and municipal
governments.
</P>
<P>
   Senators voted 60-to-10 to approve the bill, known as the fiscal
responsibility law, which now goes to President Fernando Henrique
Cardoso who is expected to sign it.
</P>
<P>
   The law will tighten payroll expenditures and public debt at all
three levels of government. It will also keep public administrators
from overspending ahead of the elections, a common practice here
especially among Brazil's 5,507 mayors.
</P>
<P>
   Payroll expenses will be limited to a maximum of 60 percent of
the budget. And long-term projects will be allowed only if
administrators show where the money will come from.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil pledged to curb its chronic budget deficit under a 1998
agreement with the International Monetary Fund in return for a
$41.5 billion loan. Cardoso said states and municipalities have run
up a debt of more than 110 billion reals, or about $61.8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The fiscal responsibility law is viewed as a type of guarantee
that Brazil's austerity program ending in 2001 will be sustainable
in the long run, without the need for emergency tax hikes and
budget cuts.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, a lower house committee is expected to approve a
separate bill establishing punishments for noncompliance with the
fiscal responsibility law.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
