<HEADLINE> Video shows dancer's body in bed of pickup truck resembling accusedkiller's  </HEADLINE>
Precede PHILADELPHIA
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOUNT HOLLY, N.J. (AP) -- The body of a woman believed to be a
slain stripper could be seen sprawled in the back of a pickup truck
as it drove across a Pennsylvania Turnpike bridge on the night she
was killed, officials confirmed Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The image was captured on videotape by surveillance equipment on
the bridge, according to a probable cause affidavit made public by
Burlington County Prosecutor Robert D. Bernardi.
</P>
<P>
   On the tape, the truck can be seen crossing the bridge linking
the New Jersey and Pennsylvania turnpikes at about 3:13 a.m. on
March 29.
</P>
<P>
   ''The body is that of a small person wearing a white top, blue
jeans and white footwear. The description of the body is consistent
with that of Rachel Elizabeth Siani at the crime scene,'' according
to the affidavit, filed Friday by Detective J.C. Villamil of the
New Jersey State Police.
</P>
<P>
   The truck is a red Dodge believed to be that of John A. Denofa,
35, of Buckingham, Pa., who is accused of killing the 21-year-old
dancer. The affidavit does not identify the truck, but says its
aluminum trim, cylindrical step-bar and color match a 1996 Dodge
truck owned by Denofa.
</P>
<P>
   The affidavit did not say whether Siani was alive or dead when
the truck passed through Toll No. 29.
</P>
<P>
   Siani, of Bensalem, Pa., suffered a fractured skull, lacerated
kidneys and punctured liver in a fall, according to the Burlington
County medical examiner, which ruled the death a homicide.
</P>
<P>
   Her body was found April 1 beneath the same bridge.
</P>
<P>
   Siani worked at Diva's International Gentleman's Club, a go-go
bar in Levittown, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   Denofa, a prominent businessman who was a Tuesday night regular
at the bar, told police he smoked marijuana with Siani the night
she disappeared, but that was the last he saw of her.
</P>
<P>
   He was arrested after police searched his home, his truck and a
motel near the turnpike bridge in Levittown, Pa., where he rented a
room that night.
</P>
<P>
   According to the probable cause affidavit released Tuesday,
Officer Ken Burns of the Bristol Township Police Department saw
Siani and Denofa enter the Econo Lodge Motel about 2:40 a.m. March
29.
</P>
<P>
   Bloodstains were found on the door and curtain of Room 223 of
the motel and fibers found on the weather stripping and metal
channel of the window in Denofa's room resemble the fabric of
Siani's sweater, the affidavit said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, a blood stain was found beneath the window, outside
the room, the affidavit said.
</P>
<P>
   Fibers matching Siani's sweater also were found in the bed of
the truck, which had blood stains on the bumper, trailer hitch,
license plate frame, bed and interior head liner, the affidavit
said.
</P>
<P>
   An unidentified second woman who was with Denofa earlier in the
evening told police that when she left him, he was with Siani,
according to the affidavit.
</P>
<P>
   Denofa, who was being held without bail at the Bucks County
Prison, is awaiting extradition to New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Several dancers at Diva's have described Denofa as a generous
tipper and courteous customer.
</P>
<P>
   Denofa owns J&AMP;L Wholesale Tapes, a sign and equipment supplies
business in Warminster, Pa., and lives in an expensive home. Denofa
and his wife, Lisa, held a neighborhood Labor Day party annually
and were well liked, according to residents.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
