<HEADLINE> Mexico Police Probe Recent Killings  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NUEVO LAREDO, Mexico (AP) -- Police are investigating whether the
gangland-style killing of four young men in the border city of
Nuevo Laredo may have been tied to drugs or a dispute over a
romance.
</P>
<P>
   One of the victims, Jorge Lopez Rodriguez, 20, was a native of
San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   The four were killed after their car, which Lopez Rodriguez was
driving, was cut off by another vehicle, from which gunmen opened
fire on Monday in Nuevo Laredo, just south of Laredo, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   One passenger, Roberto Gonzalez, 17, died in the back seat of
the car. Another passenger, Gerardo Garza Avitia, 17, was shot
three times, then run over by the gunmen's car as he tried to flee.
</P>
<P>
   The third passenger, Pedro Garza Armendariz, 16, died in a
hospital Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez Rodriguez was forced into the gunmen's car and driven
around for an hour before being shot to death and dumped nine
blocks from where the others were killed.
</P>
<P>
   Hilario Molina, a deputy state attorney general, said
investigators are exploring whether the killings may have been
drug-related -- a common cause of much of the violence on the
border. Lopez Rodriguez had been recently released from prison,
where he had been serving time for auto theft.
</P>
<P>
   But Molina said it could also be related to a dispute Lopez
Rodriguez was having with the family of a girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   One suspect has been arrested but authorities have not decided
whether to charge him in the killings.
</P>
</TEXT>
