<HEADLINE> House Chaplain Conducts Mass  </HEADLINE>
By JENNIFER LOVEN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The first Roman Catholic chaplain of the House
was welcomed Tuesday at a Mass and reception organized by the
Republican Party, but he said politics had nothing to do with his
attendance.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think some people think there are political overtones to my
being here,'' the Rev. Daniel P. Coughlin told a group of about 200
gathered in the basement of St. Peter's Church near the Capitol.
''There is not.''
</P>
<P>
   The events put on by the Republican National Committee were
criticized by Democrats as appearing to be a political ploy by the
GOP to woo Catholics, who account for a quarter of the vote in
national elections.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicagoan's appointment as chaplain last month followed a
bitter process during which some Democrats accused GOP leaders of
being anti-Catholic because they at first appeared to pass over a
priest in favor of a Protestant for the post.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview about Tuesday's events, Coughlin said he ''just
though it was a Catholic group'' that proposed them.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he felt it was inappropriate for a political party to
honor him given the highly divisive nature of the selection
process, Coughlin said: ''Anything that seems partisan -- yes. I
hope for another invitation'' from other groups.
</P>
<P>
   RNC Chairman Jim Nicholson said it was possible Coughlin did not
know Republicans organized the events, because they were put
together by the former ambassador to the Vatican, Thomas Melady.
Melady heads the RNC's Catholic Task Force, an effort to draw
Catholic voters into the party.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholson insisted the events were intended not to score
political points, but merely to introduce Coughlin to lawmakers he
will be counseling.
</P>
<P>
   ''How can anybody politicize the celebration of a Mass?''
Nicholson told a reporter.
</P>
<P>
   Still, to the group, Nicholson proclaimed: ''This is a wonderful
day for our country, and for our party, and our church.''
</P>
<P>
   Only 26 House Republicans who are on the RNC task force were
issued personal invitations to the event, along with other
prominent Republican Catholics, said RNC spokesman Chris Paulitz.
All other House members of both parties were just sent advisories
alerting them.
</P>
<P>
   Only a handful of House members attended, most Republican.
However, Coughlin said he had been ''approached by a couple people
who identified themselves as part of the minority party.''
</P>
<P>
   He said his new job has kept him extremely busy.
</P>
<P>
   ''I find it somewhat disarming to be on regular prayer on
C-Span,'' the slight, unassuming man said to laughter.
</P>
<P>
   He talked of being in awe of his grand new everyday surroundings
-- ''Walking through the hallways -- I hope I never lose that'' -- and
of feeling ''the weight of history.''
</P>
<P>
   Coughlin said scores of delighted Catholics have written to him.
</P>
<P>
   ''This has made Catholics around the country very, very happy
and very proud,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., and other Republican
leaders came under fire late last year when they announced the
selection of the Rev. Charles Wright for the chaplain job.
Democrats insisted that a Catholic priest, the Rev. Timothy
O'Brien, was the top choice of a bipartisan selection committee.
</P>
<P>
   The speaker vehemently denied their characterizations of
anti-Catholic bias. Wright eventually withdrew and Hastert
unexpectedly appointed Coughlin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-11-00 2058 </TRAILER>
