<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 21:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NCAA Council OKs Member Moratorium  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- The three divisions of the NCAA Management
Council agreed Tuesday to recommend a two-year moratorium on new
membership in the association.
</P>
<P>
   That would mean new members and those wanting changes in
division membership must wait until Sept. 1, 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said escalating membership in recent years prompted
the moratorium request, explaining it would allow time for the
divisions to evaluate and plan for championships,
educational/compliance programs, and necessary support services.
</P>
<P>
   The Division III recommendation would permit a Division I or II
school to reclassify to Division III during the moratorium.
</P>
<P>
   The recommendations will be forwarded to the appropriate
presidential group in each division and on to the NCAA's Executive
Committee later this month.
</P>
<P>
   In Division I, the Management Council approved a recommendation
for modifications to automatic qualification legislation for
Division I championships. The modification would require, for
example, that to be considered for automatic qualification into the
Division I men's basketball championship, a member conference must
have seven members which have been active Division I participants
for eight preceding years. In addition, six of those institutions
must have conducted conference competition together in Division I
for the five preceding years in men's basketball.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal calls for three exceptions:
</P>
<P>
   -- Before September 1, 2003, a Division I conference that was an
NCAA member as of Sept. 1, 1999, may be considered for automatic
qualification in all sports by meeting either existing automatic
qualification provisions or those in effect on September 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   -- Before Sept. 1, 2003, the eight-year core principle will not
apply to a Division I active, provisional or reclassifying
institutions as of Sept. 1, 1999. They would be subject to
provisions in effect on Sept. 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   -- After Sept. 1, 2003, a Division I conference as of Sept. 1,
1999 may continue to apply automatic qualification requirements in
effect on Sept. 1, 1999 until any change in men's basketball
membership occurs
</P>
<P>
   The proposed legislation also includes a one-year grace period
for conferences unable to meet the core-member requirement in men's
basketball.
</P>
<P>
   In other action the council agreed not to approve a measure that
would have recommended an earlier calendar date for telephone calls
to high school juniors in women's basketball. The council approved
allowing one telephone call to a prospect between April 24 and May
14 of the junior year Tuesday morning, but reconsidered the
proposal when student-athlete council members noted that the
measure would be intrusive to prospects during a heavy academic
time of the year and that a similar measure affecting men's
basketball recruits was defeated on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Division I Council sent to the Board of Directors
legislation to modify Division I-A football attendance
requirements. The proposal provides that a Division I school meets
football attendance requirements if it averages more than 17,000 in
actual paid attendance for home games in the immediate four-year
period. One current exception to the requirement will be retained.
A school that fails to meet home-attendance requirements can retain
Division I-A football status if it is a member of a conference
which has at least six members sponsoring football and more than
half of them meet the attendance criterion.
</P>
<P>
   The purpose of the legislation is to establish more stringent
attendance standards consistent with expectations for competing in
the subdivision while providing deserving institutions interested
in moving to Division I-A the opportunity to participate at that
level.
</P>
<P>
   Schools that fail to meet requirements would be placed in a
restricted membership category for a maximum of three years. If the
institution fails to meet the requirements after three years, it
would be reclassified into the appropriate subdivision.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
