<HEADLINE> Ex-'Star Search' Comedian Convicted  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LINCOLN, Neb. (AP) -- A former ''Star Search'' comedian accused
of several sexual assaults at college campuses throughout the
Midwest was found guilty Tuesday of the rape of a student here.
</P>
<P>
   Vinson Horace Champ, 38, of Los Angeles was found guilty of
raping a woman at Union College, a small Seventh-day Adventist
school in Lincoln, in February 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Sentencing was scheduled for June 6. Champ faces up to 50 years
in prison.
</P>
<P>
   His lawyer, Assistant Lancaster County Public Defender Shawn
Elliott, referred all questions to Lancaster County Attorney Gary
Lacy, who was not in his office Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
   Champ also has been charged or is a suspect in a series of
attacks at several other colleges.
</P>
<P>
   A booking agency in Chicago, Ario Professional Artists, booked
Champ on the college circuit. Champ, who once appeared on the
syndicated talent show, ''Star Search,'' also performed on cruise
lines.
</P>
<P>
   In the rapes, the attacker liked to spit on his victims, quizzed
them about their sex lives and asked them to pray for him.
</P>
<P>
   Champ already has pleaded no contest to raping a faculty member
at the University of Nebraska at Omaha about a month after the
Lincoln attack. Prosecutors in that case agreed to delay Champ's
sentencing until his case is resolved in Lincoln.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
