<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feds Break Up Fake Memorabilia Ring  </HEADLINE>
By BEN FOX, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO (AP) -- An investigation into fake sports and celebrity
memorabilia has resulted in charges against 20 people and the
seizure of thousands of baseballs, photos, T-shirts and other items
with forged autographs in five states, authorities said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Operation Bullpen investigation targeted a network of
forgers and distributors, as well as others who provided fake
authentication documents intended to persuade buyers the items were
legitimate, said Phillip Halpern, an assistant U.S. attorney.
</P>
<P>
   The forgery ring was based in Southern California but
authorities believe the merchandise was distributed nationwide and
beyond. Federal agents seized items, including 10,000 signed
baseballs, in California, New Jersey, Pennsylvania, Nevada and
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would imagine stuff from this ring is in every single state
in the country,'' Halpern said.
</P>
<P>
   Federal authorities planned to detail the investigation at a
news conference Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Merchandise included items with fake autographs from Albert
Einstein, Abraham Lincoln, Marilyn Monroe, Michael Jordan, Martin
Luther King Jr., Babe Ruth, Lou Gehrig, Mark McGwire and Tony
Gwynn.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the items, Halpern said, were almost comically fake,
including a baseball supposedly autographed by Mother Teresa.
</P>
<P>
   Sold on the open market as legitimate, the collectibles would be
worth about $10 million, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Both McGwire and Gwynn helped investigators identify fake
autographs, Halpern said.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation suggests the celebrity memorabilia industry is
rife with fraud, including merchandise sold at stores that appear
to be legitimate, said Halpern, who estimates that half or more of
the autographed items sold to the public are counterfeit.
</P>
<P>
   ''We seized what I firmly believe is just a fraction of what's
out there on the market,'' said Daniel Dzwilewski, assistant
special agent in charge of the FBI's San Diego division.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities began investigating the industry after receiving a
tip from Upper Deck Co. of Carlsbad, a trading card and memorabilia
firm.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI set up an office in Oceanside with an agent who posed as
a businessman who exported celebrity memorabilia to Pacific Rim
countries, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Those charged in the scheme include six members of a family in
Escondido. Angelo Marino, 67, and his son, Greg Marino, 38, forged
items while the others distributed and sold it, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The suspects face a variety of charges including forgery, mail
and wire fraud, racketeering, counterfeiting, and tax offenses, FBI
spokeswoman Jan Caldwell said. All 20 defendants are aware of the
charges and are expected to surrender to authorities, she added.
</P>
<P>
   Most of those charged live in San Diego, Los Angeles and Orange
counties, but arrests in other states are expected, authorities
said.
</P>
<P>
   At least 20 more people in several states will be charged in the
case within two months, Dzwilewski said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have dismantled a prolific group of forgers,'' Caldwell
said.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI and Internal Revenue Service executed more than 50
search warrants in the case and is storing thousands of items in a
10,000-square-foot warehouse in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Also seized as part of the investigation were a Ferrari and two
homes in San Diego County, Caldwell said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
