<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coldwell Banker Gets Games Rentals  </HEADLINE>
By PAUL FOY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Renting out an ordinary four-bedroom house
in the Salt Lake valley to Olympic visitors could bring homeowners
$800 a night during the 2002 Winter Games.
</P>
<P>
   But the official Olympic broker will charge a commission that
could be as high as 40 percent on home rentals.
</P>
<P>
   Coldwell Banker Premier Realty of Salt Lake City was chosen
Tuesday by the Salt Lake Organizing Committee as an official
manager for residential accommodations.
</P>
<P>
   The broker will help people who in August can start buying
tickets to the 2002 Games also arrange for accommodations in
private homes. SLOC will list Coldwell Banker on its Web site and
refer visitors to the broker.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Webber, president of Coldwell Banker Premier Realty, said
he will charge a ''small'' listing fee when he starts accepting
rental applications from private homeowners in a few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Webber said he hasn't set a commission on private rentals. But
SLOC president Mitt Romney said private management firms typically
charge a 40 percent commission on rentals in Park City, which has
an abundance of condominiums and second homes.
</P>
<P>
   Under the arrangement with Coldwell Banker, Webber said
homeowners will get to keep more than 50 percent. He would not
offer a more specific figure and said it will depend on the level
of service Coldwell Banker provides, such as maid service, for
private homes being rented out.
</P>
<P>
   SLOC, in turn, will take on licensing royalty on Coldwell
Banker's commissions.
</P>
<P>
   Terms of the deal were not disclosed, but SLOC collects a 15
percent royalty from licensed merchandise vendors.
</P>
<P>
   Olympic organizers already have booked 20,000 hotel rooms for
the world's media, Olympic and sports officials and for sponsors
and SLOC contractors, said John Sindelar, director of
accommodations for the Salt Lake Organizing Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Sindelar said another 12,000 hotel rooms are still available for
the games within a 2-hour drive of Salt Lake City. Some of those
hotels, however, are not booking rooms yet for the games.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, many condominium owners in Park City are holding out,
refusing so far to sign up with SLOC or property managers and
seeking deals on their own.
</P>
<P>
   SLOC has an agreement to market 85 percent of Park City's hotel
space, guaranteeing occupancy for the full 17 days of the winter
games. Those rooms have mostly been taken, but Park City has
two-thirds of its available rooms in condominiums.
</P>
<P>
   Condo owners may be put off by SLOC's 15 percent booking fee and
red tape. Any owner who teams up with SLOC must register the
agreement to the deed with the county recorder so visitors are
guaranteed their reservations even if the property changes hands.
</P>
<P>
   Sindelar said the going rate at private residences for the
Olympics is likely to average $200 a night per room.
</P>
<P>
   Coldwell Banker will market single rooms or entire houses for
rent. It will not guarantee homeowners who sign up with the broker
that they will actually find a paying tenant.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
