<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Seeks To Promote New Business  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS (AP) -- Prime Minister Lionel Jospin on Tuesday said the
creation of new companies must become less complicated, less
expensive and less insecure in France, a country where red tape and
hefty taxes have previously hobbled prospective entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at a conference on business creation, Jospin said his
Socialist-led government would simplify procedures for founding new
companies and set aside more money to help people with new business
ideas. He said an Internet portal would be created to help those
who want to set up new businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The French were beginning ''to rediscover little by little their
taste for risk,'' the prime minister said, adding that the state
must do more to lower registration fees for new firms.
</P>
<P>
   Business leaders have criticized the government for standing in
the way of entrepreneurs by burdening them with unnecessary
regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Jospin said the French government, state bank Caisse des Depots
et Consignations and the European Investment Bank will set up a new
$144 million investment fund to back up small, newly-created,
tech-heavy start-ups.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, newly appointed Finance Minister Laurent Fabius
acknowledged that an excessive number of laws and regulations makes
it difficult and costly for young entrepreneurs to set up their own
companies.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have to remove some of the brakes that too often prevent
those intending to start up new companies from actually doing so,''
Fabius told the conference.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, some 268,920 new companies were set up in France, up
0.9 percent from the previous year -- a modest improvement
considering the sharp jump in French economic growth rates. But,
with the exception of 1994, the number of companies being created
in France has been going down since the start of the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Fabius said French society should ''better value''
entrepreneurs. ''We must improve the image of the entrepreneur,''
he said, ''Failure is not a fault. After failure can come a
rebound, and a rebound with the benefit of experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Fabius said his own Finance Ministry will be the first to
contribute to a simplification of company start-up rules.
</P>
<P>
   Lionel Jospin will have to revitalize a first wave of reform,
initiated with his nomination as Prime Minister in 1997, but remain
discreet on subjects that strongly divide his left-wing majority,
such as stock-options, extension of shares for new company
creators.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-11-00 2140 </TRAILER>
