<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   
George Thiemeyer Hemmeter:
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONOLULU (AP) -- Prolific inventor George Thiemeyer Hemmeter died
Saturday. He was 94.
</P>
<P>
   Hemmeter was credited with coming up with the idea for the
newspaper vending machine in 1947. He also invented a food
dehydrator during World War II and a self-balancing washing machine
in 1950, among many other devices.
</P>
<P>
   Hemmeter was the father of prominent Hawaii developer Chris
Hemmeter.
William A. Leonard:
</P>
<P>
   CINCINNATI (AP) -- William A. Leonard, who helped bring 1960s
displays of artists Andy Warhol, Robert Rauschenberg and Jasper
Johns to the Contemporary Art Center as its director, died Saturday
of heart failure. He was 69.
</P>
<P>
   He was the museum's director from 1964 to 1971 and produced 60
exhibitions at the center and at other museums and galleries.
</P>
<P>
   After his tenure, the Contemporary Arts Center was acquitted of
misdemeanor obscenity charges in 1990 for exhibiting a display of
Robert Mapplethorpe photographs that included homoerotic pictures.
</P>
<P>
   He praised the Cincinnati Art Museum for its 1985 display of
Mark di Suvero's sculpture ''Atman'' composed of steel beams and a
swing hanging at its center, when others derided it as looking like
an A-frame for a teepee.
John Luter:
</P>
<P>
   HONOLULU (AP) -- John Luter, former chairman of the University of
Hawaii journalism department, died Saturday. He was 81.
</P>
<P>
   Luter joined the university in 1974 and helped create the
journalism department, which had operated as a program in the
English Department. He was chairman of the department until he
retired in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The program had 74 majors when he arrived, and 200 when he left.
</P>
<P>
   Luter began his journalism career at the San Antonio Light. He
was a reporter for the Washington Star, Time magazine and CBS News,
and was an associate editor at Newsweek. He also taught at the
Columbia University Graduate School of Journalism for 13 years.
</P>
<P>
   One of his most important accomplishments at the University of
Hawaii was his creation in 1981 of the Parvin Fellowships, which
annually brings groups of young journalists from the People's
Republic of China to study in Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   Luter also established the Carol Burnett Fund for Responsible
Journalism at the university. After Burnett won an initial $1.6
million lawsuit against the National Enquirer, Luter made the pitch
for the fund, which fosters the study, teaching and research of
professionalism and ethics in journalism.
Thurman Mitchell:
</P>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- The Rev. Thurman Mitchell, who left a
career as a television newsman to become a minister, died Sunday
after collapsing in his pulpit. He was 55.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell had worked as a reporter for KCTV, the city's CBS
affiliate, from 1982 until 1998.
</P>
<P>
   He became pastor of the church in 1994 after a split in the
church had left it without a pastor. While he was pastor, the
church grew from 17 members to more than 400.
Jack Scudder:
</P>
<P>
   NAMPA, Idaho (AP) -- Jack Scudder, who was the editor of the
Idaho Free Press from 1955 to 1966, died Monday. He was 80.
</P>
<P>
   Scudder was known in the community for his service with the
Civic Center Auxiliary, where he was involved in the arts. He
served the volunteer group in various roles, including president.
</P>
<P>
   Scudder's wife, Josephine, said her husband chose journalism
because he wanted to leave the world a better place.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-11-00 2145 </TRAILER>
