<HEADLINE> Venezuela Vote Fairness in Doubt  </HEADLINE>
By JORGE RUEDA, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- Catholic Church leaders on Tuesday
expressed doubt about whether May's presidential elections in
Venezuela can be fair since President Hugo Chavez's political
movement hand-picked electoral authorities.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that election officials ''only represent one of the
candidates doesn't produce a sense of serenity, nor does it
guarantee the most basic impartiality needed in any popular
election,'' said Monsignor Baltazar Porras, the country's top
Catholic Church leader.
</P>
<P>
   Porras urged the country's National Election Council to make the
May 28 elections more transparent by including international
observers and allowing opposition members on the council.
</P>
<P>
   Etanislao Gonzalez, the electoral council's head, said Tuesday
that international observers, including representatives of the
World Bank, the United Nations and the Carter Center in Atlanta,
have been invited to oversee the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Porras's comments came amid growing concern in Venezuela over
the fairness of the upcoming elections, which are required by a new
constitution pushed through by Chavez last year calling for most
public offices, including the presidency, to be ''re-legitimized''
through new balloting.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez faces his most serious challenge from Fransisco Arias
Cardenas, a former army officer who helped Chavez stage a failed
1992 coup attempt, but who now accuses the president of abandoning
the original goals of their rebellion.
</P>
<P>
   Since taking office over a year ago, Chavez has transformed
Venezuelan politics, virtually erasing the traditional political
parties that ruled the South American nation during 40 years of
democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Ostensibly to avoid a power vacuum in a transition period before
May's elections, Chavez's leftist coalition hand-picked members of
an interim legislature, the Supreme Tribunal and the National
Electoral Council.
</P>
<P>
   ''We recognize there are imperfections in the transition of
power, but you must have faith in the honor of the council's
members,'' said Luis Miquilena, the pro-Chavez head of the interim
legislature.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
