<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Tourist Disappears From Cruise  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PAPEETE, Tahiti (AP) -- An American tourist has disappeared from
the cruise liner he was traveling on in French Polynesia.
</P>
<P>
   Police identified the man Tuesday as Cris Allen Swartzbaugh. One
of his brothers, Scott Swartzbaugh, said Cris, 39, was an Iowa
native but currently lives in Tea, S.D.
</P>
<P>
   They said he was seen boarding the ''Paul Gauguin'' liner on
April 8. His disappearance was noted the following day when the
liner arrived in Raiatea, an island 125 miles northwest of Tahiti.
</P>
<P>
   The liner takes tourists on a six-day trip from Papeete to the
Sous-le-Vent archipelago every week. Investigators believe
Swartzbaugh disappeared somewhere between Tahiti and Raiatea.
</P>
<P>
   Police said the liner had been thoroughly searched. A plane and
Puma helicopter from the naval aviation forces flew over the route
taken by the ''Paul Gauguin'' but the search was called off on
Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Police were still investigating the disappearance.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're hoping that a fisherman might have found him, taking him
up on an island. There are miracles that happen,'' said Scott
Swartzbaugh, who lives next door to his brother. ''It's been a long
time for someone to be in the water. But if anyone can do it Cris
can.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
