<HEADLINE> Russian, Italian Cos. in Gas Deal  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- Russia's natural gas monopoly Gazprom and the
Italian energy company ENI on Tuesday signed a credit agreement
with Western banks for $1.1 billion to help finance the Blue Stream
gas pipeline from Russia to Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   The banks include Banca Commerciale Italiana, Mediocredito
Centrale and West Deutsche Landesbank Girozentrale.
</P>
<P>
   ENI's and Gazprom's joint venture Blue Stream Pipeline Company
will use the money to build the offshore section of the pipeline
crossing the Black Sea, and to procure Italian pipes and equipment
to build the overland section of the project.
</P>
<P>
   Gazprom said the long-term credit will be guaranteed by Italy's
export credit agency SACE, but didn't disclose the terms of the
loan. The cost of the entire project is estimated at $3.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Gazprom is due to start gas exports through the pipeline in
mid-2001, with the planned annual capacity set at 565 billion cubic
feet.
</P>
<P>
   Russia expects to earn billions of dollars from gas exports
through the 750-mile pipeline, 250 miles of which will be built on
the bed of the Black Sea.
</P>
</TEXT>
