<HEADLINE> Capital All-Stars Beat US All-Stars  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Michael Sweetney, a 6-9 center from Oxon Hill
(Md.) High headed for crosstown Georgetown University, wasn't fazed
Tuesday night by the presence of U.S. All-Star center Neil
Fingleton, a 7-6, 310-pounder headed for North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Neither were teammates Bernard Robinson and Tamir Goodman, named
co-Most Valuable Players for leading the Capital All-Stars to a
112-101 upset of the U.S. All-Stars in the 27th Reebok Capital
Classic at MCI Center.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Julius Page gave the U.S. All-Stars a 9-6 lead on a
3-pointer with 8:23 remaining in the first quarter, Fingleton had
blocked three shots and altered several more. He finished the
period with 4 blocks, 4 rebounds, 2 points and 2 assists in 6
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   With 5 minutes remaining, the Capital All-Stars went on a 10-0
run capped by David Hawkins' slam and kiss off the glass for a
101-96 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Kyle Cuffe pulled the U.S. Stars to 103-97 with a free throw,
but Sweetney answered with a slam and a 3-point play to seal the
locals' second consecutive victory in the Capital Classic after
losing five in a row.
</P>
</TEXT>
