<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Rise  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- The Tokyo stock market's main index rose Wednesday
after Japan's central bank reported an improvement in the nation's
economy. The dollar fell against the yen.
</P>
<P>
   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, which was down
some 85 points early in the session, gained 89.53 points, or 0.44
percent, to 20,612.05 at the end of the morning session. On
Tuesday, the average closed down 96.54 points, or 0.47 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar bought 106.59 yen in late morning trading, down 0.37
yen from late Tuesday in Tokyo and also below its late New York
level of 107.09 yen.
</P>
<P>
   On the stock market, the Nikkei index initially was lower with
technology issues losing ground following a drop by their U.S.
counterparts in New York, where the Nasdaq composite index fell
132.30 to close at 4,055.90 on Tuesday. The Dow Jones industrial
average gained 100.52 to 11,287.08.
</P>
<P>
   But the Nikkei moved into positive territory toward the morning
closing bell after the Bank of Japan said in a monthly report that
economic recovery has started in some areas of private demand, as
seen in a gradual upturn in business fixed investment.
</P>
<P>
   The assessment represents an upgrade in the bank's view of the
country's economy, which is struggling to emerge from its worst
downturn in 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the
first section shed 5.00 points, or 0.29 percent, to 1,696.09. The
TOPIX closed down 15.65 points, or 0.92 percent, the day before.
</P>
<P>
   In currency dealings, there was some yen-selling in the morning,
but trades remained largely stuck in a narrow range ahead of a
weekend meeting of finance officials from major industrialized
nations.
</P>
<P>
   Finance Ministers and central bankers from the G-7 -- the United
States, Britain, France, Italy, Germany, Canada and Japan -- will
gather in Washington to discuss currency and other global financial
issues.
</P>
<P>
   In other currencies, the euro was traded at 102.32 yen, down
from 102.98 yen late Tuesday in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond rose
to 1.7500 percent at late morning from Tuesday's finish of 1.7450
percent. Its price fell 0.04 point to 101.29.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
