<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-11 23:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> L.A. School Districts Break Up  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The school board voted unanimously Tuesday to
break up the sprawling Los Angeles Unified School District into 11
mini-districts, with each having its own superintendent.
</P>
<P>
   The reorganization of the nation's second largest school
district was proposed by interim Superintendent Ramon C. Cortines.
Its goals are to give schools better access to resources; to
improve communication between parents and teachers and to focus
attention on student achievement, especially reading.
</P>
<P>
   ''Student achievement is the only reason to reorganize,'' said
school board President Genethia Hudley Hayes. ''We've failed every
sector of our youngsters.''
</P>
<P>
   The district has been under fire for low student test scores and
poor management that led to the Belmont Learning Center scandal.
The nation's costliest high school sits abandoned and half-finished
on an old oil field that was found to be leaking toxic gases.
</P>
<P>
   Cortines took over the district in January and will serve as
interim superintendent through June. A nationwide search is
underway for the new general superintendent, who will oversee the
superintendents of the mini-districts.
</P>
<P>
   Officials expect the plan to be implemented by July, when the
new school year begins.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-11-00 2351 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
